<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0754 11-14 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0754,0791</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Rosenthal, Hansell and Nickerson; Separates moved for AMs
on Dorati as a0714, Vejvoda as a0582 and Wada as a0567. Hazelhurst
also moved on the sports wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Antal Dorati</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Antal Dorati, the noted Hungarian-born
composer and conductor, died Sunday. He was 82.
   Dorati was music director of the Ballet Russe de Monte Carlo from
1933 to 1939 and his conducting posts included Budapest's Royal
Opera and the Ballet Theater of New York. He was principal conductor
of the British Broadcasting Corp. Symphony Orchestra from 1962 to
1966 and of the Stockholm Philharmonic from 1966-74.
   Dorati was music director of the Washington National Symphony
Orchestra from 1970 to 1977, principal conductor of Britain's Royal
Philharmonic Orchestra from 1975-78, and remained as conductor
laureate thereafter. He was music director of the Detroit Symphony
from 1977 to 1981.
   Dorati made more than 500 symphonic recordings and won 29 Grand
Prix du Disque among many recording awards. His compositions
included chamber music, concertos and suites for strings and oboe,
and a symphonic song cycle called ``The Voices.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Jaromir Vejvoda</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaromir Vejvoda, composer of the
``Beer Barrel'' polka, died Sunday at the age of 86.
   The song, sometimes known as ``Roll Out the Barrel'' was a
favorite among soldiers in World War II, including Gen. Dwight
Eisenhower. The tune, written in 1927 for Vejvoda's own band, was
known in Czech as ``Skoda Lasky'' or ``Love in Vain.''It also was
popular in German-speaking countries under the title ``Rosamunde.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Robert Hazelhurst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert G. Hazelhurst, 64, a former professional
football player with the old All-America football Conference in the
late 1940s, died Friday.
   Hazelhurst was a triple-threat halfback for the University of
Denver in 1947. He played in the East-West Shrine Bowl and Hula Bowl
games in 1948, his senior year. Hazelhurst then played
professionally for the Boston Bulldogs.
   After a shoulder injury ended his football career, he became
president and general manager of the Denver Livestock Exchange. He
also served as a director for the National Western Stock Show.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Junichi Wada</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Junichi Wada, president of Japan's leading sports
newspaper, the Sports Nippon, died Monday of lung disease at age 80.
   Wada also was an executive of the leading daily, Mainichi
Shimbun. He joined Mainichi in 1932, upon graduating from Meiji
University.
   In 1975, Wada became president of the Sports Nippon after serving
as head of research in the Mainichi Shimbun business department. He
also was head of the Daimai Orions, a professional baseball team
that has become the Lotte Orions.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Stuart Rosenthal</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stuart Rosenthal, 41, a doctor who became a
film critic and entertainment reporter, died Monday after suffering
chest pains.
   Rosenthal started at KATU on a 90-minute Sunday morning program
and branched out to other regular programs such as ``AM Northwest''
and ``Two at Four.'' He also contributed regularly to the weekday
program ``Faces and Places,'' mostly celebrity interviews done on
frequent weekend trips to New York and Los Angeles.
   Rosenthal also wrote about film for the St. Louis Post-Dispatch
and the Kansas City Star, and recently had a story about a Burt
Reynolds film published in The New York Times. He also wrote for the
new-defunct British film magazine Focus on Film and for the last
eight years, for the USA section of International Film Guide.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Haywood Hansell</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Haywood S. Hansell, a retired
major general who commanded bomber units that attacked both Germany
and Japan during World War II, died Monday. He was 85.
   Hansell was trained as a fighter pilot and became a member of the
Air Corps Aerobatic and Demonstration Team. He was commanding
general of the Third Bombardment Wing of the Eighth Air Force and
later was commanding general of the 21st Bomber Command, 20th Air
Force, in Saipan and Guam.
   Following his retirement in 1946, he wrote two books on the war,
``The Air Plan That Defeated Hitler'' and ``The Strategic Air War
Against Germany and Japan.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>James Nickerson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUNCIE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James A. Nickerson, 61, a former newscaster
and most recently radio-TV news coordinator for Ball State
University Public Information Services, was killed Sunday in a
traffic accident.
   Nickerson worked at WLBC radio and WLBC-TV from 1956 until 1970,
when he accepted the Ball State post. He had been vice president and
news director for the WLBC stations.
   Before coming to Muncie, Nickerson was news director of radio
station WKAM in Goshen and an announcer with station KREO in Indio,
Calif.
</TEXT>
