<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 2342EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Kohl-Wiesenthal     11-14 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kohl-Wiesenthal,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Chancellor Honors Nazi Hunter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl honored Simon
Wiesenthal at the Nazi hunter's 80th birthday party Monday and
warned against minimizing Nazi crimes through comparison with other
killings.
   ``We Germans have to live with the terrible fact that under the
National Socialist (Nazi) tyranny untold suffering was inflicted on
the Jews in particular,'' Kohl said.
   He called the crimes ``a genocide without any example.''
   Kohl said that there were attempts to compare Nazi crimes with
the suffering of other people persecuted for political convictions
or religious faith.
   ``Yet anyone who uses this line of argument overlooks or denies
that the hatred for the Jews was deeper: the mere fact that someone
was of Jewish descent constituted a capital crime,'' Kohl said.
   ``Our century is not only marked by economic, social, scientific
and technologial change that was scarcely conceivable beforehand, it
will also enter history as an era in which war and genocide brought
forth new unimaginable atrocities,'' Kohl said.
   ``There is a collective guilt. ... There is a common
responsibility for ensuring that history does not repeat itself,''
he said.
   Wiesenthal thanked Kohl for his friendship and ``appreciation of
my work.''
   ``Your presence here tonight is proof of your willingness to
honor all those who did not live to see the day of liberation from
the Nazi rule,'' Wiesenthal said.
   ``You definitely do not belong to that group that simply wants to
put history behind them, on the contrary, you have always spoken
about the responsibility for everything that was committed in the
name of the Germans,'' he said.
</TEXT>
