<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     11-14 0955</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0996</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine first lady Imelda Marcos said
her recent arraignment in New York on racketeering charges was like
a crucifixion.
   ``It was worse than Gethsemane,'' she told People magazine in the
Nov. 21 edition. ``It was like being on the cross.''
   She said demonstrators in New York inflicted pinpricks on her and
other members of her entourage.
   ``I didn't feel it until much later,'' she said.
   Deposed Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos and his wife are
accused of plundering $103 million in Philippine government funds in
a fraudulent scheme to buy New York real estate. They could face 20
years in prison if convicted.
   ``It's made me very human,'' Mrs. Marcos said of the couple's
exile in Hawaii, where they have lived since fleeing the Philippines
in 1986.
   ``Before, I was Imelda, the first lady. Now I am Imelda the
deprived, the crucified. Suddenly now I am a human being.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Papandreou, the American-born
wife of Greece's socialist premier, said she will remain in Greece
even if her marriage ends.
   ``Of course I plan to stay in Greece, it's my home,'' she told a
meeting of the Women's Union of Greece aboard a cruise liner in the
port of Piraeus.
   Mrs. Papandreou, 64, has campaigned for women's rights and helped
establish the union, the country's biggest women's group, in 1976.
   She has made few public appearances since Premier Andreas
Papandreou, 69, made public several weeks ago his relationship with
a 34-year-old airline stewardess and announced he would divorce his
wife. The couple married in 1951 when Papandreou was an economics
professor in Michigan.
   ``As regards my personal life I think I have the strength to
conduct my own battle alone ... but for me the personal is
political,'' Mrs. Papandreou told reporters after Sunday's meeting.
   ``I'm not one of those people who believe that the private lives
of politicians are their own personal affair ... from the moment
that someone goes into public life he has to know that whatever he
does will be subject to research and criticism,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carol Channing and composer Jerry Herman sang
``Hello, David!'' as Broadway producer David Merrick was saluted as
the Man of the Year by the Juvenile Diabetes Foundation.
   Channing played the lead in Herman's ``Hello Dolly!,'' one of the
many hits produced by Merrick.
   The gala event Saturday at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel raised $1.5
million for the foundation, which is the principal provider of
non-government funds for diabetes research, said spokesman Sam Rudy.
   The 75-year-old Merrick, who has produced more than 80 shows on
Broadway, was saluted by such stars as Mary Martin and Georgia Brown
and the cast of ``42nd Street,'' tapped out a production number from
Merrick's latest hit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   B.B. King, honored for keeping the blues
alive in radio, capped a night of electrifying music with `` The
Thrill is Gone'' during the Ninth Annual Blues Awards.
   King, sporting his familiar guitar Lucille, was scheduled to
emcee Sunday's award show at the Peabody Hotel, but a late flight
delayed his arrival and made him the closing act.
   ``All of my life living here in Memphis I've never seen so many
talented people in one place at one time,'' King said.
   Anson Funderburgh & the Rockets with Sam Myers were the big
winners, grabbing honors as Blues Band of the Year, Contemporary
Blues Album of the Year for ``Sins'' and Song of the Year for
``Changing Neighborhoods.'' Myers was chosen as Instrumentalist of
the Year.
   All performers received a Handy Award, a golden statuette in the
likeness of W.C. Handy, father of the blues.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's great decathlon champions
of the past gathered to honor Rafer Johnson, the 1960 Olympic
decathlon gold medalist, for his work with the mentally disabled in
the California Special Olympics.
   Johnson, who helped launch the California organization in 1968
and now serves as its president, received the Spirit of Friendship
Award at a gala Saturday night that raised more than $500,000.
   On hand to pay tribute to Johnson were Bob Mathias, gold medalist
in the 1948 and 1952 Games; Milt Campbell, who beat Johnson for the
gold in 1956; Bill Toomey, who won the decathlon in Mexico City in
1968; and Bruce Jenner, gold medalist at the 1976 Games in Montreal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newlyweds Herb Ross and Lee Radziwill
are asking $5.6 million for his five-bedroom, eight-bath mansion
overlooking the Riviera Country Club.
   The couple plans to move to their ranch in Santa Ynez, about 110
miles northwest of Los Angeles.
   Ross, the director of ``Funny Girl,'' ``The Sunshine Boys'' and
``Steel Magnolias,'' and Radziwill, the sister of Jacqueline Kennedy
Onassis, married two months ago.
   Ross built the house in 1981 for his previous wife, Nora Kaye, a
prima ballerina in the 1940s and 1950s. She died in 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A local arts center plans to establish an
annual award for classical singers in honor of Marian Anderson, the
first major black artist signed by the Metropolitan Opera.
   Soprano Jessye Norman and violinist Isaac Stern will present a
benefit concert next Aug. 12 to raise some of the $500,000 needed
for the award. The benefit will mark the 50th anniversary of a
concert given by Miss Anderson on the steps of the Lincoln Memorial
in Washington, D.C.
   The Charles Ives Center for the Arts will administer the award
for singers of achievement and potential, which is intended to be a
cash prize and a performance at the center.
   Anderson, who retired in 1965, has lived in Danbury since 1945.
</TEXT>
