<DOCNO> AP881114-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 0343EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     11-14 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Against Yen, Share Prices Up Marginally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell today against the Japanese yen,
while share prices edged up on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 123.00 yen, its lowest point since Jan. 4
when it finished at 121.65 yen, off 0.70 yen from Friday's close of
123.70 yen. The currency opened at 122.55 yen, also the lowest since
Jan. 4, and ranged from 122.50 to 123.10 yen.
   After dropping sharply, the U.S. currency recovered slightly
toward the end of trading because of dollar-buying by the Bank of
Japan and by speculators, said Yukuo Takahashi, vice president of
Chemical Bank.
   He said the dollar's fall was due mainly to investors' pessimism
about the United States' ability to reduce its trade deficit.
   ``The next president has been elected, but many (investors) doubt
if he has a potential remedy to reduce the deficit,'' Takahashi said.
   But he added the dollar was not likely to decline much further
ahead of the release of U.S. trade figures for September, which is
due Wednesday.
   Takamasa Yamasaki of Daiwa Bank attributed the dollar's decline
to speculative dollar-selling.
   ``Market players are likely to buy the dollar only when the Bank
of Japan intervenes, but their dollar-selling trend is so strong
otherwise,'' he said.
   The central bank was reported to have bought dollars shortly
after the market opened. The bank does not publicly comment on its
activities, but Bank of Japan Gov. Satoshi Sumita said it was
willing to take concerted measures with other nations to prevent the
U.S. currency from falling further.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa also said the foreign exchange
rate needs to be watched closely, and there would be aggressive
intervention if the rate becomes un stable.
   Meanwhile, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which reached a
record high 28,489.57 points Friday, added another 31.33 points, or
0.11 percent, to close at 28,520.90. The index lost 83.01 points in
early trading but gradually recovered.
   ``This proves the Tokyo market is stable,'' said a trader with a
major securities firm, speaking anonymously. He said trading was
thin due to uncertainty in the foreign exchange market.
   A Nomura Securities' analyst also said many market players were
in a wait-and-see mood ahead of the release of the September trade
figures.
   Financial issues attracted participants in thin trading with
first section volume estimated at 550 million shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
