<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     11-14 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20 Killed In Rebel Ambush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Tamil separatists today
ambushed a private passenger bus in northeastern Sri Lanka, killing
at least 20 men, women and children, police and military sources
said. Three were reported wounded.
   A military spokesman said the massacre occurred at 8 a.m. near
Pinkatiya, 146 miles northeast of Colombo. The victims were all
believed to be Sinhalese, police said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   According to police in Colombo, a group of suspected Tamil
extremists surrounded the bus as it was traveling from Trincomalee
to Anuradhapura, a Sinhalese holy city. It was not known how many
passengers were aboard the bus.
   It was the first attack by Tamil rebels since the Oct. 9 massacre
of 47 people in a Sinhalese village in the war-torn region.
   The attack occurred as officials were preparing for Saturday's
election of a provincial council to take over administrative duties
in the newly merged northeastern district.
   The council is a key provision of an India-sponsored peace accord
aimed at granting limited autonomy in the district. The move is
aimed at ending five years of bloodshed by Tamil extremists
demanding a separate homeland.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
16 million people. They claim they are denied education, jobs and
land by the predominantly Buddhist Sinhalese, who comprise 75
percent of the population and control the govearnment and the army.
   The liberation Tigers of Tamil Ealam, the most militant of the
Tamil separatist groups, opposes the peace accord saying that it
does not go far enough in meeting demands for self-rule.
   The Tigers have threatened to disrupt Saturday's election.
</TEXT>
