<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 0359EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PresidentialTrees 1stLd-Writethru a0445 11-14 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Trees, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Genealogist Says Bush, Quayle Distantly Related to Each Other,
Lincoln</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Theodore Roosevelt to Republican in 7th graf, `Bush,
he ....'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush and Vice
President-elect Dan Quayle may be more than just running mates. A
genealogist who specializes in the lineage of presidents says Bush
and Quayle are 10th cousins once removed.
   The two are also related to Abraham Lincoln, and the man thought
to be Marilyn Monroe's father, said Gary Boyd Roberts, a genealogist
at the New England Historic Genealogical Society in Boston.
   Bush, a Yankee, and Quayle, from a wealthy Indiana newspaper
publishing family, both have 17th century roots in New England,
Roberts said.
   Roberts has spent almost a decade researching Bush's ancestry,
which will be included in his upcoming book on presidential lineage,
timed to coincide with the 200th anniversary of George Washington's
inauguration April 30.
   Roberts is director of publications at the genealogical society,
the nation's oldest and second largest.
   ``Part of my mission is to show how one goes out from one's self
to one's family to the community and to various groups around the
nation,'' Roberts said. ``If you look at pedigree, you can tell
about patterns in culture.''
   Bush, he said, is only the third of what he calls ``Social
Register'' presidents. The first two, Republican Theodore Roosevelt
and Democrat Franklin Delano Roosevelt, who were distant cousins,
were closely connected to New York society.
   Both Bush and Quayle are WASPs _ white, Anglo-Saxon, Protestants
_ with a twist. They both have strong ancestral ties to the South as
well as New England, Roberts said.
   According to Roberts, Bush is distantly related to 10 American
presidents, including Franklin Pierce, the nearest relation (fifth
cousins four times removed); Lincoln; Ulysses S. Grant; Rutherford
B. Hayes; Grover Cleveland; William Howard Taft; Calvin Coolidge;
Franklin Roosevelt; Richard Nixon; and Gerald Ford, the most distant
relation (11th cousins once removed.)
   Bush also is descended from British royalty going as far back as
12th century King Henry I, the son of William the Conqueror, said
Roberts.
   Quayle ``almost certainly'' has some royal ancestry but Roberts
has not thoroughly researched his family tree. And he had ancestors
on the Mayflower, including Miles Standish and John Alden. Quayle's
father is a member of the Mayflower Society.
   But that honor, as Roberts explains it, is not uncommon. There
are an estimated 20 million to 30 million people descended from the
23 families who survived passage on the Mayflower, Roberts said.
   Bush's and Quayle's common ancestor was James Hamlin, who died in
Barnstable in 1690. Bush and Nixon, as well as former presidents
Hayes and Taft, are descended from Robert Foote, of Shalford, in the
English county of Essex, who died in 1608.
   Bush and Franklin Delano Roosevelt share an ancestor in Anne
Marbury, the noted religious reformer, heretic and a founder of
Rhode Island, who was killed by Indians on Long Island in 1643.
   Roberts discovered one of both Bush's and Quayle's more
celebrated relatives _ Marilyn Monroe _ through another genealogist
affiliated with the society, Richard Brenneman. Brenneman has
documentation to show that Bush and Quayle share a common ancestor
with Monroe's supposed father, Charles Stanley Gifford, who was born
in Rhode Island in 1888 and died in California in 1965.
   Most Monroe biographies cite Gifford as the man Monroe's mother
claimed was her father. Monroe's mother never married Gifford but
Monroe and Gifford made contact with each other over the years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 0458EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HardlinePalestinians     11-14 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hardline Palestinians,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Hardline Stance: Don't Give Up An Inch Of Land</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABLUS, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Graffiti spray-painted along a
hilly street in this West Bank city gave a message of intransigence
to the Palestinian leaders meeting in Algeria.
   ``It is disgraceful for a hand to shake hands with the one who
kills our own people,'' said the slogan, signed by a pro-Syrian PLO
faction.
   While many in the occupied territories are looking to the
Palestine National Council session in Algiers to declare Palestinian
independence on Tuesday, thus granting implicit recognition of
Israel's existence, a significant number strongly reject such a move.
   The slogan in Nablus was signed by the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, a Syrian-backed PLO faction long opposed to
softening the Palestinian refusal to recognize the reality of Israel
40 years after its founding.
   Already, other small Syrian-backed, leftist PLO factions such as
Saiqa, the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General
Command, and Fatah Uprising have declared a boycott of this week's
session of the Palestine council.
   Moslem fundamentalists, who command an even larger following than
the leftists, also object to any move toward recognizing Israel. In
a leaflet distributed in the occupied lands last week, the
fundamentalist group Hamas, or Zeal, called on the PLO not to
capitulate.
   ``We are against all the positions that are calling for the end
of armed struggle ... for peace with the murderers ... for
recognition of a Zionist state on even one inch of our land,'' it
said.
   Fundamentalists have repeatedly disputed the PLO-backed
leadership of the 11-month uprising against Israeli occupation of
the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The PLO, which includes the Palestinians' 20 percent Christian
minority as well as majority Moslems, wants Palestine to be a
secular nation, while fundamentalists demand an Islamic state.
   The differences were recently patched up, but the rift apparently
is reopening over the issue of recognizing Israel.
   The declaration of independence expected to be accepted by the
Palestine council is based on the United Nations' 1947 partition
plan calling for Arab and Jewish states side-by-side in Palestine,
or what has become Israel and the occupied territories.
   Moderate Palestinians argue this implies recognition of the
Jewish state and hope a council declaration based on the so-called
two-state solution would open the way for peace talks.
   But Moslem fundamentalists argue the PLO-dominated Palestine
National Council has no right to speak for all Palestinians.
   ``The PNC (Palestine council) does not take Islamic stands,''
said Ahmed, a lecturer at An-Najah University in Nablus who refused
to give his last name. ``I don't think the Islamic movement is
represented in the PNC.''
   Sheik Said Bilal, a fundamentalist leader in Nablus, said that
before adopting a declaration of independence, the Palestine council
should consult Islamic religious leaders throughout the world.
   He named a half-dozen such leaders in countries from Egypt to
Pakistan, which is not an Arab country.
   ``Palestine is an Islamic land and the entire Islamic nation
should decide whether the partition plan would be a good step,'' he
said.
   Other non-fundamentalist Palestinians see the disunity over the
issue as reason enough to hold off on any new stance toward Israel.
   Bassam Shakaa, the hardline ex-mayor of Nablus who lost his legs
in a car bomb set by Jewish underground members, said any
declaration of independence should have the backing not only of
Palestinians but of most Arab nations.
   ``Unless we first establish unity,'' he said, ``we will not get
more support for our struggle through this declaration.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
