<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 0524EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeamstersElection     11-14 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters Election,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters Local 560 Election Pits Old Guard Against Newcomers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD RICHISSIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNION CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle for control of the country's
largest Teamsters local and its 8,500 members pits the powerful and
corrupt former regime against its old enemies.
   Members of Local 560 will be voting in the first election since a
judge ruled the local was dominated by the mob and then deposed its
executive board in favor of a trustee.
   Michael Sciarra was removed as the local's president, and Joseph
Sheridan as vice president, in 1986 because of their alleged ties to
organized crime. Both deny any wrongdoing, but have been barred from
running for union office.
   It was the first time a union's leadership had been ousted by the
government for corruption.
   While some felt that helped pry the corruption-plagued local from
the grip of organized crime, others perceive one slate of candidates
as trying to wedge that influence back in.
   Danny Sciarra, Michael's brother, and Mark Sheridan, Joseph's
nephew, are on the Teamsters for Liberty ticket, running for
president and vice president, respectively.
   ``I think he killed himself at that nominating meeting,'' former
Teamster George D. Hansen said of Michael Sciarra, who nominated his
brother.
   ``Any talk that they weren't corrupt went down the drain when
(Danny) Sciarra and (Mark) Sheridan were nominated. That's exactly
what happens under mob rule. They're just trying to perpetuate it.''
   If Daniel Sciarra wins the race for president, it's because mob
influence still reigns, said Libero Marotta, a lawyer who advises
opposing candidate Ray Carney. A third slate is not running a
president.
   Carney was a friend of a rival union leader who was slain 27
years ago during a power struggle with former local president
Anthony ``Tony Pro'' Provenzano, who is in prison for racketeering
and murder convictions.
   Carney could not be reached for comment. Several messages left at
his campaign headquarters were not returned.
   ``With the (local) you have a history of outright bossism and
gangsterism. It's not a secret that Michael Sciarra was a part of
that. Who's naive enough to believe Danny Sciarra won't be?''
Marotta said.
   Ballots were to be mailed today to members and must be returned
by Dec. 6.
   Danny Sciarra admits he's running in place of his brother and
plans to let Michael in on some of the decision-making at the local.
But he adamantly denies either of them are involved with the mob,
and says Michael looked out only for the interests of the membership.
   Michael Sciarra said there was no intimidation when he was
president, and there will be none if his brother wins. He scoffed at
suggestions the membership wouldn't vote for Danny because of the
allegations against him.
   ``I think they'll vote for him all the more because of what's
happened to me,'' Michael Sciarra said.
   Ed Stier, the trustee who has worked to rid the local of
corruption, said he would not object if Danny Sciarra wins the
election, .
   ``My job isn't to try to call this election,'' Stier said. ``My
job is to create a democratic process in Local 560 by which the
membership has a chance to elect who they want.
   ``You can't overcome 25 or 30 years of dictatorship in a couple
years, but I think we've started that process.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
