<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     11-14 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SLIDELL, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donna Folse went to a lot of trouble to blow
a big pink bubble. And by the time the contest judge counted to 15,
she was wearing a smile and a blue ribbon.
   ``They tease me at work all the time because I chew gum,'' said
Ms. Folse, the only adult competing in a bubble gum-blowing contest.
``Now I've got a ribbon to show for it.''
   Meantime, her young rivals were peeling bubble gum from their
faces.
   Folse wasn't the only grownup acting like a kid Sunday as 3,000
people celebrated the 100th birthday of this Louisiana city.
Sunday's picnic was the last event in a yearlong centennial
celebration.
   Contests and games included hula-hoop twirling, red-bean
spitting, horseshoe pitching, cricket racing, and a tug of war
between the city administration and City Council.
   Even though the administration pulled to victory, one councilman
claimed his side won.
   ``We thought it was a rope push,'' said Lynn Barthelemy. ``So we
won.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless mutt is giving up a dog's
life by moving into the governor's mansion.
   Gov. James Thompson decided to keep a mixed-breed hound found
tied to the fence outside the the grounds of his Springfield
residence over the weekend, said spokesman Jim Bray.
   ``The governor fell in love with the dog immediately,'' Bray
said. ``He's a dog lover _ he's got two already.''
   Thompson named the dog ``Trooper'' in honor of the state police
guards who found him, Bray said.
   A note found with Trooper, who was very thin but otherwise in
good health, said: ``Please give pup a good home, we can't. We will
miss him dearly, please take care of him.''
   Thompson's other two dogs, an Irish setter named Gov and a cocker
spaniel named Mo, took an immediate liking to the new dog as well,
Bray said.
   Bray said Thompson was unconcerned that the dog might be a
political spy.
   ``It's not a Trojan horse ... I think the dog's too young to have
any political leanings,'' Bray said. ``I'm sure it'll be a fan of
the governor.''
</TEXT>
