<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     11-14 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Slightly Firmer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in European trading this morning
after the Bank of Japan reportedly intervened to prop it up in
earlier trading in Tokyo, foreign currency dealers said. Gold prices
rose slightly.
   Traders said that while the Bank of Japan bought only a small
amount of dollars at 122.50 yen, they were impressed with the
central bank's persistence in supporting the currency.
   The bank does not publicly comment on its activities, but its
governor, Satoshi Sumita, said it was willing to take concerted
measures with other nations to prevent the U.S. currency from
falling further.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa also was quoted as saying that
``agressive intervention'' will be used if exchange markets are
unstable.
   In the United States, aids to President-elect George Bush said
over the weekend that Bush has no interest in seeing a lower dollar.
As well, Nicholas Brady, who is expected to continue as treasury
secretary under Bush, said the United States remains committed to
exchange rate stability.
   The dollar rallied slightly near the end of Tokyo's trading day,
but closed at 123.00 yen, its lowest level since Jan. 4. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 123.70 yen.
   European traders said one factor adding caution to the market is
Wednesday's scheduled release of U.S. trade figures for September.
   August's trade gap was $12.18 billion and the market expects
September's to range from $9 billion to $11 billion.
   Dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday:
   _1.7465 West German marks, up from 1.7345
   _1.4660 Swiss francs, up from 1.4553
   _5.9680 French francs, up from 5.9285
   _1.9635 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9551
   _1,303.50 Italian lire, up from 1,296.50
   _1.2285 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2225
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8030, cheaper for buyers
than late Friday's $1.8137.
   London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price for
gold of $420.65 a troy ounce at midmorning, up from $419.95 bid late
Friday.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $420.25, up from $420.20 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 32 cents to close at a bid
$422.51.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.40 a troy ounce,
down from Friday's $6.45.
</TEXT>
