<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 0637EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-MansfieldRetires     11-14 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mansfield Retires,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador Mike Mansfield Announces Retirement At Age 85</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Mike Mansfield, a lean Montanan who
spent much of his lengthy political career promoting better
relations between the United States and Asia, announced today that
he is retiring at age 85.
   Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno reacted to the imminent departure of
Japan's much valued friend with ``deep regret,'' a ministry official
said. Mansfield said he would leave Tokyo before Jan. 1.
   Mansfield, a Democrat who set longevity records during his 16
years as U.S. Senate majority leader and in his 11 years as envoy to
the crucial Tokyo post, told a packed news conference at the
American Embassy that he and his wife Maureen had decided it was
time to retire.
   ``We decided it was time for me to resign subject to the will of
the president, and that has been done,'' Mansfield said.
   Mansfield said he delayed announcing his retirement plans until
after Congress had adjourned; until a resolution had been reached on
U.S. demands that Japan import American rice; and, most importantly,
until after last week's presidential election.
   Describing bilateral relations as ``excellent,'' Mansfield said
the situation between Japan and the United States was stable enough
that ``we can leave with our heads high and our arms swinging.''
   Mansfield's service to the United States started at 14 as an
under-age enlistee in the Navy for the duration of World War I. He
subsequently served with the Army, and later with the Marine Corps,
for whom he worked in Asia.
   Before Mansfield began the first of his five terms as a
representative from Montana's First District in 1942, he taught Far
Eastern and Latin American history at Montana State University.
   In 1944, Mansfield was sent on a foreign policy mission to China
at President Franklin D. Roosevelt's request. Prior to his Tokyo
appointment, he returned to China several times at the invitation of
the Beijing government.
   Mansfield's assignment to Tokyo in 1977 made many Japanese happy
because of his prestige in Congress and his long advocacy of East
Asia's great importance to the United States. The U.S.-Japan
relationship, he often said, is the most important to Washington _
``bar none.''
   It is ``our hope that we will work together in the next century,
which will be the century of the Pacific,'' Mansfield said today.
   Following Mansfield's announcement, Uno expressed appreciation
for the ambassador's efforts to improve relations between Tokyo and
Washington. ``It was truly fortunate that we had a person like
Ambassador Mansfield in Tokyo for a long time,'' ministry officials
quoted him as saying.
   Mansfield's calls for patience in dealing with the Japanese in
trade negotiations generated rumors, however, of splits in both the
State Department and the Tokyo Embassy into pro- and anti-Mansfield
camps. The latter argued he was too ``soft'' on Japan and had failed
to counsel firm stances on the trade issues that caused friction
between Washington and Tokyo.
   Mansfield argued in return that Japanese markets had opened in
many ways during his tenure and Japan has taken on a significant
portion of the security burden in Asia. He spoke out in favor of a
wide-ranging trade agreement with Japan, an idea that is unlikely to
materialize for years.
   ``What we ought to do is sit down, get away from this nickel and
diming way of conducting trade negotiations ... and face up to the
issue as a whole. Not the $60 billion deficit with Japan, but the
$170 billion deficit with the whole world,'' he said last year.
   In January, Mansfield had coronary bypass surgery, renewing
speculation he might retire, but he returned to the Tokyo Embassy
last spring.
   Washington's decision not to make an immediate attempt to force
the opening of the Japanese rice market, a position endorsed by
Mansfield, freed him to retire, convinced of ``the excellent
relationship that exists between our two countries at this time,''
he said today.
   He added he would leave Japan with regret after ``an exhilerating
experience.'' The years in Tokyo ``have been the most enjoyable in
our lives.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 0708EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SeattleFire     11-14 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seattle Fire,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ammonia Leaks From Fire At Refrigeration Building In Seattle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR J. ANASTOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ammonia gas seeped from a cold-storage building
during a blaze that sent three fightfighters to the hospital and
resulted in the evacuation of about 100 people from their homes,
officials said today.
   The multi-alarm fire was burning out of control early today at
the Rainier Cold Storage and Ice building, said Deputy Fire Chief
Steve Bailey. He said the building's walls are packed with sawdust
and the sawdust was smoldering.
   ``This is a fire we dreaded occurring and it occurred,'' Bailey
said. ``We could be here for days.''
   The back wall of the four-story, turn-of-the century building,
originally built by the Rainier Brewing Co., collapsed as flames
shot out its windows.
   The cause of the fire, which broke out Sunday night, had not been
determined, Bailey said.
   About 4,000 pounds of ammonia were in the lines that supply the
building's refrigeration, said Mike Roberts, Rainier vice president
of marketing and warehousing. The bottom floor was an ice plant, he
said.
   Roberts said 22-room structure contained about 13 million pounds
of fruits, vegetables, meats and seafood.
   The odor of ammonia was evident in the area near the blaze.
   ``Normally, it dissipates easily. We had a cloud on the ground
and at one time we had a cloud moving up, so it's hard to tell which
way it's going to go,'' he said.
   Ammonia in high enough concentrations can cause burns on the
throat and lungs and can be fatal.
   Three firefighters were taken to Harborview Medical Center. One
firefighter who inhaled ammonia was admitted in satisfactory
condition, said nursing supervisor Pamela Fanton. A firefighter with
a leg injury and another who suffered chest pains were released.
   About 10 blocks in the mostly industrial area were cordoned off,
said police Sgt. Gary Morrell. About 100 people were taken to an
emergency shelter at a nearby high school, said Hope Tuttle, Red
Cross director of public affair.
</TEXT>
