<2ND_LINE>PM-Bias Shooting,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Arrested In Staten Island Racial Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of black teen-agers shouting racial slurs
beat two white brothers a block from their home in a melee that left
one black wounded by gunfire, police said.
   Police on Sunday charged two black teen-agers in the brawl on
Staten Island, one of them accused of firing the shot that wounded
another black. Another youth was being sought.
   The attack was believed to be the second racial incident in the
borough in a little more than a month, police said. On Oct. 7, a
17-year-old black was struck and killed by a car after an encounter
with a group of whites.
   Daniel Marsac, 20, and Dean Marsac, 17, told police they were
attacked as they walked home early Sunday. One suffered a broken
nose and the other a black eye, said their father, Daniel G. Marsac.
   ``About 20 to 30 kids, all black, are slamming their fists into
their hands, saying `White boy, white boy,''' the younger Daniel
Marsac said.
   ``They grabbed me from behind by my jacket, about five of them,
and three of them jumped on my brother,'' he said. ``I was afraid of
knives _ but then I heard gunshots.''
   Police said at least three shots were fired, one of which hit
Lloyd Bryson, 17, in the side. He was listed in satisfactory
condition at St. Vincent's Medical Center.
   Nobert Jamel Grigger, 14, was charged as an adult with assault
and weapons possession, police Sgt. Raymond O'Donnell said. Michael
Boone, 16, was charged with assault and aggravated harassment of the
Marsac brothers, O'Donnell said.
</TEXT>
