<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 0921EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Koop-AIDS     11-14 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koop-AIDS,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surgeon General Talks About Minorities And AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Discrimination, language problems and poverty are
as much at the heart of the AIDS epidemic as drug abuse and
promiscuity, says U.S. Surgeon General C. Everett Koop.
   ``If you just look at the numbers in AIDS, the numbers that have
died, you're missing the whole story,'' Koop said Sunday at a news
conference before an address at a meeting of the Association of
American Medical Colleges.
   ``Minorities, poverty, discrimination, access to care ... all
these are part of the whole story.''
   He said the fight against the deadly disease has failed to convey
AIDS information effectively to blacks and Hispanics, who have been
stricken with AIDS in numbers disproportionate to their populations.
   Of the 77,994 AIDS cases reported since June 1981 in the United
States, 26 percent were among blacks and 15 percent among Hispanics.
Blacks make up about 14 percent of the overall population and
Hispanics make up 7 percent.
   Koop said higher rates of illiteracy in the black and Hispanic
communities may be part of the problem in conveying information
about the disease.
   A related problem is lack of access to health care among
minorities and groups at high risk for contracting AIDS, such as
prostitutes and intravenous drug users, he said.
   ``We have to make sure that they get it,'' Koop said. But often,
``they don't know where to get it ... and many times, the medical
profession doesn't feel comfortable treating them.''
   Koop said the government AIDS education campaign has employed
black and Hispanic public relations firms to reach those groups,
``so it's very difficult to understand where these black and
Hispanic groups are making their errors.''
</TEXT>
