<HEAD>Palestinian Guerrilla Squads Uncovered, 54 Arrested, Army Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with third day of curfews in
occupied territories, Shamir reax, other details. Edits to tighten.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>With PM-PLO
^By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army said today it arrested at least 54
Palestinian guerrillas in the West Bank while the PLO's
parliament-in-exile met in Algiers with the intention of declaring
an independent Palestine homeland.
   In the West Bank and Gaza Strip, Palestinian activists
distributed copies of an anthem for the would-be state entitled ``My
Homeland, My Homeland.''
   ``Palestine live free, live liberated from the enemy,'' said the
lyrics, which are from an old Palestinian song once used as an
Egyptian anthem.
   Most of the 650,000 residents of the Gaza Strip were kept under
curfew for a third day today as a deterrant to violence during the
four-day meeting in Algiers, Algeria of the Palestine National
Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile. The session opened Saturday.
   Curfews also were imposed in three West Bank villages, telephone
lines were cut to many areas in the occupied territories, and
Palestinians reported travel limitations and extra army patrols.
   The parliament-in-exile of the Palestine Liberation Organization
was expected to declare an independent Palestinian state in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip at its Tuesday session.
   Israel radio and army radio today reported the arrests of at
least 54 Palestinians who allegedly belonged to 16 guerrilla squads
and the destruction of several houses.
   ``This is a message to residents (of the occupied territories).
It clarifies that the army is there and continues to operate
efficiently,'' said a military official who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The radio reports said that in the West Bank villages of Jaba and
Jalbun, soldiers detained 33 Palestinians on suspicion of belonging
to guerrilla groups that set forest fires and prevented Arab workers
from traveling to jobs in Israel.
   In Tulkarem, the army detained three Arab youths suspected of
throwing a firebomb at a military patrol six weeks ago that wounded
one soldier. Their houses were demolished, army radio said.
   In Hebron, security forces detained a Palestinian suspected of
stabbing and wounding a Jewish youth in Jerusalem in May, Israel
radio said.
   In Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, the army arrested 17
members of a squad belonging to Moslem fundamentalist Hamas (Zeal)
movement on suspicion of planting a bomb near a Jewish settlement.
The bomb did not explode.
   In east Jerusalem, security forces uncovered a squad identified
as belonging to Fatah, Yasser Arafat's mainstream PLO group, the
radio reports said. Squad members were said to be suspected of
planting a bomb that exploded in September near the house of Trade
Minister Ariel Sharon, causing no damage or injuries, and of
planning an attack on a police station.
   Another squad, based in the Jerusalem neighborhoods of Anabta and
Abu-Tor, belonged to the radical fundamentalist Islamic Jihad
movement, Israel radio said, and was suspected of organizing riots.
   Also in east Jerusalem, security forces were said to have
uncovered a guerrilla group belonging to Naif Hawatmeh's Democratic
Front for the Liberation of Palestine. Its members were suspected of
organizing riots and staging firebomb attacks in March and August.
   On Sunday, Israeli officials denounced the Palestine National
Council's expected move to approve a U.N. Resolution 242, which
implicitly recognizes Israel's right to exist.
   ``We will not negotiate with the PLO. It's not a problem of
definition and formulations of various positions. We'll not
negotiate with them because they're opposed to peace with Israel,''
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said on Israel radio.
   In the West Bank town of Jenin, 43 miles north of Jerusalem,
troops killed a Palestinian on Sunday and another was wounded, said
an army spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The death of 27-year-old Alam Hamtouli raised to 311 the number
of Palestinians killed in the uprising against Israeli occupation of
the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which began Dec. 8. Eleven Israelis
also have died.
</TEXT>
