<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Shuttle     11-14 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Shuttle,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets To Make Second Shuttle Launch Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of spotlights illuminated the Soviet space
shuttle today as experts made final preparations for the second
attempt to launch the Buran, the Tass news agency said.
   The Soviet shuttle was scheduled to blast off on its first,
unmanned flight at 6 a.m. Moscow time Tuesday (10 p.m. tonight EST)
from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Soviet Central Asia.
   Workers labored overnight under nearly 700 spotlights to prepare
the Buran, meaning Snowstorm, the official Tass news agency said.
Liquid fuels were to be added to its giant booster rocket 14 hours
before the flight, Tass said.
   The Buran is to make two orbits on fully automatic control and
then return to a 2.7-mile-long concrete runway a few miles away from
the launch site.
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda today ran a front-page
picture of the shuttle attached to the rocket being transported to
the launch site.
   The first launch was scrubbed on Oct. 29, when an access arm did
not pull far enough away from the spaceship in the final minute
before blast-off.
   Computers automatically stopped the launch when the arm did not
retract.
   V. Filin, the deputy chief engineer for the booster rocket,
blamed the failure on ``overcomplicated construction'' of the joint
between the access tower and the spacecraft.
   Filin said an analysis showed it would take not three seconds to
fully retract the access arm, as had been expected, but 38 seconds.
   ``As a result of the analysis ... (access arm) became simpler but
more reliable, and that has been confirmed by experiments,'' Filin
said.
</TEXT>
