<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Czechoslovakia     11-14 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Czechoslovak Dissidents Freed After Independent Seminar Blocked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities today freed more than
20 dissidents arrested to prevent them from attending an independent
seminar, and the Communist Party denounced them for waging
``psychological warfare,'' sources said.
   Eighteen people arrested between Thursday and Sunday were
released before dawn, according to dissident sources in Prague,
reached by telephone from Vienna.
   At least a dozen Westerners arrived in Prague on Friday to take
part in ``Czechoslovakia 88,'' a seminar on the country's history
and future.
   Four others who had planned to attend were refused visas,
according to the Vienna-based International Helsinki Federation.
   Banned playwright Vaclav Havel, who eluded a police roundup of
dissidents Thursday and formally opened the seminar at a Prague
hotel, was detained Friday morning, the Prague sources said.
   Havel and his brother, Ivan, were also released today, said an
emigre source in Vienna.
   Three signatories of the Charter 77 human rights document were
held under house arrest over the weekend, the Vienna source said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In addition, seven other activists who tried to attend the
symposium were detained and interrogated over the weekend and
released, the source said.
   The Communist Party daily Rude Pravo said the dissidents tried to
use the planned symposium as a ``form of provocation, making use of
this for the cooperation of NATO countries for psychological
warfare.''
   The release of the dissidents came as Soviet Politburo member
Alexander N. Yakovlev arrived for talks with Communist Party leader
Milos Jakes, the official CTK news agency reported.
   Two weeks ago, Communist authorities used force to break up an
independent rally of 5,000 people and detained dozens of people.
   On Monday, the Rude Pravo daily branded the rally, called to mark
Czechoslovakia's 70th anniversary of independence, ``a provocative
action by anti-socialist forces.''
   In Vienna, the International Helsinki Federation for human rights
held a meeting on Sunday and today attended by Czechoslovak emigres,
including Jiri Pelikan, head of Czechoslovakia's state-run
television in 1968 during the popular reform movement that ended
with the Soviet-led invasion of Prague.
   Havel telephoned the Vienna seminar today, thanking the
participants for protesting the detentions this week, said a
participant, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
