<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1016EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Scotus-BeerPrices     11-14 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Beer Prices,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Agreeds to Hear Connecticut Case on Beer Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to judge the
constitutionality of a Connecticut law aimed at assuring that beer
sold in the state costs no more than it does in three neighboring
states.
   The court said it will review a ruling that the 1984 law
regulating beer prices unduly interfered with interstate commerce.
   The justices in 1983 voted 5-3 in striking down as
unconstitutional a similar Connecticut law.
   The earlier law prohibited brewers from selling its brand of beer
in Connecticut at a price higher than the lowest price which it sold
beer in New York, Massachusetts or Rhode Island. Under that law, the
controlling price was adjusted each month.
   The retail price of beer generally has been higher in Connecticut
than in its neighbor states, and many Connecticut consumers buy beer
in one of the three neighboring states.
   The earlier law was struck down because it was deemed to affect
the price of beer outside Connecticut by locking beer prices in all
four states for one-month periods to the level posted in Connecticut.
   The 1984 Connecticut law, however, stated that the posted
Connecticut beer prices only had to reflect the lowest prices being
offered ``at the time of the posting.''
   The law did not prevent brewers from lowering prices in the three
neighboring states ``at any time during the calendar month covered
by such posting.''
   Beer brewers immediately challenged the 1984 law but a federal
trial judge upheld it.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last June 13 reversed the
judge's ruling and struck down the law.
   ``The realities of beer price regulation in the border state area
show that Connecticut's statute inevitably exercises control over
the prices set for sales occurring wholly outside its territory,''
the appeals court ruled.
   ``Accordingly, we hold that the amended Connecticut beer price
affirmation provisions directly regulate interstate commerce in
violation of the Constitution,'' it added.
   The 2nd Circuit court's ruling was appealed by state officials
and in-state beer wholesalers.
   The cases are Healy vs. Beer Institute, 88-449, and Wine and
Spirits Wholesalers vs. Beer Institute, 88-513.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1016EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SkinheadsBeating     11-14 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Skinheads Beating,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beating Victim Dies In Apparent Racial Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police believe white supremacist
``skinheads'' beat to death an Ethiopian man with a baseball bat.
   Mulugeta Seraw, a 27-year-old African immigrant, was attacked
outside his apartment early Sunday and died eight hours later at
Emanuel Hospital & Health Center.
   Police spokesman Dave Simpson said Seraw and two friends from
Ethiopia were jumped by five people who drove up in a car as Seraw's
friends dropped him off at home. One of the friends was hospitalized
in fair condition.
   Police sought five suspected ``skinheads,'' a group committed to
the use of violence against blacks, Jews and minorities. The three
young men and two young women had close-cropped hair and
military-style jackets, Simpson said.
   Seraw, a bus driver, moved to the United States seven years ago
and attended Portland State University, a relative said.
   Three teen-agers were convicted earlier this year in the March 10
beating of a Chinese-Singaporean man and the harassment of his
family. The victim said the attackers shouted racial slurs as he
left a restaurant.
   At the time of the attack, there were thought to be 25 to 30
skinheads active in the Portland area, according to the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, which monitors the
activities of the radical right.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
