<DOCNO> AP881114-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1022EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Voting     11-14 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Voting,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Louisiana Ruling Affirmed; Law Applies to Judicial Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today let stand a ruling that
the federal Voting Rights Act, designed to prevent racial
discrimination, applies to state judicial elections.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by Louisiana
officials who said the law is not intended to cover the judicial
branch and could impair the independence of judges.
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled last February in
favor of blacks seeking to apply the voter rights law to the
election of Louisiana judges.
   The black registered voters said their voting power was diluted
unlawfully by a system in which two Louisiana Supreme Court justices
are elected at-large from a district comprised of four parishes.
   The state court has seven justices, five of whom are elected from
single-member districts. The remaining two are elected at large from
a district comprised of Orleans, St. Bernard, Plaquemines and
Jefferson parishes.
   Orleans Parish has a black population of 55 percent and accounts
for more than half the population of the four-parish judicial
district.
   The black voters filed a lawsuit to split the four parishes and
create two single-member districts, thus enhancing the chance that
Orleans Parish could elect a black justice to the state court.
   The blacks said the at-large system violates the Voting Rights
Act of 1965, which is designed to prevent dilution of black voting
strength.
   Louisiana officials argued that the law covers only
``representatives'' of the people, namely members of the legislative
and executive branches of government.
   The state officials, headed by Gov. Buddy Roemer, said:
   ``Judges should not be representatives. The larger the
constituency, the less parochial pressures can be brought to bear.
An advantage to at-large elections for judges is that judges can
make the difficult decisions without undue fear of dissatisfaction
in the electorate.''
   They added, ``Judges have but one constituency, the blindfolded
lady with scales, sword and shield.''
   But the 5th Circuit court said the Voting Rights Act is intended
to be a broad attack on racial discrimination in voting.
   ``Clearly, judges are candidates for public office,'' the appeals
court said. ``The act must be interpreted in a broad and
comprehensive manner in accordance with congressional intent to
combat racial discrimination of any kind in all voting practices and
procedures.''
   Judges are elected in most states. The Louisiana officials said
there are only eight states _ Delaware, Hawaii, Massachusetts, New
Hampshire, New Jersey, Rhode Island, Vermont and Virginia _ where
judges are appointed.
   The Reagan administration supported the 5th Circuit court's
interpretation of the voting rights law.
   ``The natural reading of the term `representatives' does not
exclude elected judges in the context of the Voting Rights Act,''
the Justice Department said.
   Eight states urged the Supreme Court to hear Louisiana's appeal
and decide the issue. They are Alabama, Arkansas, Florida, Georgia,
Illinois, Mississippi, North Carolina and Texas.
   The case is Roemer vs. Chisom, 88-327.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1026EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NotaryFraud     11-14 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Notary Fraud,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Notaries Bilking Hispanic Aliens, Commission Told</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of notaries are duping
immigrants into paying thousands of dollars for flawed immigration
papers by posing as legal advisers, a state commission has found.
   Most of Florida's 350,000 notaries are abiding by their duty as
official witnesses to legal transactions, but some are preying on
immigrants, especially Hispanics, who need help changing their
immigration status, said several members of the Governor's Study
Commission on Notaries Public.
   These notaries capitalize on the fact that the Spanish ``notario
publico'' refers in most Latin American countries to a high-ranking
public official, qualified and licensed to give legal advice, the
commission said.
   Although these notaries charge high prices for their work, they
often provide nothing but worthless sheets of paper easily spotted
by immigration officers who can have the immigrant deported,
commission members said.
   ``This is absolutely the worst kind of fraud on the public
because it's aimed at the people who are least able to fend for
themselves,'' said Robert Sondak, a commission member and Miami
lawyer.
</TEXT>
