<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthernAfrica-Talks     11-14 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Southern Africa-Talks,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South African Official Says Peace Talks `Glacial'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South African official today described as
``glacial'' the progress in talks between Cuba, Angola and South
Africa aimed at achieving peace in southwest Africa.
   The main issue of the negotiations is a timetable for the
withdrawal of an estimated 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola, where
they are backing the Marxist government against Western-supported
rebels.
   A seond issue is establishing a framework for the independence of
South-West Africa, also known as Namibia, which has been under South
African control for 73 years.
   One South African official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
described progress in the latest round as ``glacial. Things are on
track, but on a very slow track.''
   However, a senior U.S. delegation member said Sunday that
progress had been made on the issue of Cuban troop pullout.
   The American official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the negotiations have ``never been closer to agreement.''
   The three countries have agreed to hold an extra day of talks on
Tuesday.
   The U.S. official cited progress on the issue of a Cuban troop
withdrawal from Angola as one of the reasons to extend the
closed-door talks, which began Friday and had been scheduled to end
Sunday.
   ``If people can't go the extra mile, you could see a rapid change
of atmosphere,'' the American official said.
   The United States, which began mediating the negotiations in May,
proposed a plan in October that reportedly calls for a gradual
two-year withdrawal of Cuban troops. Cuba has sought a 2{-year
pullout timetable.
   South Africa has linked independence for South-West Africa, a
former German colony it took over after World War I, to a
satisfactory agreement on the Cuban withdrawal. It is ruling the
country in violation of a U.N. resolution demanding independence for
South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
   The target date for the start of the pullout was reported to be
Jan. 1, the same day on which a U.N.-supervised plan for bringing
independence to South-West Africa would begin.
</TEXT>
