<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Farming, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0470,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Calls Unusual Top-Level Meeting on Agriculture</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Gorbachev quotes, details. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev today
convened an unusual gathering of the Communist Party and
government's top officials and told them the country's farm problem
is the most critical one they face.
   The Tass news agency said Gorbachev addressed a gathering in the
industrial city of Orel, about 230 miles south of Moscow, that
included national party and government leaders, officials of the
state-run media and provincial Communist Party chiefs.
   The Soviet leader called the Soviet Union's food supply
difficulties ``the most important problem of the internal policy of
the Soviet Union,'' official Radio Moscow said.
   Although Gorbachev frequently goes on trips outside of Moscow to
push his reform effort, it was rare for him to call a large
gathering of top national and regional officials outside of the
Kremlin.
   The inclusion of media officials and regional party leaders
indicated the importance of the gathering. Among the Kremlin
officials who attended the gathering were Politburo member Yegor K.
Ligachev, formerly regarded as the No. 2 leader but shifted at the
end of September to the agriculture portfolio.
   Ligachev had not attended a mid-October meeting in the Central
Committee on agriculture.
   Gorbachev said improvements in the Orel region's agricultural
production in the past three years prove the value of his drive for
greater local control, Tass said.
   The improvements indicate ``much depends on the initiative, and
independence of local organs of power to rule and decide practical
problems of the agricultural sector,'' Tass quoted him as saying.
   The Communist Party's policy-making Central Committee will meet
in February to discuss plans to let families and other small groups
of farmers rent land from giant collective and state farms on
long-term leases, Gorbachev said.
   The lead article of the government newspaper Izvestia this
evening said the Orel region had increased its sales of meat by
one-third and milk by 17 percent in the past three years. It ran its
story under a headline ``Lease Contracts Return the Land to Its
Master.''
   Tass said the Orel conference will consider ``pressing issues''
of Gorbachev's reform effort, primarily what the Communist Party
must do to improve food supplies.
   ``The participants will familiarize themselves with the
experience of introducing new relations of production and economic
relations and expediting social progress in the countryside, which
has been gained in the Orel region,'' Tass said.
   Soviet farming is plagued by low productivity, frequent disregard
for the land and machinery, waste in shipping and storage, and few
cultural and social amenities in the countryside.
   Soviet food stores are frequently empty of anything but basic
goods.
   Gorbachev has said that improving the food supply is one of his
top priorities, and is pushing for a shift to lease contracts in
farming.
   Officials say such a system instills in farmers greater care for
the land and makes them more efficient than other farmers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
