<HEAD>Journalist Who Criticized Government Minister Is Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MASERU, Lesotho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested a newspaper editor today
after he published reports accusing Lesotho's finance minister of
improper dealings with an Italian company, his lawyers said.
   Police declined to comment on the arrest of Johnny Maseko, 29,
editor of The Mirror, an independent newspaper published weekly in
the tiny mountain kingdom of Lesotho.
   Maseko was charged two weeks ago with criminal defamation for a
series of articles published in September about Finance Minister
Evaristus Sekhonyana.
   Maseko appeared briefly in court on Friday but did not plead. He
was released on bail of $40.
   His articles said Sekhonyana in 1981 authorized the transfer of
millions of dollars into a Swiss bank account for an Italian
construction firm operating in Lesotho.
   The government subsequently accused the Italian firm, Banco, of
failing to complete building projects that had already been funded.
Company officials fled the country and the firm was liquidated.
   Lesotho is completely surrounded by South Africa. Its 1.6 million
people are ruled by a six-man military council that took power in a
1986 coup, ousting leftist Prime Minister Leabua Jonathan.
   Sekhonyana was the only government minister who kept his post
after the coup.
