<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd item to CORRECT spelling of Tanaka's name.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Takeo Miki</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Takeo Miki, who sought to
reform the governing party's economic policies after Prime Minister
Kakuei Tanaka resigned amid a financial scandal, died today at age
81.
   Miki served in Japan's House of Representatives for a record 51
consecutive years beginning in 1937, and as prime minister from 1974
to 1976.
   Miki, who studied at the University of California at Berkeley and
Japan's Meiji University, spoke against the possibility of war with
the United States in 1938, when militarists in the government tried
to suppress such sentiments.
   In the 1970s, as leader of a small faction in the governing
Liberal Democratic Party, he was a compromise choice for the
premiership after Tanaka's resignation in 1974.
