<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-DoubleJeopardy     11-14 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Double Jeopardy,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules in Arkansas Sentencing Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This is today's only Scotus decision</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court ruled 6-3 today that the
state of Arkansas can hold a second sentencing trial for a man
mistakenly sent to prison as a habitual offender.
   The court said a second trial would not violate the Fifth
Amendment's double jeopardy clause, which protects a defendant from
undergoing trial more than once for any single offense.
   In this case, Johnny Lee Nelson pleaded guilty in 1982 of
burglary and theft for taking $45 from a vending machine.
   A jury sentenced him to 20 years in prison after prosecutors
introduced evidence of four prior felony convictions. Four felony
convictions triggers Arkansas' habitual offender law, which allows
sentences of 20 years to 40 years compared to 5 years to 20 years
for non-habitual offenders.
   Unbeknownst to the prosecutor or defense, one of Nelson's
convictions had been pardoned. But it wasn't until more than three
years later, after a petition filed by Nelson from prison, that a
court-ordered review discovered the error.
   A lower federal court invalidated the habitual offender sentence,
and the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed the ruling, which
barred a retrial under the habitual offender law.
   The state appealed, seeking to have the sentence reinstated by
introducig evidence of another conviction not introduced at the
previous trial.
   The majority opinion, written by Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist, reversed the lower courts. Rehnquist said ``it has long
been settled'' that the double jeopardy clause does not prevent a
retrial when a defendant wins a reversal due to ``some error in the
proceedings leading to conviction.''
   ``Permitting retrial in this instance is not the sort of
government oppression at which the double jeopardy clause is aimed;
rather, it serves the interest of the defendant'' by affording him a
fair adjudication, Rehnquist said.
   He added, ``Our holding today thus merely recreates the situation
that would have been obtained if the trial court had excluded the
evidence of the conviction because of the showing of a pardon.''
   In a dissent, Justice Thurgood Marshall said a retrial is
``squarely foreclosed'' in the case. He noted that the high court
ruled in 1978 that states may not retry defendants when prosecutors
initially failed to present sufficient evidence of guilt.
   He said if the state had offered proof of three convictions and a
blank piece of paper to prove a fourth, ``no one would doubt that
Arkansas had produced insufficient evidence and that the double
jeopardy clause barred retrial.''
   Joining Rehnquist in the majority were Justices Byron R. White,
John Paul Stevens, Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Anthony
M. Kennedy. Marshall was joined by Justices William J. Brennan and
Harry A. Blackmun.
   The case is Lockhart vs. Nelson, 87-1277.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
