<2ND_LINE>PM-Bishops, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leader Says Bishops Won't Drop High-Profile Stands on National
Issues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 7 grafs with speech given, item withdrawn at
Vatican request, picking up in 5th graf pvs, `In recent;' deletes
penultimate graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT FURLOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Along with congratulations, the nation's Roman
Catholic bishops sent President-elect George Bush a reminder today
they will speak out firmly on national issues and not ``only in
praise and appreciation'' of White House policies.
   As their annual meeting got under way, the bishops also showed
frustration bordering on irritation on an intra-church matter, a
late intervention by the Vatican that will keep them from voting on
guidelines for resolving disputes with theologians.
   The Vatican action _ based on an objection that the guidelines
suggest equality between theologians and bishops _ ``might be
perceived as confrontational or as belittling the episcopal
conference (of bishops), which I know is not intended,'' said
Cardinal Joseph Bernardin of Chicago. He and other bishops said the
complaint should have come much earlier.
   The vote on the guidelines was put off until next June, but the
bishops will get another chance this week to publicly discuss their
not-always-harmonious relationship with the Vatican. A vote is
scheduled for Wednesday on a proposal concerning the authority of
bishops' conferences.
   At the beginning of today's opening session, the president of the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops, Archbishop John May of St.
Louis, declared they would stand with Pope John Paul II ``in
denouncing injustices and actions which foster disrespect for human
life, from abortion to the death penalty.''
   The reference is a pointed one since President-elect Bush
campaigned for the presidency as a vigorous defender of capital
punishment _ portraying rival Michael Dukakis as weak for taking the
other side _ as well as a foe of abortion.
   In recent years, several of the bishops' major statements have
stirred controversy outside as well as inside the church,
particularly as they took issue with Reagan administration policies
on nuclear arms, Latin America and the U.S. economy.
   ``We are sometimes criticized for being too concerned about the
world, of pursuing an agenda that in the minds of some critics is
secular, leftist or in some way `ideological,''' May said. But he
said actions and statements by the pope have shown the bishops it is
not possible to have ``too much social consciousness.''
   The bishops this week will consider a number of seemingly secular
proposals, including one calling on Congress to ease a 1986 law and
give legal standing to many more undocumented Hispanic workers.
   May indicated that if U.S. Catholics once kept quiet out of fear
they would be accused of disloyalty to their government, such
attitudes are gone.
   ``Catholics in America have long since passed the time when we
must prove ourselves to this country which we love,'' he said. ``Now
is the time to translate our teaching into action, to build a more
just nation and a more peaceful world.''
   May took a considerably more conciliatory stance on the main
intra-church matter the bishops will debate and vote on this week _
a proposal that they reject a draft Vatican document that appears to
undercut the theological authority of bishops' organizations such as
theirs.
   The bishops' proposed response uses such phrases as ``rigid and
confusing'' and ``overly defensive and negative'' to describe the
Vatican draft and says it seems to be ``pretending to be a study but
with its conclusions already determined.''
   Still, May said the bishops' response has been portrayed
incorrectly by the news media ``as if it signaled some sort of
struggle with the Holy See. With all due respect for the creative
imaginations of certain writers, this is simply false.''
   May said the bishops were simply responding to the Vatican's
invitation for comment.
   He said it is ``always a thankless office'' to give criticism,
even when asked. And he said, ``There has been no action by the body
this year that is more profoundly obediential and respectful than
the work on this document.''
   The pope has publicly supported the bishops' national pastoral
letters on nuclear arms and the U.S. economy. But there also has
been criticism from top officials in the Vatican, who ask for whom
the bishops were speaking, and on what authority. Other critics have
suggested the bishops were taking on issues that were none of their
business.
   But May said, ``Our people need to hear that the work we have
begun on `social issues' _ whether on nuclear policy, human rights
or advocacy for the unborn, the poor and the homeless _ will
continue.''
   Noting that the 300 or so bishops were meeting in the nation's
capital, May said it was appropriate to congratulate Bush and to
assure him ``of the bishops' continuing commitment to the
commonweal.''
   ``But our voices will not be heard only in praise and
appreciation,'' he said.
   Among specific issues this week, the bishops will:
   _Hear a report from a special committee drafting a statement on
AIDS. An earlier document drew fire from some bishops, partly
because it seemed to approve condoms as a way of preventing the
deadly disease.
   _Call for greater religious liberty in Eastern Europe, saying
that despite the emergence of Soviet ``glasnost,'' or openness,
``intimidation of religious dissenters continues.''
</TEXT>
