<HEAD>MacKay Seeks Recount in Senate Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT Mackay to MacKay in 3rd graf
pvs, `The recount ...; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `Attorneys for ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Rep. Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay, the
loser by a narrow margin to Republican Connie Mack in the race for
the U.S. Senate, has demanded a recount in five of the state's
biggest counties.
   The protest filed Sunday was accompanied by charts showing that
in the contested counties, a much larger percentage of people than
usual voted for president but cast no vote in the Senate race Nov. 8.
   The recount is being sought in Hillsborough, Dade, Broward,
Orange and Palm Beach counties, where MacKay contends about 170,000
votes were not reported. MacKay won all five counties but by smaller
margins than his staff anticipated.
   Attorneys for Mack said they will ask the canvassing boards in
the five counties to reject MacKay's request.
   Mack attorney Gregg Thomas said the drop-off in voters
participating in the Senate race could have been caused by the
position of the race on the ballot, people being turned off by the
``hotly contested race'' or confusion over the similarity in the
candidates' names.
   MacKay attorney Steve Uhlfelder said the congressman isn't yet
alleging fraud.
   Nearly complete but unofficial returns compiled by The Associated
Press show Mack with 2,044,575 votes and MacKay with 2,014,924.
   The Panama City News-Herald reported Sunday that Bay County, the
last county remaining, had completed counting absentee ballots,
giving Mack 2,048,356 votes to 2,016,828 votes for MacKay, a margin
of 31,528 for Mack.
   If the recounts disclose potential fraud or gross irregularities,
Uhlfelder said, MacKay has until 10 days after the election to file
a lawsuit contesting the vote.
   Mack campaign spokesman Mark Mills said further pursuit of a
recount by MacKay ``looks like sour grapes'' and could ``tarnish his
good reputation'' in the state.
</TEXT>
