<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Marshals-Drugs     11-14 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marshals-Drugs,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer-Aided Marshals Nab 218 Drug Fugitives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Marshals Service, with the aid of a
computerized tracking system, announced today it had hunted down and
arrested 218 drug fugitives in a 10-week operation that was so
successful it paid for itself with $1.3 million in seized cash and
property.
   The operation cost $1.1 million and was launched Aug. 27 when 105
deputy marshals were assigned full-time to special units.
   The 218 fugitives all are accused of various drug-related
offenses, including 84 alleged drug lab operators, drug financiers,
major suppliers or lead figures in drug organizations, said marshals
service director Stanley Morris.
   Morris said the operation, called Warrant Apprehension Narcotics
Team or WANT-II, is an attempt to ``add a bottom line'' to law
enforcement efforts targeting drug traffickers. The number of
federal drug fugitives grew by nearly 25 percent in the last two
years, with total outstanding warrants rising to more than 4,200.
   ``Intensified anti-drug activities by DEA, the FBI, the U.S.
Customs Service and other investigative agencies have led to an
increasing number of charges filed against drug traffickers,''
Morris said at a news conference. ``Consequently, the number of
narcotics fugitives _ those who avoid arrest or fail to appear in
court _ has increased significantly in the past few years.''
   A key to the project's success was a special computerized system
called ``Scorecard,'' a computer program capable of storing and
sorting through a vast quantity of data from fugitive case files to
develop investigative leads for the teams trying to locate the drug
figures.
   The leads developed through Scorecard were passed along to deputy
marshals and local police who checked out the information and made
the arrests.
   WANT-II operated from Galveston, Texas; New Orleans; Mobile,
Ala.; Jacksonville and Tampa, Fla., and Miami, with a headquarters
unit at El Paso, Texas.
   Seized during the operation was a $127,000 Ferrari Testarossa
from accused drug trafficker Nicholas Hunter-Reay, who was arrested
in Miami.
   Hunter-Reay, who vanished after his 1979 federal indictment in
California for alleged cocaine distribution, was living comfortably
under an assumed name in Delray Beach, Fla. He was a member of the
Broward County Sheriff's Advisory Council when he was arrested Sept.
15.
   Arrested Sept. 25 in the operation was Francisco Penaranda,
indicted in 1985 as the kingpin of an international drug trafficking
conspiracy that allegedly brought huge quantities of cocaine from
Colombia into the United States and Canada.
   Also caught up in the operation were Trepop Pidech and Hobart
Dunn, indicted for allegedly masterminding the laundering of nearly
$3 billion in profits from the Penaranda network.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1222EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-CharlesAt40 2ndLd-Writethru a0488 11-14 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Charles At 40, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0488,0754</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At 40, The Heir To The British Throne Has Carved Out His Niche</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Charles' comments, color.
Pick up 7th pvs, Later today. Minor editing to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wearing a button proclaiming ``Life
begins at 40,'' Prince Charles celebrated his 40th birthday today
with the inner-city young people whose cause he has championed
during his long wait to ascend the British throne.
   Obviously enjoying the daylong public celebrations, the prince
launched a nationwide appeal to raise $72 million for the Prince's
Youth Business Trust, which helps unemployed young people establish
their own businesses. The government has agreed to match donations
up to that level.
   To cheers and laughter, Charles delivered a parody of some of his
own more eccentric interests, particularly the notion that he
regularly consults the plants in his gardens.
   He said that before he came to Birmingham, ``an entire bed of
old-fashioned roses ... were forced to listen to my demented
ramblings on the meaning of the universe as I sat cross-legged in
the lotus position on the gravel paths in front of them.''
   Charles said the ``Life begins at 40'' button was a present from
his two young sons, Prince William, 6, and Prince Harry, 4.
   As he crosses into middle age, the heir to the British throne,
who has no constitutionally defined job, has carved his own role _
as crusader for the underprivileged and protector of the environment.
   On the eve of the prince's birthday, one of his close associates,
Tom Shebbeare, said Charles is irritated by the news media's
obsession with peddling what he called ``tittle-tattle'' and fiction
about Charles' private life, which he said distracts from the
prince's serious work.
   Hundreds of well-wishers cheered and sang ``Happy Birthday, Dear
Charlie'' when the heir to the British throne arrived in Birmingham.
   Later today, he was to attend a glittering Buckingham Palace ball.
   As Charles was en route to Birmingham, the Defense Ministry
awarded him the double promotion. The ranks are ceremonial; the
prince ended his active career with Britain's armed services in 1976.
   Charles chose the Prince's Trust _ which he established in 1976
to help disadvantaged youths find jobs _ to organize his public
birthday celebration in Birmingham, Britain's second-largest city.
   Shebbeare, director of the Prince's Trust, said in an interview
published Sunday in the Observer newspaper that the prince had
decided not to give an interview himself because he didn't want to
get involved ``in the hype'' surrounding his birthday.
   ``He is now pretty determined that he has departed on an
interesting and useful role as the Prince of Wales, and that his
interventions into areas of public life are things that he can do
usefully for the nation,'' Shebbeare was quoted as saying.
   After years of being picked on by the tabloid press, which has
accused him of everything from eccentricity to failing as a husband,
Charles has recently been lauded as ``charismatic'' and ``a great
communicator.''
   The new media appraisal followed a 70-minute television attack on
modern architectural development _ including central Birmingham,
which Charles said had been turned into a monstrous concrete maze in
which only cars could find their way. ``People didn't stand a
chance,'' he said.
   The prince has been expressing his views with greater
determination on other issues as well: the creation of jobs and
businesses, the building of homes that people would like to live in,
the protection of the environment, and a united Europe where
individual countries retain their own languages and culture.
   But there are other sides to the 21st Prince of Wales.
   There's the action man who loves polo and skiing, who plummetted
into the ocean in a tangled parachute, and who skied clear of an
avalanche that killed one of his best friends.
   There's the father who played at the seaside in the Spanish
resort of Majorca with his sons, and who took them to their first
fox hunt on Saturday _ enraging animal rights activists.
   There's the husband whose relationship with his wife, Diana _
repeatedly named one of the most beautiful and best-dressed women in
the world _ is chronicled daily in the tabloid press, regardless of
any factual basis.
   Charles' birthday ball was to be attended by 300 guests,
including members of the royal family and King Olav of Norway.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
