<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Italy-Strike,0141</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most Flights Canceled At North Italian Airports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National and international flights were
canceled at airports in northern Italy because of a 12-hour strike
by air traffic controllers Monday, but Tuesday's scheduled
nationwide strike was called off.
   The strike forced the cancellation of flights to and from Milan,
Turin, Genoa, Venice and Pisa.
   ``Only flights to the Italian islands were unaffected by the
walkout,'' said a spokesman for Milan's Linate airport. ``All other
flights were canceled.''
   The unions called off Tuesday's scheduled 13-hour nationwide
strike after reaching an accord with management.
   The agreement calls for more flexible work schedules and
promotion of 500 controllers to a higher pay category.
   The controllers agreed to suspend any labor unrest through Jan.
16 pending final acceptance of the agreement by the two sides.
</TEXT>
