<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Detainee Death,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three White Police Suspended After Death of Black Detainee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police suspended three white
officers Monday and ordered an investigation into the death of a
black man in custody.
   Oupie Mpete, 26, died Friday while in detention, one day after he
was arrested for a ``criminal offense'' in Reivilo in north-central
South Africa, said police Col. Vic Heyns.
   Heyns said Mpete was not held under the country's 29-month-old
state of emergency regulations, but declined to elaborate Mpete's
alleged offense.
   An estimated 30,000 people have been detained without charge for
varying periods of time under the emergency, and five are known to
have died in custody.
   Heyns did not release the names of the suspended officers.
   Many detainees have alleged that they were victims of police
assault and torture. Some have filed lawsuits against the police,
and on several occasions police have paid have paid out-of-court
settlements.
</TEXT>
