<DOCNO> AP881114-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1231EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w BC-Scotus-At-A-Glance     11-14 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus-At-A-Glance,430</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are highlights of Monday's Supreme Court
actions.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ABORTION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court, without comment, refused to give husbands the legal
power to prevent their wives from having abortions. The justices let
stand an Indiana Supreme Court decision that a husband has no right
to interfere with his wife's constitutional right to abort her
pregnancy. The state court's ruling last July was based directly on
past rulings by the nation's highest court.
   The case is Conn vs. Conn, 88-347.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MARCOS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court denied an emergency request from deposed Philippine
President Ferdinand Marcos and his wife, Imelda, that they not be
compelled to abide by a federal grand jury's request for financial
and other records related to an investigation of the couple. A
federal judge in New York ruled Aug. 11 that the Marcoses, who are
charged with looting their nation's treasury of more than $100
million, must honor the subpoenas and no longer have immunity as
ruler and first lady of a foreign country.
   The case is Marcos vs. U.S., A-361.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>VOTING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court let stand an appellate ruling that the federal Voting
Rights Act, designed to prevent racial discrimination, applies to
state judicial elections. Without comment, the justices rejected an
appeal by Louisiana officials who said the law is not intended to
cover the judicial branch and could impair the independent of judges.
   The case is Roemer vs. Chisom, 88-327.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DOUBLE JEOPARDY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court ruled that the state of Arkansas can hold a sentencing
trial for a man mistakenly sent to prison as a habitual offender. By
a 6-3 vote, the court said a second trial would not violate the
Fifth Amendment's double jeopardy clause, which protects a defendant
from undergoing trial more than once for any single offense.
   The case is Lockhart vs. Nelson, 87-1277.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BEER PRICES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court agreed to rule on the constitutionality of a
Connecticut law aimed at assuring that beer sold in the state costs
no more than it does in three neighboring states. The justices said
they will review a ruling that the 1984 law regulating beer prices
unduly interfered with interstate commerce. In 1983, the court voted
5-3 in striking down as unconstitutional a similar Connecticut law.
   The cases are Healy vs. Beer Institute, 88-449, and Wine and
Sprits Wholesalers vs. Beer Institute, 88-513.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TRUCKS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The court agreed to hear an appeal by trucking companies seeking
refunds from Arkansas of taxes they paid under a levy that was
declared unconstitutional. The court also agreed to study the refund
issue in a case from Florida involving taxes on alcoholic beverages.
   The case are McKesson Corp. vs. Division of Alcoholic Beverages
and American Truck Associations vs. Smith, 88-325.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0073 </DOCNO>
