<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeathAppeals     11-14 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Death Appeals,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cop-Killer Slated for Electric Chair Gets Stay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leo Alexander Jones received a stay of
execution this morning an hour before he was to die in the electric
chair for the 1981 ambush slaying of a young police officer.
   U.S. District Judge John H. Moore II in Jacksonville granted
Jones, 38, a hearing for Tuesday. The execution was rescheduled for
7:01 a.m. Wednesday.
   In Florida State Prison near Starke, Jones refused a last meal
this morning. Prison officials had not yet shaved his head or legs
where the electrodes were to be attached when news of the stay came
down at 11:10 a.m.
   ``This is unusual in my experience for a stay to be issued this
close to an execution,'' Bob Macmaster, a spokesman for the state
Department of Corrections. Jones was slated to die in the electric
chair at 12:01 p.m.
   Jones was condemned for the sniper slaying of Officer Thomas J.
Szafranski. The 28-year-old officer had gone to Jones' apartment
building to respond to a hostage situation and was shot in the head
while sitting in his squad car.
   Prosecutors said Jones had been arrested on a traffic violation a
week earlier and vowed to kill Szafranski.
   A total of 103 people have been put to death in the United States
since U.S. Supreme Court reinstated capital punishment in 1976.
Nineteen men have been executed in Florida, two this year.
</TEXT>
