<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1256EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GeographicAwards     11-14 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Geographic Awards,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Glenn, 14 Other Explorers Honored by Geographic Society</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former astronaut John Glenn and undersea
explorer Jacques-Yves Cousteau are among 15 recipients of $10,000
cash and crystal globes awarded by the National Geographic Society
on its 100th anniversary.
   Sir Edmund Hillary, the first man to reach the summit of Mount
Everest, and Robert D. Ballard, the Navy scientist who discovered
the sunken remains of the Titanic, also were among the pioneers
selected for society's ``Centennial Awards,'' which will be
presented Thursday.
   Other winners:
   _Bradford Washburn and Barbara Washburn for cartography and
mountaineering. The Washburns spent seven years creating a precise,
large-scale map of the Grand Canyon. Barbara Washburn was the first
women to reach the summit of Mount McKinley, North America's highest
peak.
   _Frank C. Craighead Jr. and John J. Craighead, biology and
ecology. The Craigheads were pioneers in the use of satellites for
radio tracking of animals and are known especially for their
research on grizzly bears.
   _Harold E. Edgerton, who developed the method of using strobe
lights to freeze action in pictures, allowing for the photography of
hummingbirds and other extraordinarily fast creatures and objects.
He also pioneered the underwater camera and side-scan sonar for
ocean research.
   _Thayer Soule, lecturer. Soule has shared his knowledge of the
world and its peoples with film and lectures since 1947.
   _Mary D. Leakey and Richard E. Leakey, for their research into
the beginnings of mankind. The Leakeys, from a first breakthrough in
1959, have made a series of discoveries of bones of ancestors of
modern humans.
   _George F. Bass, underwater archeologist, for his work in
increasing the understanding of the ancient world through
exploration of shipwrecks.
   _Jane Goodall, for her pioneering research of chimpanzees in
Tanzania, the longest continuous field research ever conducted on a
wild animal.
   _Kenan D. Ballard for a lifetime of work unearthing and restoring
the ancient classical Greek city of Aphrodisias, in present Turkey.
   Glenn, now a Democratic senator from Ohio, was the first American
to orbit the earth. Hillary was honored both for his famed climb of
Everest and his subsequent work in creating schools, hospitals and a
national park in the region.
   ``One mark of great individuals is their ability to look byond
areas of expertise to see the larger picture _ to understand the
problems facing us all and to do something about them,'' said the
society's president, Gilbert M. Grosvenor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1309EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bush-Environment     11-14 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Environment,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Environmetalists Say Bush Now Must Fulfill Campaign Promises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The environmental community, backed by polls
showing Americans want cleaner air, water and soil, is looking to
George Bush to put presidential substance behind his pro-environment
campaign pledges.
   ``Proclaiming himself an environmentalist is not enough,'' says
Robert SanGeorge, the National Audubon Society's vice president for
public affairs. ``Now is the time for action. He's got a lot to
prove.''
   Bush, declaring that ``I am an environmentalist,'' set himself a
broad environmental agenda during the campaign, promising action
against global warming, air and ocean pollution, toxic waste and
loss of wetlands.
   ``If he specifically proposes to Congress half of what he's
promised in the campaign, he'll have a hell of an environmental
record,'' says Gaylord Nelson, counselor to the Wilderness Society.
   Bush's statements represented a repudiation of many of the
policies that kept the Reagan administration and the
environment-conservation lobby fighting for eight years. His
campaign ads about the filthy waters of Boston harbor put
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis on the defensive.
   Both candidates ran as environmentalists, elevating the issue to
a higher level than in previous presidential races as they played to
an increasingly popular cause.
   A Gallup poll released two days before Bush's election said 65
percent of the respondents _ Republicans and Democrats _ said
``proposing laws to increase protection of the environment'' should
be the next president's top priority.
   ``The reason Bush got so many votes was because he did eliminate
some of the skepticism about his earlier environmental stands,''
said Nancy Light of the Sierra Club.
   She and other environmentalists said in interviews last week with
The Associated Press that the skepticism came from Bush's role early
in the Reagan years directing the effort to scrap federal
regulations, including some sacred to the environmental movement.
   Bush worked to overcome this by strong, although mainly
generalized, statements in favor of a better environment.
   ``In many ways Bush set up the expectation he's going to be the
best environmental president since Teddy Roosevelt,'' said Rick Hind
of U.S. Public Interest Research Group. ``But his past leaves us
puzzled as to whether he will live up to this expectation.''
   ``He made a lot of promises and commitments,'' said Dan Becker of
Environmental Action. ``It would be cynical for him to turn his back
on them.''
   They and others say the nation won't have to wait until Bush
assumes office Jan. 20 to get a sense of his environmental direction.
   ``The clearest indications will be the appointments he makes to
the key environmental posts,'' said Brent Blackwelder of the
Environmental Policy Institute.
   These jobs are the secretaries of the interior and energy and the
administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency.
   ``He needs to put in people who are not like the James Watt
wrecking crew,'' said David Baker of Friends of the Earth, referring
to President Reagan's first and highly controversial interior
secretary.
   Fred Krupp, executive director of the Environmental Defense Fund,
praised Bush's first Cabinet choice, James A. Baker III as secretary
of state. He said that as treasury secretary Baker was instrumental
in pushing international lending agencies to pay attention to the
environmental consequences of their Third World loans.
   Krupp sees the top job at the State Department as a post growing
in environmental importance because of worldwide problems such as
global warming. ``The greenhouse effect overrides all other
environmental problems. It is in a class with preventing nuclear
war.''
   Environmentalists ticked off a long list of items they say needs
leadership from the new administration: better toxic waste control;
protection of ground water; a strengthened Clean Air Act; a national
energy policy that puts conservation and safe, clean alternatives
ahead of petroleum and coal; cleaner oceans and rivers; better
management of public lands.
   Nelson, a former Democratic senator from Wisconsin, says what
Bush does about the environment could be the most important legacy
of his presidency.
   ``It could put him down in history as a great leader,'' Nelson
said.
   After its struggles with the Reagan administration, the
environmental community is taking a deep breath and looking ahead,
even if Bush wasn't the first choice of many of its leaders.
   After Ronald Reagan, said SanGeorge, ``it can't get any worse.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
