<DOCNO> AP881114-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Bush-Transition     11-14 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Transition,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transition Team Opens Washington Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The co-directors of George Bush's transition
opened the president-elect's office today, saying their boss had no
firm timetable for making appointments but the team would move
expeditiously.
   The men, Craig Fuller and Robert Teeter, would not confirm
speculation that Bush would act this week to keep Treasury Secretary
Nicholas F. Brady in the job he has held since August. Brady, a
former chairman of Dillon, Read & Co., is a long-time friend of Bush.
   But Teeter, a top strategist in the presidential campaign, said
Bush's economics team ``is one that he would want to pay attention
to.'' Other speculation has centered on Richard Darman as the new
budget director.
   Since Bush's election last Tuesday, the dollar has fallen against
the Japanese yen and the German mark, causing jitters on Wall
Street. Bush, who is vacationing in Florida, sought to minimize the
situation today. ``These gyrations happen,'' Bush said.
   Fuller, chief of staff in the vice president's office, said he
and Teeter had spent ``a great deal of time'' talking with each
other over the weekend and had also consulted with Bush by telephone.
   ``We're delighted to be coming to work,'' he said at a briefing
for reporters on the sidewalk outside the transition office about 12
blocks from the White House.
   Bush has no timetable for making appointments in the 70-day
period before his inauguration, but he will name people as decisions
are made, Fuller said. Bush named former Treasury Secretary James A.
Baker III the new secretary of state the day after Bush was elected.
   For major appointments, Fuller said Bush would be presented with
three to five names. The president-elect does not have to chose any
of the people on the list, however. Both Fuller and Teeter will
interview candidates.
   On his return to the nation's capital Tuedsay, Bush will meet
with German Chancellor Helmut Kohl. Vice President-elect Dan Quayle
will sit in on the meeting, Fuller said. On Wednesday, Bush sees
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   Besides the top jobs, the transition needs to hire people who
will work in the office until Jan. 20. Officials will also sift
through resumes from people hoping to be hired for the 5,000
political jobs that come open next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 2144EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--FoodAirlift     11-14 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Food Airlift,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Group Packs Food For Hurricane Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shipment of relief supplies put together
by a Mississippi church group for Jamaicans still recovering from
Hurricane Gilbert will include a classic Southern delicacy _ 40,000
pounds of red beans and rice.
   Also included in the $30,758 package is 5,000 pounds of dried
eggs, 5,000 pounds of powdered milk and 10,000 pounds of flour, said
Jerry Mitchell of Jackson, coordinator of a disaster relief program
for the Mississippi Conference of the United Methodist Church.
   ``Even though it's out of the newspapers, the people are still
suffering,'' Mitchell said.
   At least 26 people were killed in September when Hurricane
Gilbert swept over Jamaica and damaged most of the island's homes
and crops.
   An Air National Guard C141B transport will carry the food later
this week, Mitchell said. A shipment of building materials is
planned later this month.
</TEXT>
