<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Dukakis     11-14 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis: `It's Nice To Be Back'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis said today it's ``nice to
be back at the Statehouse'' and too early to decide whether to seek
re-election in 1990.
   ``I'm back at a job I love. I'm challenged by it,'' Dukakis said
at his first news conference on state issues since he lost the race
for the White House. He promised to make a decision on his plans
sometime next year.
   During the news conference, Dukakis announced steps to address
the ``major challenges'' facing Massachusetts government, including
a budget deficit projected by House Ways and Means Committee
chairman Richard Voke at $282 million.
   The governor refused to rule out new taxes but promised to
balance the $11.6 billion budget when the fiscal year ends in June.
   ``We face major challenges,'' Dukakis acknowledged, but he
disagreed with critics who maintain the state faces a ``fiscal
crisis'' and denied that problems have worsened at home because of
his presidential campaign.
   Asked about his political future, Dukakis said he had made no
decision about whether to run for governor again in 1990. ``It's too
early to tell,'' he said.
   The governor spent the weekend getting his first rest in weeks.
``It's nice to be back at the Statehouse,'' he said after taking the
trolley to work. ``The Green Line was on time and working.''
   Dukakis said he was grateful to legislators for their ``patience
and cooperation'' during his 20-month presidential effort.
   Dukakis outlined the steps he is taking to control spending, four
months into the fiscal year. They include giving his finance
secretary veto power over most hiring, meeting with his Cabinet
secretaries to discuss savings targets, and getting tough on
spending in government accounts that traditionally run
``deficiencies.'' He singled out the huge Medicaid account.
   Despite the savings steps, Dukakis insisted tax collections are
only slightly below the monthly benchmarks set by the Revenue
Department.
   Asked about the need for new or higher taxes, Dukakis said: ``I
hope we can avoid them.'' Asked if he foresees layoffs, he said: ``I
would hope not.''
</TEXT>
