<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryWomen     11-14 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Women,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Jobs Opened to Women in Military Following Discrimination
Review</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year-long review of the military's treatment
of its female personnel ended Monday with the Army announcing it was
opening 11,138 new jobs to women, Pentagon officials said.
   The decision, when combined with previous moves by the Navy, Air
Force and Marine Corps, brings to more than 24,000 the number of
previously closed positions opened to women since the review began
in October 1987.
   ``I think the overall message is that the secretary (of defense)
is firmly committed to opening all positions to women that are
compatible with existing laws and statutues,'' said Dr. David J.
Armor, the principal deputy assistant secretary for manpower.
   Armor said the decision indicates the Pentagon's commitment to
``maximize (women's) opportunities in the military.''
   Currently, women comprise 10.4 percent of the U.S. armed forces,
or about 217,400 enlisted personnel and officers of the 2.1 million
total.
   Armor declined to predict whether opening additional positions to
women might attract more female recruits. ``In the Army, for
example, we have 50 percent of the Army positions open to women. But
I don't think we'll ever have 50 percent of those positions filled
by women because it requires the people to volunteer.''
   Armor appeared at a Pentagon briefing to announce completion of
the work of the DoD Task Force on Women in the Military, a panel
formed in October 1987 after another advisory committee reported
strong evidence of sexual harassment and abuse in the Navy and
Marine Corps.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci, in reviewing task force
findings last January, ordered a new educational effort to attack
sexual harassment. He also ordered all four services to adopt the
same ``risk analysis'' rule for determining if particular jobs
should be closed to women.
   The task force found that while roughly 50 percent of military
personnel were assigned to combat positions _ which by law must be
filled by men _ and roughly 50 percent were in non-combat support
jobs, there were thousands of jobs in the middle that required
judgment calls that frequently went against women.
   ``Each of the services had a way of designating positions,''
Armor said. ``That led to situations where a reconnaissance aircraft
in the Navy was closed but it was open in the Air Force. So what
we've really done here is adopted the same value in evaluating
risk.''
   The new rule specifies that a particular job or military
occupation should be judged not on the basis of the skills involved
or the unit to which it is now assigned, but on whether the position
would expose an individual to the same risk of hostile fire as a
combat job.
   Applying that standard, the Navy previously had opened new jobs
to women aboard logistic support ships; the Air Force had opened
positions in its Red Horse civil engineering units and surveillance
aircraft like the TR-1 and U-2 spy planes; and the Marine Corps had
opened slots within its embassy guard force and base security forces.
   The Army positions opened on Monday include jobs within a
specialty that involves constructing electrical power systems to
support rear headquarter units; some additional jobs in the Engineer
Combat Support Equipment Companies; and many new positions within
the headquarters staff of combat units.
   Such headquarters operations would be set up well behind the line
of fighting where the risk of combat exposure is not that great, the
Army decided.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0085 </DOCNO>
