<1ST_LINE>u w AM-HeartDevices 1stLd-Writethru a0570 11-14 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heart Devices, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0570,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Gadgets Zap Fatty Deposits That Cause Heart Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 14th graf pvs, bgng: `In addition,' to remove garble</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors are attacking heart disease with a
variety of tiny new devices that shave, sand or burn away fatty
deposits that clog the arteries, according to reports Monday.
   ``This is in its infancy,'' said Dr. George Beller of the
University of Virginia. ``Progress is being made by leaps and
bounds. We are starting to see the first trials in patients.''
   All of the gadgets being developed are intended to burrow through
plugged heart arteries and blast away the fatty buildups that choke
off the flow of blood and cause heart attacks.
   They were described Monday at the annual meeting of the American
Heart Association. An estimated 30,000 people are attending the
four-day meeting.
   All of the devices are intended to replace or improve balloon
angioplasty. This treatment, performed on 184,000 people last year,
is one of the nation's most common medical procedures.
   During angioplasty, doctors thread a tiny balloon through an
artery into the heart. There it's inflated, squeezing open the
narrowed blood vessel. However, in about 30 percent of cases the
vessel soon closes shut again.
   Doctors hope the new tools will solve this problem. The devices
have been tested on numbers ranging from about 50 to more than 200
patients. While these initial results show they can open up clogged
arteries, more followup will be necessary before doctors know
whether the long-term success is any better than with balloon
angioplasty.
   The new devices include:
   _Shaver catheter. This device works something like a miniature
electric razor. Anything on the vessel walls that contacts the
catheter's whirling blades is sliced off and removed.
   _Rotablator. This is a diamond-coated burr similar to a dentist's
drill. ``It literally polishes and sands the inside of a diseased
vessel,'' said Dr. Robert Ginsburg of Stanford University.
   _Hot-tipped laser. This metal point is heated by a laser. It
burns away the fatty deposits.
   _Smart laser. This approach uses a laser beam directly to burn
the deposits. Earlier attempts failed because the pin-point beam
burned holes in the artery. Now doctors are marking the fat first
with specific colors, then using lasers that only attack those
colors.
   _Laser and balloon. In this technique, doctors open up the artery
with a balloon. Then they use relatively low levels of laser heat to
seal off tears in the vessel wall and, they hope, prevent it from
squeezing shut again.
   In addition, several reports at the meeting describe the use of
mesh tubes that are pushed into the newly opened blood vessels. The
goal is to hold the blood vessels open after angioplasty.
   Of the devices described, the shaver catheter has been tested
most widely, used on about 230 heart patients at several hospitals.
   Its developer, Dr. John B. Simpson of Sequoia Hospital in Redwood
City, Calif., predicted that it will be approved for widespread use
in about a year. Doctors working with other devices said as much as
five years more testing may be required before they can be employed
routinely.
   Several experts said they doubt the devices will replace the need
for coronary bypass surgery, a common technique in which blood is
detoured around plugged arteries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1339EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-IslandTelephones Bjt   11-14 0802</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Island Telephones, Bjt,0824</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Isolated Island Dwellers Hope New Phone System Will Draw Newcomers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GLENN ADAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLE AU HAUT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 45 year-round residents of this
rockbound island are putting their highly prized privacy on the line
and allowing telephones in their homes in an effort to guarantee
their future.
   ``The survival of the community's at stake here,'' said Belvia
MacDonald, who led efforts to bring phones to the island but won't
get one herself. ``I like the quietness, and they're going to put in
a phone booth I can use.''
   MacDonald, who has lived with her lobsterman husband on the
rugged island for more than three decades, said Isle au Haut needs
new residents to keep businesses viable and the post office and
one-room schoolhouse open.
   Telephones could be an incentive for people considering living on
Isle au Haut, one of about 2,000 islands along Maine's jagged coast
and perhaps the last New England town without service.
   While there have been only minor fluctuations in the island's
population, residents are getting concerned about an impending loss
as the core of year-round residents ages. A few older people already
have moved off the island over the last couple of years to be closer
to medical facilities.
   Rocky and guarded at one end by 500-foot cliffs, Isle au Haut's
residents are proud of their spirit of self-reliance, required for
the sometimes harsh environment and isolation.
   ``People out here enjoy this remote living, without the worries
and hassles of a more normal environment,'' said Louis ``Bud''
Blaisdell, a town selectman.
   While some do not relish the arrival of phones, they prefer that
intrusion to the prospect of losing their way of life.
   Crime is unheard of. Virtually every adult pitches in with some
civic service, such as volunteer firefighter or town selectman. In
summer, practically everyone, from the youngest child to elderly
folks, join in evening softball games.
   ``Any problem of any sort, people will cooperate and help.
They're very sensitive to others' problems,'' Blaisdell said. ``It's
like a large family.''
   Electrical service was introduced only 18 years ago to the
fishing community, also as a hedge against population loss. The
islanders' power cooperative hooked up to the mainland grid by an
undersea cable in 1982.
   To a visitor, the utility poles running and a car or pickup truck
that occasionally rolls by are the only clues that the 20th century
has arrived on the six- by three-mile Isle au Haut, French for high
island.
   It may be the last town in Maine, and possibly New England, to be
without telephone service, said Bill Black of the Maine Public
Advocate's Office, which was involved in efforts to bring phone
service to the island.
   Efforts began two years ago, when a ``telephone committee'' found
that 88 percent of the residents wanted the service. Initial efforts
to find a supplier failed. Companies said the project would be too
expensive. But in June, Jeffrey V. Webber, founder and president of
the tiny Island Telephone Co., came forward.
   Webber set up a similar service a few years ago for the Maine
island of Frenchboro, and can provide it to Isle au Haut for an
estimated $180,000.
   The microwave towers are to be erected this week.
   Sixteen homes have been connected to phone lines and can
communicate among themselves, and Webber said full service off the
island should be in place by Thanksgiving. ``If they don't get it
with their turkey, they'll get a bow on it'' this Christmas, he said.
   ``I'm pretty much against the phones, though we're going to get
one,'' said Lori Jablon, a teacher's aide. ``You can't pretend they
don't exist.''
   The island's more than 300 summer residents are likewise split,
but have supported community efforts to provide service.
   Blaisdell, a retired engineer who made due for years without
running water, welcomes the new technology. To call his son in
Florida, he now must drive to the dock and board the mailboat for a
40-minute ride to the island of Stonington to the nearest pay phone.
   Tina Tully, one of the first islanders to get a phone, described
her first call as ``wonderful.''
   Her federally licensed radio phone has been the island's only
dependable telecommunications link with the world, but she said her
neighbors have always respected her family's privacy and seldom
asked to use it.
   Citizen's band radios, used sometimes in the past, are impersonal
and their signals are often drowned out by static, residents say.
   None of the islanders interviewed could recall a situation in
which a phone would have made the difference between life or death.
And no one knows how life will change when the full system is up,
but so far, Tully said, ``It hasn't done anything but make life
easier.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
