<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1421EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     11-14 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerrie Schipske didn't win a seat on
the City Council, but her post-election cleanup could be a sign she
has a bright future as an environmental activist.
   Ms. Schipske, anxious to clear the community of her campaign
signs after last week's election, ran a newspaper ad offering $1 for
each sign returned.
   Unfortunately, she neglected to say in the ad that she only
wanted her campaign signs, not everybody else's.
   On Sunday, as she waited at a park to collect her own signs,
people showed up with signs from Assembly, Senate, congressional and
presidential contests as well as from elections in the cities of
Cypress, Garden Grove and Huntington Beach. There were even signs
promoting the campaign of Les Robbins, who had defeated Ms. Schipske.
   ``I kept telling them, `Why should I pay for someone else's
signs?''' she said.
   But she paid $50 for her own signs and promised to send checks to
15 families that brought only signs she didn't want.
   And afterward she hauled all the signs away.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NORTH BERGEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In one corner, dozens of Sudanese
Dervishes stand ready to defend Khartoum against British cavalry.
Nearby are Abyssinian tribesmen, poised to fight off Mussolini's
invasion.
   And just around the corner, Zulu warriors armed with shields and
spears fight Boer settlers for the plains of South Africa.
   All in New Jersey, where about 1,000 collectors of military
miniatures gathered Sunday to trade, sell or admire detailed
replicas of armies and weaponry.
   ``There seems to be less interest this year in mainstream armies,
like the British and French,'' mused Tom Fallon, a clinical
psychologist from Boston who paints the intricate uniforms on the
tiny armies he sells during weekends. ``I'd say the English Civil
War and the Boer War are the most popular this year.''
   Fallon's wares included a regiment of Imperial Chinese troops
from the Boxer Rebellion of the 1890s and Belgian soldiers from
World War I.
   ``In many ways the more obscure the conflict, the greater the
value to the collector,'' he said. ``But we, that is collectors, are
not militarists. We do this so that we can remember the mistakes of
the past, so that we do not repeat them.''
   Bill Lango, a collector and vendor from North Bergen, said he
began collecting miniatures in 1965.
   ``I wanted to get the toys I had as a kid back from my parents,
but we moved around a lot and they threw the stuff out along the
way,'' he said. ``So my wife and I started going to antique shops on
the weekends and it kind of became a habit.''
   But it's peaceful habit, he said. ``We think of ourselves more
like people who trade baseball cards than warlike.''
   Collecting soldiers, according to Vincent Vernon of Bardstown,
Ky., can be traced to ancient Egypt. Louis XIV had an army of toy
soldiers as a child, and Napoleon used toy soldiers to plan
conquests.
</TEXT>
