<HEAD>9,000 Kurds Settled In Houses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIYARBAKIR, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities Monday moved 9,000 Kurdish
refugees from a tent city to houses in this southeastern city, the
Anatolia news agency reported.
   The 60,000 Kurdish refugees who fled Iraq in its eight-year war
with Iran have been living in five tent cities.
   The refugees were moved to some of the 450 homes the government
built 13 years ago for victims of an earthquake. The houses were
considered badly made and were rebuilt for the refugees.
   Last month, another group of 6,700 Kurdish refugees were moved to
houses in the eastern city of Mus.
   The Kurds charged Iraqi armed forces had attacked them with
chemical weapons in the war. A cease-fire took effect Aug. 20.
