<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Portraying the piano-pounding Jerry Lee
Lewis takes a lot of spontaneity, says Dennis Quaid, star of ``Great
Balls Of Fire.''
   ``To be spontaneous, you've got to be willing to fall flat on
your face, and that's what it's like with Jerry Lee. That's why
you're always on the edge of your seat watching him. You're just
waiting for him to fall,'' Quaid said.
   ``He's up there with one foot on the wire,'' Quaid said in a
recent interview.
   ``Great Balls Of Fire,'' which covers Lewis' life from 1956-58,
is filming in Memphis through early January.
   Quaid said he had planned to sing in the film, but no one told
Lewis, who also planned to do the singing.
   ``Before we really knew each other, we had a conversation in a
packed dressing room. When he saw me, he said: `Son, you can't sing
like Jerry Lee Lewis.'
   ``Now I don't really operate this way but I had to, so I said:
`Well, for that matter, you can't act like Dennis Quaid, either.'
And we spent five hours talking it over.''
   Lewis prevailed.
</TEXT>
