<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Morrissey, director of the new comedy
``Spike of Bensonhurst,'' relishes the freedom of being an
independent filmmaker despite the hardships.
   ``To be an independent is to take a really difficult route these
days,'' said Morrissey, who collaborated with pop art innovator Andy
Warhol on the offbeat comedies ``Trash,'' ``Flesh'' and ``Heat.''
   ``You know independent voices were heard in Hollywood in the '30s
and '40s,'' he said. ``People were able to say, `Let's do this,' and
it was done _ just like that.''
   Morrissey said he likes to do things his way and will continue to
do so even if ``Spike,'' a comedy of real-life absurdity set in a
Mafia-run neighborhood, attracts offers from Hollywood studios.
   ``It's a debilitating process working with the studios,'' he
said. ``With the length of time it takes for drafts and development
deals, your enthusiasm is gone before you're ready to make the
film.''
