<HEAD>Authorities Look To Link to Terrorists In Bombing Attempt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with no plea entered at court
appearance, no comment from prosecutor on published reports. PICKS
UP 8th graf pvs, `Animal rights ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An animal rights activist accused of
planting a bomb in an attempt to kill the head of a surgical
instruments company may have been supplied with the explosive device
by a terrorist group, a newspaper reported.
   The activist, Fran Stephanie Trutt, 33, of New York City, was
arraigned in Superior Court today on charges of attempted murder,
possession of explosives and manufacturing a bomb. She was being
held on $500,000 bail.
   Trutt did not enter enter a plea or speak during the appearance
and was scheduled for another hearing Nov. 29. Judge Edward Leavitt
refused to lower bail.
   Trutt was arrested Friday and accused of hiding a powerful,
radio-controlled pipe bomb packed with roofing nails in bushes at
the headquarters of U.S. Surgical Corp., near the vacant parking
space of chairman Leon Hirsch.
   The Sunday Advocate of Stamford quoted an unidentified source as
saying that police and the FBI are convinced that Ms. Trutt could
not have made the sophisticated bomb herself and that they believe a
terrorist group supplied the device.
   Three more bombs were discovered in Trutt's apartment after her
arrest.
   ``They're not nuclear weapons,'' a source told the newspaper.
``But the bombs are unique for their electronics.''
   The New York City police department's terrorist task force has
joined the FBI in the investigation into the manufacture of the
bombs, said spokeswoman Sgt. Diane Kubler.
   Assistant State's Attorney Harry Katz had no comment today on the
published reports.
   Animal rights activists have disavowed Trutt, saying that she is
not a member of their groups.
   The Norwalk company manufactures surgical staplers, which close
incisions without stitches, and demonstrates the devices on
anesthetized dogs.
   Trutt had a remote-control device in her hands that was to be
used to detonate the foot-long pipe bomb when she was arrested,
police said. About 200 people were working in the plant overnight at
the time.
   The three nail-wrapped bombs found in Trutt's basement apartment
were fashioned from plumbing pipes and ``certainly would have
destroyed the entire building'' and damaged surrounding houses, said
police Deputy Inspector Vincent Tarone.
   The New York-based Fund for Animals filed a complaint over the
experiments with the state Department of Health Services, which
rejected the complaint last month.
   Trutt's parents, Mary and Harry Trutt of New Hyde Park, N.Y.,
said their daughter told them in a telephone call from the jail
Saturday that she was set up by friends, who then tipped police.
   In an interview with Newsday, the Trutts said their daughter, who
graduated from Adelphi University and has a teaching certificate,
had no mechanical schooling and couldn't possibly have assembled the
bombs.
   She cared deeply about animals, often picking up strays and
nursing them back to health, the Trutts said. ``She would never,
never, under any circumstance, hurt anyone, or do anything to harm
anybody,'' Mrs. Trutt said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
