<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 2145EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--Drought-Lilacs     11-14 0140</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Drought-Lilacs,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thanks To Drought, Lilacs Bloom In Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND ISLAND, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lilacs in November? Thanks to this
year's drought, the purple, sweet-smelling flowers are blooming now.
   ``I was really shocked when we were out walking and saw them,''
said Barb Anderson of Grand Island. ``We thought we were seeing
things.''
   Lilacs can bloom in the fall ``in years with very hot, high
temperatures and some moisture stress,'' said Don Steinegger,
University of Nebraska extension horticulture specialist. ``It
doesn't happen on a regular basis but it does happen.''
   Lilacs, apples, cherries, peaches and pears, all can flower in
the fall. Plants that usually flower in the spring form their buds
in late summer, and the buds stay dormant over the winter,
Steinegger said. But heat and dryness during development can bring a
bloom on early, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
