<DOCNO> AP881114-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1456EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Botha-Film     11-14 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Botha-Film,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Questions Raised About Botha Link To Anti-Communist War Film</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition parties Monday
demanded an inquiry into why state television helped finance an
anti-communist war film for which President P.W. Botha's daughter
was production coordinator.
   The film ``Back To Freedom'' opened in South Africa last week and
has been panned by critics as an amateurish propaganda exercise.
   The far-right Conservative Party called for a commission to
investigate the South African Broadcasting Corp.'s involvement in
the production.
   Parliament member Dave Dalling, media spokesman for the liberal
Progressive Federal Party, said the film company involved was owned
by a friend of President Botha. Dalling asked who authorized the
corporation to provide more than $1 million to finance the film.
   Botha's daughter, Rozanne, coordinated production of the film,
but in the credits her last name is given as ``Both'' instead of
Botha. The film's scriptwriter, a university professor, also used a
pseudonym.
   Public controversy was sparked by reports in Sunday newspapers
that Alvyn Schlebusch, the Cabinet minister formerly in charge of
the corporation, had recommended that the final $200,000 installment
of its payment to Mimosa Films be withheld because the film was
substandard.
   According to the reports, President Botha overruled Schlebusch
and ordered the payment.
   Schlebusch subsequently resigned. His successor, Stoffel van der
Merve, said the broadcasting company's involvement in the film was
legitimate.
   In return for its financing, the corporation was to get all
domestic box office profits and half of overseas profits.
   The movie plot is based loosely on the civil war in Angola, where
South African-backed rebels are fighting the Soviet- and
Cuban-supported troops of Angola's Marxist government.
   South African military equipment was used in the film and dozens
of soldiers reportedly served as extras. The Sunday Times newspaper
said it was believed the script was submitted to Angolan rebel
leader Jonas Savimbi for approval.
</TEXT>
