<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1456EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TunnelExplosion     11-14 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tunnel Explosion,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Victims of Tunnel Explosion Died of Burns, Carbon Monoxide
Poisoning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LIGHTFOOT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three victims of a sewerage tunnel explosion
lived a short time before succumbing to burns and carbon monoxide
poisoning, a medical examiner's investigator said Monday.
   ``They might have been unconscious,'' said Richard Goeb, who
could not say exactly how long the men lived.
   Milwaukee County District Attorney E. Michael McCann said the
cause of Thursday's explosion may never be known, but his office was
investigating to ensure that all possible safety precautions are
taken in tunnel work.
   ``There's no question it is dangerous,'' McCann said. ``Can
anything be done? We hope it can.''
   McCann said it may still be another week before investigators can
enter the tunnel. High levels of methane gas have kept it closed
since the bodies were removed.
   The victims were identified as Ron Kohne, 49, a shift
superintendent from Big Sandy, Tenn.; Tony Bell, 25, a shift foreman
from Sturgeon Bay; and Rick Sochacki, 34, a safety officer from
South Holland, Ill. All were employees of the S.A. Healy Co. of
McCook, Ill., and were checking methane levels when the explosion
occurred.
   It took eight hours for rescuers to reach the victims and remove
their bodies from 2,000 feet inside the tunnel, part of a project
for the Metropolitan Milwaukee Sewerage District.
   Occupational Safety and Health Administration investigators were
interviewing Healy workers and officials and fire department
personnel who took part in the rescue, Gerald Cunningham, spokesman
for OSHA, said Monday.
   Cunningham said OSHA investigators were hoping to determine
whether an OSHA regulation to provide a safe and healthful workplace
and safe and healthful environment had been violated.
   Cunningham said Healy, which in March was cited by OSHA for
violations including inadequate ventilation of a shaft leading to a
tunnel, had been ``most cooperative'' in the investigation.
   Company officials did not immediately return calls seeking
comment.
   Six people, including those on Thursday, have died on the
Metropolitan Milwaukee Sewerage District project.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
