<HEAD>Iran Asks Soviets To Resume Joint Projects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran has urged the Soviet Union to resume
joint ventures halted by the eight-year Iran-Iraq war, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported Monday.
   Mohammad Iravani, Iran's economic and financial affairs minister,
made the request to Oleg Bortyevmev, deputy chairman of the Soviet
construction committee, during his visit to Tehran.
   Iravani asked the Soviets to complete a project that would boost
output at the Isfahan steel plant, as well as transportation
projects and dams on the Aras, Atrak and Harirud rivers, according
to the agency, monitored in Nicosia.
   Bortyevmev said his government wants to build factories in Iran
for making construction materials.
   Iran and the Soviet Union also plan to operate a shipping line in
the Caspian Sea, and Iran has agreed to buy two freighters from the
Soviet Union.
   The Soviet Union pulled hundreds of technicians from Iran after
Iraqi air raids in 1985. A cease-fire in the war took effect Aug. 20.
