<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nigeria     11-14 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nigeria,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem Leader Begins Reign in Nigeria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new leader of Nigeria's Moslems was
installed under heavy security Monday, one week after rioting over
his appointment led to the deaths of 10 people.
   Ibrahim Dasuki became the 18th Sultan of Sokoto during a
traditional ceremony of pomp and prayer in which he was crowned with
a turban. Police and soldiers stood guard.
   He succeeds Sadiq Abubakar, who led the Moslem community for 50
years before his death Nov. 1 at the age of 85.
   Three days after Abubakar died, a nine-member committee known as
the ``kingmakers'' gave the title to Dasuki, 65, a former civil
servant and previous secretary of Nigeria's Supreme Council for
Islamic Affairs.
   On Nov. 6, the military governor approved Dasuki as the new
sultan, touching off two days of rioting by Moslems who favored
Abubakar's elder son, Muhammadu Maccido.
   Radio Nigeria said rioters burned buildings, including a radio
station and a branch of the Luxembourg-based Bank of Credit and
Commerce International, of which Dasuki is chairman.
   Officials ordered a dusk-to-dawn curfew with soldiers patrolling
the streets.
   Before order was restored, 10 people were killed and dozens more
were hurt, including at least five policemen who were seriously
injured. Authorities have not said how the 10 civilians died.
   Sokoto is 465 miles north of Lagos, the capital.
   The sultan's position is powerful, heading the Moslems who make
up 47 percent of Nigerians. He also is revered by Moslems in
neighboring countries and frequently is consulted by Nigerian
politicians of all denominations.
   Christians account for 34 percent of the nearly 103 million
people in Nigeria, black Africa's most populous and powerful nation.
Most other Nigerians are animists.
</TEXT>
