<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     11-14 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0714</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bhutto, Rivals Draw Large Crowds at Final Campaign Rallies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benazir Bhutto drew 20,000 people to
rally of her populist party in Peshawar and the rightist opposition
attracted an equal crowd in Lahore on Monday, the last day of
campaigning for national elections.
   Ms. Bhutto ended the campaign of her Pakistan People's Party for
the Wednesday election at Peshawar, a northwestern border city in
the heart of the region where more 3 million Afghan refugees live.
   The nine-party Islamic Democratic Alliance chose the old Punjab
capital of Lahore for its last rally, which was preceded by a slow
procession through the streets of the northeastern city.
   Witnesses said a Bhutto rally at Lahore on Sunday attracted
``record-breaking'' crowds whose procession arrived at the rally
site eight hours late. About 60 percent of Pakistan's 107 million
people live in Punjab.
   Shaukat Ali, a journalist for the English-language Lahore
newspaper Dawn, said some people at the Sunday rally were those
``who just want to get a look'' at Ms. Bhutto, who is from Sind, a
southern province, and pays few visits to the north.
   Leading the Islamic Alliance rally Monday was Nawaz Sharif, the
Punjab chief minister.
   Ms. Bhutto's main opposition comes from the alliance on the right
and the Awami National Party on the far left.
   At Peshawar's Jinnah Park, named for Mohammed Ali Jinnah, founder
of Pakistan, Mrs. Bhutto said Monday her party champions workers and
farmers. She said the Islamic Alliance, which includes loyalists of
the late President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, has ``become an opposition
alliance against the People's Party.''
   Her father, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, founded the Pakistan People's
Party and it carried him to power in 1973.
   Zia overthrew Bhutto in 1977. The former prime minister was
convicted of conspiring to kill a political rival, who was not
slain, and was hanged in 1979.
   Zia died in a plane crash Aug. 17, along with the U.S. ambassador
and 28 other people. Pakistani investigators said they suspected
sabotage, but the cause has not been established.
   Only a few women are involved in the election campaign, and
Benazir Bhutto alluded at Monday's rally to Moslem fundamentalists
who oppose the prospect of a woman leader.
   ``As a woman I am your sister. You are my force. Your success is
my success,'' she told her supporters, who had begun gathering three
hours earlier for her 20-minute speech.
   Officials ordered all campaigning to end at midnight Monday.
Federal and provincial authorities announced the mobilization of
police, army and paramilitary forces to guard against violence
during a lengthy voting period that runs through provincial assembly
elections Saturday.
   Officials said security would be tightest in Hyderabad and
Karachi, southern cities where nearly 300 people were killed in
September during ethnic riots with a political undertone in
September.
   At stake Wednesday are the 217 National Assembly seats, and the
party winning the most will have first chance at forming a
government. On Saturday, voters will chose the 483 members of the
four provincial legislatures.
   No reliable polls have been conducted but the election is seen
mainly as a contest betwen Ms. Bhutto's left-leaning party and the
Islamic Alliance, whose main leaders are Sharif, the Punjab chief
minister, and former Prime Minister Mohammad Khan Junejo.
   It will be the first democratic election since the one that swept
Zulfikar Ali Bhutto to power in 1973. He was re-elected in 1977 but
Zia nullified the vote after the coup, declaring it rigged.
   Parties rather than issues have dominated the campaign. Ms.
Bhutto has abandoned her father's unsuccessful policy of
nationalizing industry and, like the Islamic Alliance, pledges
continued close relations with the United States and aid to
anti-communist guerrillas in Afghanistan.
   Both favor Pakistan's nuclear research program, which the
government says is for peaceful purposes.
   Pakistan's 48 million eligible voters, three-fourths of them
illiterate, must present government identity cards in order to cast
ballots. Officials said about 93 percent of eligible voters had
cards, but Ms. Bhutto claimed the percentage was far lower.
   She has urged supporters who do have not been given cards to
demonstrate peacefully at voting stations.
</TEXT>
