<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Salvador, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0588,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Asks Latins To Pressure Nicaragua</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Shultz delivering speech;
PICKS up 4th pvs, `President Jose ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P.
Shultz said today Latin American nations should close ranks behind a
``new diplomacy'' aimed at pressuring the region's dictatorships
into making democratic reforms.
   ``The time is right for a new diplomacy _ a diplomacy based on
democractic solidarity and on the aggressive advocacy of democracy
by democratic states,'' Shultz said in a speech to Organization of
American States foreign ministers.
   In comments while en route here for an eight-hour visit, Shultz
said democracies in the region should consider ways to make
Nicaragua ``feel a sense of isolation'' as a means of promoting
democratic reform.
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte convened the weeklong OAS meeting
with a condemnation of leftist guerrillas battling waging a
9-year-old war against his U.S.-backed government. He also urged
debt relief for the hemisphere's nations.
   Duarte also called upon delegates to provide ``moral support''
for an eventual summit meeting of Central American presidents that
would try to breathe new life into a regional peace process begun in
August 1987.
   ``What is at stake is not just peace in Central America, but the
security of the entire continent,'' he said.
   In Shultz's comments, he singled out Paraguay and Cuba as
countries which have not been part of the democratic trend in the
hemisphere.
   Shultz criticized the OAS for what he regards as its indifferent
attitude toward the hemisphere's democratic development.
   ``This organization has not always been out front on issues
concerning democracy,'' Shultz told the delegates. ``Too often it
has been one step behind when it has needed to be one step ahead.''
   He suggested the OAS has been negligent in not insisting that
Nicaragua live up to its 1979 commitment to a pluralistic political
system.
   ``Agreements exist; promises have been made,'' he said. ``The
dictators and the totalitarians must be told they are not free to
subjugate their peoples.''
   A return trip to Washington is planned for tonight.
   In an interview last week, Assistant Secretary of State Elliott
Abrams said the Sandinistas have been so unyielding on democratic
reform that ``they've disappointed people who are even moderately
sympathetic to them.''
   He said there has been an increase in repression in Nicaragua
this year, including the continued detention of about 40 persons
involved in an anti-government protest last June.
   The Sandinistas contend U.S. efforts to destabilize Nicaragua are
continuing despite the military aid cutoff to the Contras. They cite
a statement two months ago by House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Tex., that
the administration was trying to disrupt peace talks in Nicaragua by
having the CIA ``provoke'' a clampdown by the Sandinistas.
   Shultz has been a frequent visitor to El Salvador over the years,
and the officials said today's speech was to include numerous
expressions of esteem and affection for Duarte, who is dying of
cancer.
   Duarte, who is in the last year of a five-year term, has been
perhaps the closest ally of the United States in the hemisphere and
his government is the biggest recipient of U.S. aid in the region.
   There are diplomats from at least two OAS countries with whom
Shultz had no plans to meet: Panama and Nicaragua. Reagan
administration policy forbids substantive contact with officials
from either government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
