<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--MaineEarthquake     11-14 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Maine Earthquake,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maine Quake 3.8 on Richter Scale; No Damage Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEWISTON, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small earthquake rumbled through western
Maine early Monday, but no injuries or damage were reported,
authorities said.
   The earthquake, which hit at 1:16 a.m. and measured 3.8 on the
Richter scale, was centered near Sumner, according to John Minsch of
the U.S. Geological Survey's National Earthquake Information Center
in Golden, Colo.
   Rumford police Sgt. Mike Boutte said police had received about 65
calls from people who reported feeling the quake. Boutte said there
were no reports of damage.
   The Maine Geological Survey also received a few calls from people
who felt the quake or noticed windows rattling, said the agency's
Mike Foley.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight damage
in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6
severe damage.
</TEXT>
