<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BalloonCrash     11-14 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Balloon Crash,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Balloon Blown Off Course and Crashes; Two Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CIRCLEVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-altitude balloon blown 500 miles
off course by a storm crashed today, seriously injuring two men
aboard, authorities said.
   Rescuers spotted the wreckage of the helium balloon near here and
reached the two men at mid-morning, said Utah Civil Air Patrol
spokesman Jerry Wellman. The were taken by ambulance to Garfield
Memorial Hospital in nearby Panguitch.
   Garfield County sheriff's dispatcher Cathy Holt said Ron Martin,
46, of Long Beach and Scott Hendricks, 30, of Chino, suffered broken
bones and complained of back injuries.
   The long-range balloon had taken off Sunday evening from a
parking lot near Disneyland in Orange County, Calif.
   Hajnal Crieg, who along with Martin owns the four-passenger,
3,500-cubic-foot balloon, said Martin, the craft's pilot, and
Hendricks, his friend, had intended only to take a tour of the Los
Angeles basin.
   ``But a storm came in. You can't really control a helium balloon,
so they went wherever the wind takes them,'' she said of the trip,
which ended about 500 air miles east of Los Angeles. ``They were
just on an overnight trip.''
   The crew had radioed air traffic controllers this morning that it
was losing altitude and needed emergency assistance. The Federal
Aviation Administration said it lost radar contact about 10 miles
south of Circleville.
   While a snowstorm enveloped much of the state, weather was clear
in southern Utah today, allowing an immediate search, Wellman said.
However, the National Weather Service had issued a high-wind warning
for the area in the morning.
   A balloon reported to have taken off near Disneyland on Sunday
apparently was not connected to the amusement park, said spokesman
Bob Roth.
</TEXT>
