<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-US     11-14 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-US,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Visiting Congressmen Promise American Aid To Philippines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. congressmen told President
Corazon Aquino on Monday that Washington will honor a pledge of more
economic aid and urged Manila to extend an agreement on U.S.
military bases after 1991.
   Mrs. Aquino told the Americans her government must achieve the
``widest consensus'' among Filipinos for ``entangling foreign
commitments.''
   The six-member delegation, led by Senate Minority Leader Robert
Dole, met with Mrs. Aquino and Philippine officials on the first
stop of a four-nation tour of Southeast Asia.
   The other members of the delegation were Sens. James McClure,
R-Idaho, Arlen Specter, R-Pa., Franck Murkowski, R-Alaska; and Reps.
Lawrence Coughlin, R-Pa., and William Lehman, D-Fla.
   Dole said President-elect George Bush will honor a commitment
made by President Reagan to support a multinational aid package to
bolster the Philippine economy.
   ``It's not just some statement, some rhetorics. It's going to
happen,'' Dole told reporters.
   Last month, Reagan pledged in a letter to Mrs. Aquino to work
with Japan, South Korea, West Germany and other U.S. allies to
develop the aid plan.
   The letter was delivered shortly after the United States and the
Philippines concluded an agreement Oct. 17 that guarantees U.S.
military use of six bases through 1991 in exchange for $962 million
in American aid.
   Any extension of the agreement beyond that year must be approved
by two-thirds of the 23-member Philippine Senate, where opposition
to the bases is strong.
   ``It is in the interest of both countries that we work out
appropriate arrangements fully consistent with Philippine
sovereignty that would permit continuation of access to the bases
facilities,'' the congressmen said in a statement.
   U.S. officials have said privately they would like to begin talks
on a new treaty early next year. The pact expires Sept. 16, 1991.
   Mrs. Aquino told the delegation that as democracies, the
Philippines and the United States ``need the widest consensus and
the most willing support for entangling foreign commitments.'' She
made no direct reference to the U.S. bases.
   Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus told reporters he briefed the
delegation on the results of a recent survey that showed about 75
percent of the 1,200 people polled favored extending the bases
beyond 1991. About 25 percent of the supporters, however, wanted
better financial terms from Washington.
   The delegation also will visit Bangkok, Thailand, Singapore and
Indonesia.
</TEXT>
