<HEAD>Orchestra Unrest Hampers Rehearsals For Gala Night</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walkouts by the orchestra have disrupted
rehearsals of ``William Tell,'' the Gioacchino Rossini opera which
is scheduled to inaugurate La Scala's season in December.
   A theater spokesman reported Monday that six rehearsals have been
canceled so far and that others are being put at risk by the labor
unrest.
   Members of the orchestra have been refusing to show up for
rehearsals to press their demands for higher pay and fringe benefits.
   The theater management has countered that pay increases can not
be immediately granted because of a recent government decision to
cut back on funds allocated to opera houses.
   ``William Tell,'' directed by maestro Riccardo Muti and starring
Chris Merritt, is to be performed on a gala night inaugurating the
opera season Dec. 7.
