<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FoamingStatue     11-14 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foaming Statue,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Embarrassing Solution for Sybil Luddington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARMEL, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They thought about chopping off Sybil
Luddington's head, and they thought about boring holes into her
skull. But so far they've contented themselves with putting a gasbag
over her head.
   Sybil was the 16-year-old heroine who rode through the
countryside warning colonists that the British were burning Danbury,
Conn., in 1778.
   She has been memorialized in a song, a poem, a postage stamp and
a statue put up in 1961 on the shore of Lake Gleneida in Carmel.
   But the statue has been acting up lately, acquiring the
unbecoming habit of foaming at the mouth.
   Suggestions were made to decapitate it to examine what was
causing the foaming, and boring holes to see what was inside.
   But on Sunday, metallurgist Terry Lowe put a plastic bag over the
head of the statue and pumped it full of gas.
   He said he had identified the foam as calcium sulphate, or
gypsum, and believes it was part of a plaster mold left behind when
the statue was made. He thinks the residue is seeping from the pores
in the bronze.
   Lowe said he will watch the bag for signs that the gas is
escaping into the statue, which would confirm that there are such
pores.
</TEXT>
