<HEAD>11-Year-Old Takes Bus on Four-Accident Rampage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old boy stole a bus Monday morning and
took it on a wild seven-block ride which led to four collisions and
left one woman and the boy injured, the Transit Authority said.
   The boy climbed in the 40-foot, 13-ton bus in a Brooklyn
maintenance yard, and pulled out onto the street, where the
accidents quickly began, said TA spokesman Bob Slovak.
   Slovak said the bus smashed into the left side of a parked fire
engine; crashed into the left side of a parked truck; collided
head-on into a car, injuring a woman inside; and careened into a
pillar beneath subway tracks.
   The youth bailed out of the moving bus between the second and
third accidents, said Slovak. He was injured in one of the first two
crashes, and was taken to St. Mary's Hospital.
   Police were investigating why the boy was not in school, Slovak
said.
   Slovak was unsure where the driver of the moving car was taken,
and had no details on her injuries. The bus went just seven blocks
before smashing into the pillar, he said.
