<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     11-14 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tamil Rebels Fire at Bus Passengers, Kill 27</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil rebels ambushed a bus in
northeastern Sri Lanka and opened fire on the passengers, killing at
least 27 people, police said.
   Three people also were injured in the morning attack on the
state-run public bus near Pinkatiya village, about 146 miles
northeast of Colombo, said a police official who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   Soldiers were searching the area for at least 15 attackers who
fled after the killings, he said.
   The victims are believed to be Sinhalese, including several women
and children.
   In Colombo, President Junius R. Jayewardene called a meeting with
the powerful Buddhist clergy who have been calling for him and his
Cabinet to resign. Government sources, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said no agenda has been fixed for the Monday night
meeting.
   The island nation off the southern coast of India is facing two
violent uprisings _ the lingering Tamil rebellion in the northeast
and a backlash by radical Sinhalese in the south.
   The mostly Buddhist Sinhalese claim government peace overtures to
the predominantly Hindu Tamils grant too many concessions to the
minority community.
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest Tamil militant
group, say the government's offers fell below expectations to end
alleged discrimination in jobs and education. They are continuing
their 5-year-old war for an independent homeland.
   The ambush came six days before local elections in the
Tamil-dominated northeast province.
   The Tigers have vowed to disrupt the election of the first
provincial council with limited autonomy. It was sanctioned by an
Indian-brokered peace accord in July 1987 and was meant to appease
Tamil demands for self-rule.
   Radical Sinhalese, mainly from the People's Liberation Front,
have stepped up demands for Jayewardene's resignation and called a
four-day strike last week.
   It caused severe food and fuel shortages, especially in the
Sinhalese-dominated south, and crippled the tourism industry that
brings in $67 million a year.
   Armed with broad new powers to combat the Sinhalese threat, the
Sri Lankan army went on television Monday warning it will crush any
group that tries to bring down Jayewardene's government.
   ``The armed forces have been vested with enough power by the
government to deal with any group or movement which threatens the
sovereignty, independence and the very existence of the democratic
form of government,'' said a statement read by an unidentified army
officer.
   The government says the People's Liberation Front has killed at
least 550 people, mostly Sinhalese government officials and
supporters, since the peace accord was signed.
   On Wednesday, the army got orders to shoot anti-government
demonstrators on sight. The following day, soldiers killed at least
18 people when they opened fire on protesters in three southern
towns.
   On Friday, Jayewardene issued an emergency decree providing a
maximum sentence of death by hanging for anyone convicted of
instigating a strike.
   Seventy-five percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people are
Sinhalese, who control most government and military jobs.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
