<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bush-Vacation     11-14 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Vacation,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Barbara Bush: In The Swim, But No Photos, Please</HEAD>
<BYLINE>RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GULF STREAM, Fla., (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The next first lady of the United
States had one request for the news media on Monday: ``Please don't
take pictures of me swimming.''
   ``My children are complaining all across the country,'' Barbara
Bush laughingly told photographers and television crews who staked
out the beach near the vacation home where she and her husband are
staying.
   President-elect George Bush chimed in with his daughter's
reaction to photographs of her mother swimming in a modest one piece
bathing suit: ``I could tell you exactly what Dorothy said when she
called in, but I don't use those kinds of words in front of the
national press corps.''
   Mrs. Bush is an avid swimmer, sometimes doing a mile at a time.
Both she and the president-elect have been seen daily since Thursday
in the balmy waters off the ocean-front home of their friend William
Stamps Farish III.
   The Bushes traded quips with reporters at the conclusion of a
question-and-answer session on the beach. Photographers told Bush
that if he planned to fish as usual that afternoon, he should try to
do so a little closer to the line behind which Secret Service agents
require the film crews to stand.
   ``Barbara says if you don't take pictures of her swimming, I'll
fish here,'' Bush joked.
   He also said noted that he has taken to wearing a T-shirt when he
swims, so nobody can snap revealing pictures of him.
   Talking about how he has enjoyed his few days at the beach, he
said:
   ``I think my mental attitude is in much better shape. I know my
body is. I'm sure everybody can attest to that, to these long
lenses, these long penetrating lenses which cause us to wear
T-shirts when we go swimming and all this kind of thing because we
don't want to be analysed by the doctors from the New York Times.''
   Reflecting further on the vacation time at the end of a long
political campaign, Bush said, ``You get to clear your mind. You get
to think a little bit about the future, you see these tremendous
problems but you just get refurbished in your desire to do the best
job you can.''
   He said he has run and fished every day.
   ``I love the fishing. It doesn't matter what you catch. It's the
fact you're out there and fishermen know that.
   ``And so I'm still of the Isaac Walton school _ that the days I
spend fishing should not be deducted from the time I spend on
earth.''
</TEXT>
