<HEAD>Bush Circumspect About Son's Political Aspirations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GULF STREAM, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush took a
cautious approach on Monday when asked about the political
aspirations of his oldest son, George W. Bush.
   In a beachfront question-and-answer session, a reporter
questioned Bush on speculation that his 42-year-old son would run
for governor of Texas.
   `I never intervene in primaries, and I expect if any of the Bush
boys ran they would have primaries. But I have no reason to believe
that he's going to do that which you asked about,'' Bush replied.
   His son, a graduate of Harvard Business School, campaigned full
time for his father's White House bid.
   He previously ran unsuccessfully for Congress and has been active
in grassroots politics. He took a leave from his oil company in
Midland, Texas, and moved his family to Washington to work on his
father's campaign.
   It was the younger Bush _ eldest of his five children _ who
announced the Texas delegation vote that put his father over the top
to be nominated at the Republican convention in New Orleans this
past summer.
   In that announcement he called his father, ``the man who made me
proud every single day of my life and a man who will make America
proud, the next president of the United States, my beloved father,
George Bush.''
