<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dubcek     11-14 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dubcek,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dubcek Says He Expects to Be Rebuked Upon Return Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOLOGNA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Dubcek said Monday he expects a
rebuke from the Czechoslovak regime for his outspokenness during his
first trip abroad in 18 years.
   Addressing 300 political science students, Dubcek repeatedly
invoked Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms as
justification for his own failed democratic moves in 1968.
   Since his first day in Italy on Saturday, Dubcek has praised
Gorbachev and criticized current leaders in Czechoslovakia and those
who saw him ousted as party chief shortly after Soviet tanks took
over Prague streets on Aug. 21, 1968.
   The Moscow-led invasion ended his attempt to ease censorship,
allow political freedoms and improve the economy during his few
months as Czechoslovak leader.
   Dubcek spoke animatedly about the Soviet bloc's past and future
in an overcrowded lecture hall at the University of Bologna, which
awarded him an honorary degree Sunday for his defense of personal
liberties.
   Referring to his party's version of events leading to the
invasion, Dubcek told applauding students: ``When I reject these,
what do you think they will tell me when I return home? (They will
say) that I am helping Western propaganda.'' He then joined in the
subsequent applause.
   Dubcek had believed after a meeting with Soviet leaders Aug. 3,
1968, that he could continue his reforms. The official version says
he was warned of the possible consequences.
   In all his appearances, Dubcek, 66, has been intent on convincing
the world he was right to implement his liberalization policy.
   After recounting for his young audience the years of violence
during the Stalinist era, Dubcek said:
   ``Gorbachev is trying to put distance from that system of so many
things that didn't work ...
   ``Many ask why, despite all the enormous difficulties, I continue
to insist that socialism is reformable.
   ``The idea of reform continues to live today ... The 20 years
that have passed have confirmed the rightness of our idea as you see
what is happening in the Soviet Union and other countries.''
   Dubcek said Western support is important for socialism's new
direction and Gorbachev's ``perestroika'' campaign to reform
political and economic policy. He dismissed as unfounded the
speculation that he submitted to some kind of censorship when he
read only excerpts from his highly critical speech at Sunday's award
ceremony. He said he cut out parts to save time since the text had
been published the previous evening.
   Dubcek was expected to spend at least another day in Bologna.
   Venice and Florence also are on his itinerary before his return
sometime next week to Bratislava, Czechoslavakia, near the Austrian
border, where he lives in retirement after years of working at a
lowly forestry department job assigned to him after he was stripped
of party membership in 1970.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1604EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-OAS Bjt   11-14 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OAS, Bjt,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OAS Meet Considers Organization's Future</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The financially strapped
Organization of American States opened its General Assembly on
Monday with a warning from its secretary-general that it could
become ``merely a bureaucratic contrivance.''
   Joao Baena Soares, the Brazilian head of the 31-member OAS, also
said that ``a new reality must be created within our hemisphere ...
that will find the OAS to be an effective political forum between
the Americas, north and south.''
   Baena Soares spoke just before Salvadoran President Jose Napoleon
Duarte, who formally opened the week-long session. Duarte, who has
terminal cancer, energetically condemned leftist guerrillas battling
his government and called for support for the stalled Central
American peace process.
   U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz attended the inaugural
session.
   In his speech, Baena Soares addressed two fundamental criticisms
leveled at the OAS since its foundation in 1948: that it is an
ineffective, essentially bureaucratic forum, and that it is
dominated by the United States.
   ``Over this session of the General Assembly there looms a central
issue that must be settled,'' said Baena Soares. ``The member
governments must decide what they want to do with the OAS at this
critical juncture in the life of the Americas.''
   He also lamented the organization's ``extremely difficult
financial circumstances.''
   The OAS is nearly bankrupt because most member nations are far
behind in their dues. The United States, which provides the lion's
share of the budget as well as the OAS headquarters in Washington
owes $41 million.
   ``The (financial) situation has been insurmountable because of a
failure to comply with the legal obligations that establish the
member states' commitment to contribute their quotas,'' Baena Soares
said.
   Baena Soares said in September the U.S. arrears ``severely
affect'' the functioning of the OAS. House Speaker Jim Wright said
at the time that Latin nations interpreted Washington's retention of
funds as an effort to reassert its domination of the forum.
   An OAS commission has recommended that the organization cut its
$66 million budget by 30 percent and fire a fourth of its staff of
1,004. The foreign ministers and heads of delegations meeting here
will decide whether to accept the recommendation.
   Shultz said in a speech that the Reagan administration ``will ask
for full funding of our assessed contribution to the OAS in 1990.''
   Baena Soares declared: ``It is often said that the OAS is too
costly. Indeed it is, if all its diplomatic-political potential is
not used, if it subsists as merely a bureaucratic contrivance.''
   He also called for joint action on Latin America's foreign debt.
The United States, the largest hemispheric creditor, has tried to
discourage tentative efforts by debtor nations to form a block that
would give them more weight in debt negotiations.
   Duarte, 62, called on the OAS delegates to approve a resolution
``that emphatically condemns terrorism and delegitimizes those who
seek political power by violence and terror.''
   He accused leftist rebels waging a 9-year-old war against the
U.S.-backed government of resorting to terrorism.
   Duarte is suffering from liver cancer. Because of weight and hair
loss during chemotherapy, he appeared haggard but he spoke
emphatically in a clear, strong voice.
   Doctors said when the cancer was diagnosed in June that Duarte
had between six and 18 months to live.
   Duarte asked delegates to provide ``moral support'' for an
eventual summit meeting of Central American presidents that would
try to breathe new life into a regional peace process begun in
August 1987.
   ``What is at stake is not just peace in Central America, but the
security of the entire continent,'' he said.
   Diplomats from the five Central American countries _ Guatemala,
El Salvador, Honduras, Nicaragua and Costa Rica _ have been trying
without success for months to set a date and place for a summit.
There has been talk in recent days of a summit before the end of the
year, but nothing has been formalized.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
