<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EagleRescue     11-14 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eagle Rescue,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Golden Eagle Rescued From Gulf Of Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASS CHRISTIAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at a Gulf Coast wildlife
center are trying to nurse back to health an ailing golden eagle,
not normally seen in Mississippi, which was rescued after it plunged
into the Gulf of Mexico.
   Shrimp boat workers said they saw the eagle fly too close to the
water and hit a wave Saturday. Capt. Charlie Schmidt of the Theresa
Maria said he assumed the eagle would fly away on its own, but it
was still there when the ship sailed past the spot an hour later.
   The shrimpers scooped up the bird and a fishing official called
the Wildlife Rehabilitation Center, said Robin Berry, director of
the center.
   ``He was in bad shape, very weak and thin,'' Berry said. The
eagle, with an estimated wing span of about five feet, weighed only
about six pounds.
   The eagle was fed liquids through a tube Sunday and was
improving, Berry said.
   Berry and her staff hadn't figured out what weakened the eagle.
``He might have eaten a poisoned rat,'' she said.
</TEXT>
