<DOCNO> AP881114-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1726EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola     11-14 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Talks Extended As Pretoria Complains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa expressed dissatisfaction Monday at
the pace of talks on peace for southwestern Africa as negotiators
agreed to a second unforeseen day of meetings.
   Cuba, Angola and South Africa continued to search for a
breakthrough in closed-door bilateral talks mediated by U.S.
Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker.
   South African spokesman Roland Darroll said the latest round,
originally set for three days ending Sunday, would continue Tuesday.
   But he added: ``It seems the more time there is, the more people
take their time.''
   Negotiators agreed to extend the talks after a U.S. delegate, in
an upbeat assessment, cited progress on the issue of a Cuban troop
withdrawal from Angola. In Washington, State Department spokeswoman
Phyllis Oakley echoed his optimism. ``We're hopeful that agreement
can be reached,'' she said.
   But a senior South African diplomat cautioned Monday, ``There's
still a lot of ground to cover.''
   ``We are waiting for more complete replies'' from Cuba and Angola
on a U.S. peace plan put forward in October, said the official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He described progress as ``glacial.''
   ``Things are on track, but on a very slow track,'' he said.
   The main remaining issue in the peace effort begun in May is
setting a timetable for withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops backing
Angola's Marxist government against South African- and
U.S.-supported UNITA rebels. The other component is a framework to
end South Africa's 73-year control of South-West Africa, or Namibia.
   In New York, the U.N. General Assembly took up a resolution
Monday condemning Pretoria's rule of Namibia. Passage of the measure
was considered certain.
   It calls on South Africa not to link Namibian independence to
``irrelevant and extraneous issues, particularly the presence of
Cuban forces in Angola.''
   Debate was expected to last until Wednesday. Last year, a
virtually identical resolution passed with no opposition. The United
States, Western Europe and Nordic countries abstained.
   The resolution calls on all nations to obey international
boycotts against South Africa, including the mandatory arms embargo.
   It urges member states to increase aid to the South-West Africa
People's Organization, the guerrilla movement which the United
Nations recognizes as the sole representative of Namibia.
   The United States considers SWAPO a terrorist organization and
withholds a small part of its U.N. dues that would be used to fund
SWAPO activities.
   In Geneva on Sunday, a senior U.S. delegate said negotiators have
``never been closer to agreement.''
   However, he added: ``If people can't go the extra mile, you could
see a rapid change of atmosphere.''
   A U.S. proposal reportedly calls for a gradual two-year
withdrawal. Cuba seeks a 2{-year timetable.
   Target date for the start of the pullout is said to be Jan. 1,
the same day a U.N.-supervised process for bringing independence to
Namibia would begin.
   The former German colony Pretoria took over after World War I
lies between South Africa and Angola.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
