<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1803EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Smothers     11-14 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Smothers,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Sqabbling Is Real</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: For release 6 p.m. EST; Time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The on-stage squabbling that has been the
basis of the Smothers Brothers appeal for 30 years isn't an act, the
brothers insist.
   ``Sometimes, we have an argument right on stage and people don't
know it. They think it's part of the act,'' Dick Smothers said.
   Dick and Tom Smothers began performing as a folk-singing team
when they were students at San Diego State University 30 years ago.
They moved on to the stage and television. Their latest effort is a
series of six specials they did for CBS this season.
   ``What we write comes out of what we really see happening between
them,'' staff writer John Hadley says in the Nov. 19 issue of TV
Guide magazine.
   ``Being at odds with each other has kept them alive and kept them
working,'' he said.
   Tom, 51, plays the sly, but childlike, brother on stage. Dick,
50, said it is ``hard work being his brother'' because Tom ``is a
meticulous taskmaster.''
   ``I go to parties and I want to make sure they run OK, so I
rearrange the furniture,'' said Tom.
   Tom also believes his brother would not be on stage with him if
he had an alternative.
   ``Dickie would never be in show business if I hadn't needed a
singer,'' said Tom. ``And, if he had a choice and could live
comfortably, he'd just as soon be out of it.''
</TEXT>
