<HEAD>Tests Indicate No Heart Disease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tests show Mayor William Hudnut does not have
coronary artery disease but probably needs his heart medicine
adjusted, a spokesman said Monday.
   Hudnut, 56, in his 13th year as mayor, has been taking medication
since last year to regulate his heart's rhythm.
   Spokesman David Arland said Hudnut's doctor did a series of tests
to check for a blocked coronary artery after X-rays from a treadmill
test last week indicated a possible problem.
   ``The treadmill test was a false positive,'' Arland said. ``He
had complained of shortness of breath and slight chest pains. He may
need an adjustment of his heart medication.''
   Arland said Hudnut was happy, relieved and feeling better.
