<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Escape     11-14 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Escape,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Vows To Tighten Security After Rebel Commander's Escape</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino vowed Monday
to tighten prison security after a communist rebel commander and his
wife escaped when they were released temporarily from military
detention to attend a party.
   Mrs. Aquino said the government cannot allow its efforts to crush
the 19-year-old communist rebellion ``to go wasted.''
   Romulo Kintanar and his wife escaped from Camp Crame,
headquarters of the Philippine national police force, after
attending a party Saturday in another part of the compound.
   Kintanar, 41, had commanded the 25,000-member communist New
People's Army when he and his 38-year-old wife, Gloria, were
arrested in March. He is believed to be the chief organizer of
assassination squads responsible for killing scores of police
officers and soldiers.
   Officials said Kintanar and his wife slipped away from a birthday
party for Lt. Col. Robelito Comilang, a former prison warden.
   Comilang said he invited Kintanar, his wife and other prisoners
to the party at his home at Camp Crame.
   Kintanar was released from his cell about noon and escorted to
Comilang's home, according to Brig. Gen. Pantaleon Dumlao.
   Kintanar and the guard left the party about two hours later and
returned to the prison compound, Dumlao said. Kintanar, his wife and
another rebel prisoner then returned to Comilang's party,
accompanied by the guard, then slipped away.
   Landrito said he did not give permission for Kintanar to leave
his cell the second time because ``I was in my office, sleeping.''
   Relatives of Kintanar's wife claimed the military may have
murdered the couple and fabricated the story as a cover-up.
   Because of the escape, Comilang was placed under house arrest. He
also was relieved of his military duties, as was Gen. Renato de
Villa, the military chief, acting warden Maj. Benjamin Landrito and
camp commander Col. Percival Adiong, according to police spokesman
Lt. Col. Cresencio Maralit. He said three prison guards were
arrested.
   ``I will give instructions that we have to have stricter rules
there,'' Mrs. Aquino told reporters. ``We cannot allow all of our
efforts to go wasted simply because of the laxity.''
   Kintanar, who was held in the maximum-security section of the
camp, was the third prominent opponent of the government to escape
custody since April.
   ``There has been more damage in this case to the credibility of
the entire government machinery because you can imagine soldiers and
policemen in the field reacting, `Why will we risk our lives
catching these people? It's so easy for them to escape from
confinement,''' said Sen. Ernesto Maceda, chairman of the Senate
defense committee.
   About 160 communist rebels and soldiers arrested in coup plots
are held at Camp Crame.
   In April, Lt. Col. Gregorio Honasan, leader of the August 1987
coup attempt, escaped from a prison ship in Manila Bay with the help
of his guards. He remains at large.
   A few days later, a Honasan aide, Lt. Col. Eduardo Matillano,
escaped after being allowed to leave his cell to visit a dentist. He
was recaptured in September.
</TEXT>
