<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     11-14 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Group Formed To Press For Multiparty System in Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new group has been formed to press for
multiparty elections with non-communist candidates and to demand
that Hungary renegotiate its ties with the Warsaw Pact, official
media reported Monday.
   The Federation of Free Democrats was launched Sunday at a meeting
of a network of independent political, ecological, religious and
youth groups, according to a participant at the session in
Budapest's Jurta Theater.
   The network, which was established in May, on Sunday split into
two groups _the new federation and a second group that will take a
less active political role, said the participant, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The formation of the new group also was reported by the
government daily Magyar Hirlap and the state news agency MTI.
   Last week, the government approved a draft law that would
legalize independent groups and trade unions, and could pave the way
for a multiparty system. The Communist Party has been Hungary's only
political party since it assumed power in 1948.
   However, Justice Minister Kalman Kulcsar said that a new law
governing alternative political parties probably would not be ready
until 1990, when a new constitution is to be issued.
   The network of democratic groups formed in May was a loose
organization of about 1,500 individuals who supported democracy, but
was not organized as a purely political group or the nucleus of a
new political party.
   The Federation of Free Democrats intends to ``give its members
some kind of organizing framework with a clear political purpose,''
said the participant.
   The Federation of Free Democrats is headed by a nine-member
committee, including the dissident Ferenc Koeszeg, sociologist
Ottilia Solt, historian Miklos Szabo, pastor Gabor Ivanyi and a
worker, Istvan Vass.
   The new group is calling for the democratic right of association,
the organization of alternative political parties and representation
in Parliament, according to a draft program.
   The group also demands that Hungary renegotiate its ties with the
Soviet-led Warsaw Pact military alliance and the withdrawal of the
Soviet Union's estimated 65,000 troops from Hungary.
   Another group that has said it intends to support candidates for
Parliament is the Hungarian Democratic Forum, which was established
in September.
</TEXT>
