<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Iraq     11-14 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace in 10 Days if Iran's Willing, Says Iraqi President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi President Saddam Hussein said Monday
his country and Iran could sign a peace treaty in 10 days if Tehran
is willing, the official Iraqi News Agency reported.
   ``The phase of interference in the internal affairs of others is
over,'' INA quoted Hussein as saying.
   ``In 10 days, everyone (Iran and Iraq) could be at peace if the
will and decisions were there,'' he told soldiers in Baghdad
receiving medals for valor.
   Peace talks between Iran and Iraq stalled Aug. 25, five days
after a United Nations-sponsored cease-fire halted fighting in the
8-year gulf war.
   Talks in Geneva recessed Friday and are expected to resume soon.
   Both sides blame the other for a deadlock over troop withdrawals
to the pre-war border.
   Iran insists the southern border is the middle of the
Shatt-Al-Arab waterway, as defined by a 1975 treaty.
   Iraq abrogated the treaty a few days before it invaded Iran in
September 1980 and insists the border runs along the eastern,
Iranian bank.
   Tehran radio reported Monday that the two countries agreed to
repatriate more than 1,500 sick or disabled prisoners over a
three-week period starting Sunday.
   The exchange will be organized by the International Committee of
the Red Cross, which is waiting for Iran and Iraq to provide lists
of all other disabled prisoners for another exchange beginning Dec.
5.
   The Red Cross estimates there are more than 100,000 prisoners.
   Hussein said Iraq has been seeking peace since 1985 and would
have accepted the U.N. cease-fire resolution when it was approved on
July 20, 1987.
   Iran equivocated until July this year, when it unconditionally
accepted after a series of battlefield defeats.
   ``We are still discussing how to fix the cease-fire,'' Hussein
said. ``We want the cease-fire to be fixed so that no spark could
flare up and cause us a problem.''
   He did not indicate whether Baghdad is prepared to soften its
stand in the talks.
   But he stressed: ``We are continuing the way of peace and believe
in it, unless they (the Iranians) attack us. Then, we would mobilize
120 army divisions. But, by God's will, this will not happen.''
   Iraq's military currently has 54 divisions and an estimated 1
million men under arms.
   Tehran claims Iraq occupies 386 square miles of Iranian territory
in the central border sector.
   ``Iran is not short of land, space and free waters,'' INA quoted
Hussein as saying. ``Let each of us live freely in his own homeland,
without interference in internal affairs.''
   His country already is preparing for peace. In Baghdad on Monday,
French Foreign Trade Minister Jean-Marie Rausch conferred with Iraqi
officials on bilateral trade and France's participation in Iraq's
post-war reconstruction, INA reported.
   It said delegates from the Soviet Union, Romania and West Germany
also are in Baghdad discussing cooperation on several industrial
projects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
