<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AeromexicoTrial     11-14 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aeromexico Trial,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aeromexico Suit Mistrial Declared</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge declared a mistrial Monday in
a civil suit aimed at assigning blame for the Aeromexico jetliner
disaster two years ago.
   U.S. District Judge David V. Kenyon agreed with government
attorneys that jurors were tainted when an attorney for the pilot of
a small plane said the pilot may have died two minutes before the
crash over Cerritos on Aug. 31, 1986. The crash killed 82 people.
   The judge noted that the trial had just begun with opening
statements and no evidence had been presented. Kenyon said he did
not want to take objecting parties``kicking and screaming'' into the
rest of the trial.
   ``I see some prejudice, some very genuine prejudice, to certain
parties,'' Kenyon said, saying the opening statement of an attorney
could ``have had a lasting effect and would be on the mind'' of
jurors.
   U.S. Justice Department lawyer Steven J. Riegel made a mistrial
motion which was denied last week.
   Kenyon said then that trial could continue, but told jurors they
could not consider the heart attack scenario presented by attorneys
for the family of small plane pilot William Kramer.
   But on Monday, Riegel re-introduced his motion and after four
hours of arguments the judge reconsidered and declared the mistrial.
   In the new trial, jurors may not hear anything about an alleged
incapacity or death of Kramer before the accident, Kenyon also
ruled. A pool of 100 prospective jurors will be called Tuesday to
select a new panel.
</TEXT>
