<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--California Earthquakes,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Light Quakes Shake South Peninsula Area; No Damage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTOLA VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three light earthquakes shook
Northern California Monday, but there were no reports of damage or
injuries, the U.S. Geological Service said.
   The three quakes appeared to be centered on the San Andreas
Fault, said Pat Jorgenson.
   The first quake struck at 10:58 a.m. and registered 2.4 on the
Richter scale, said Jorgenson. The second was at 11:21 with a 3.0
magnitude and the final one hit at 11:52 a.m., registering 2.75.
   All three were in a location about 30 miles south of San
Francisco.
   The open-ended Richter scale is a measure of the energy released
by an earthquake.
   A quake of 3.5 can cause slight damage in populated areas, while
a quake of 6.0 can cause severe damage.
</TEXT>
