<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JFKAssassination     11-14 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-JFK Assassination,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PBS Special Questions Second Gunman Theories in JFK Assassination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amid a new wave of books, TV specials and
docudramas that have revived the specter of a conspiracy in the John
F. Kennedy assassination, a public television broadcast this week
casts doubt on many of the second gunman theories.
   The JFK segment of the ``Nova'' series, narrated by former CBS
News anchorman Walter Cronkite, used available evidence _ and in
some cases new scientific analyses _ to test theories that a second
gunman shot at Kennedy and that the wounds were altered to hide
evidence of a conspiracy.
   The program, which for the first time gained access to autopsy
photos of the slain president, concludes only that the available
evidence, even when put through modern-day scientific testing, is
inconclusive on whether there was a second gunman.
   The one-hour Public Broadcasting Service special, ``Who Shot
President Kennedy,'' was scheduled to air Tuesday night, one week
before the 25th anniversary of the slaying.
   Producer Robert Richter received permission from the Kennedy
family to show 52 color and black-and-white autopsy photos to four
doctors who were part of the emergency medical team that struggled
to save the president in Dallas.
   Each of the four doctors examined the photos individually behind
closed doors at the National Archives, where evidence from the JFK
assassination is stored. They concluded that the wounds looked the
same as they did when the president arrived at Parkland Memorial
Hospital in Dallas on Nov. 22, 1963.
   The testimony strikes directly at a cornerstone of the second
gunman theory: that Kennedy was shot from the front by a gunman on
the infamous grassy knoll as well as from behind by Lee Harvey
Oswald and that bullet wounds were altered somewhere between Dallas
and the Washington autopsy to make it appear as though entrance
wounds were actually exit wounds.
   Nova received family permission to view the original autopsy
photos only by agreeing not to show them during the broadcast, but
the program does show, for the first time, several graphic autopsy
shots of the slain president. Richter said they were copies obtained
by an outside source whom he declined to identify.
   Richter used a computer model of Dealey Plaza to show how the
much-maligned ``single-bullet theory'' embraced by the Warren
Commission could be correct.
   According to Richter's computer model, a single bullet fired from
the sixth floor of the nearby Texas School Book Depository, where
Oswald was perched, could have traveled through Kennedy's neck, if
he had been bending slightly forward, and go through then-Gov. John
Connally of Texas.
   But the surgeon who operated on Connally in Dallas, interviewed
on the program, doubted that the bullet could have done that damage
and remain nearly intact. The bullet, recovered later at the
hospital, had little damage.
   Nova producers also had a fuzzy photograph, which some say showed
a gunman on the grassy knoll, analyzed by scientists at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology and Polaroid Corp. The
analysis was inconclusive.
   The program did not explore other theories that say Oswald was
the lone gunman but that he and Jack Ruby, the nightclub owner who
shot Oswald, were part of an organized crime or Cuban plot to kill
the president.
   Cronkite said additional tests on the bullet could be helpful to
formulate a more conclusive opinion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1917EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HeavyWater     11-14 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heavy Water,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Water Exports To Be Outlawed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OLE WALBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norway is moving to outlaw exports of heavy
water as evidence mounts that material sold for peaceful research
has been diverted to make nuclear weapons.
   Foreign Minister Thorvald Stoltenberg has told parliament he was
drafting a bill to halt the sales, charging that other countries had
failed to control how the water was used.
   ``Our experience from the concrete events now being pursued shows
that control systems in some countries are being circumvented
without those responsible facing punishment,'' Stoltenberg said
Thursday.
   Allegations that Norway had an unwitting role in producing
nuclear weaponry proved embarrassing for a nation known as the
distributor of the Nobel Peace Prize.
   A Norwegian TV documentary last month said as much as two-thirds
of the heavy water Norway has sold may have been used in reactors
for weapons production.
   The Norsk Hydro A.S. chemical company has been making heavy water
for 50 years as a byproduct of its ammonia fertilizer production. It
has sold 450 tons of the material, which looks like ordinary water,
to 38 countries.
   Heavy water, or deuterium oxide, is used as a coolant in nuclear
reactors. But it also can be used to enable reactors to run on
natural uranium rather than enriched uranium fuel, and to convert it
into plutonium for possible use in nuclear weapons.
   A law banning exports would be mostly a symbolic gesture, since
Norsk Hydro has reduced its output of heavy water from a peak of 20
tons annually to less than two.
   The government has been under fire for losing track of its
shipments at least three times and failing to ensure that it was
used for peaceful purposes.
   Norway sold 15 tons to a West Germany company in 1983, but it
never arrived at its stated destination. The Norwegians traced it to
Basel, Switzerland, then lost it.
   Last week investigators confirmed the shipment was flown to
Bombay, where India has a nuclear facility. It apparently had
arrived at the same time as a Soviet shipment, making it difficult
to find, state prosecutors said.
   Norway refuses to sell to India, which exploded its first nuclear
device in 1974, because it refuses to sign the nuclear
non-proliferation treaty.
   In 1986 Romania received a shipment of 12{ tons which, according
to Norwegian press reports, was later sent to Israel. Romania is the
only Soviet bloc country with full diplomatic ties with Jerusalem.
   In 1959 Norway sold 20 tons to Israel for research at a reactor
it was then building in Dimona. It received an additional ton in
1970.
   Claims by a former Dimona technician in 1986 that nuclear
explosives were being produced at the desert facility prompted
Norway to demand its contractual right to inspect its goods. Israel
refused to open the Dimona plant to outsiders.
   The technician, Mordechai Vanunu, told a London newspaper that
Israel had stockpiled up to 100 warheads, which would make it the
sixth-largest nuclear power in the world. Vanunu was sentenced to 18
years in prison on treason charges for his disclosures.
   After months of negotiation, Israel and Norway initialed an
agreement under which the Norwegians would be allowed to inspect the
nine tons which remain.
   But some critics have suggested the agreement was an empty
gesture, even if Norway could determine whether its heavy water had
been used to manufacture bombs.
   ``After all, we cannot sent troops to Israel to get the water
back,'' said Kaare Willoch, chairman of parliament's foreign
relations committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1918EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BuriedBodies-Victims     11-14 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Buried Bodies-Victims,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Victims Are Unidentified, But Officers Have Strong Clues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Buried Bodies Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The seven bodies unearthed from shallow
graves around Dorothea Montalvo Puente's neatly kept Victorian
rooming house haven't been identified, but detectives have a good
idea who they may be.
   Puente, 59, was known to open her eight-bedroom home on a
tree-lined street a half-mile from the Capitol to retirees, the
homeless, the physically or mentally disabled and others on limited
incomes.
   She was described as a shy and kindly widow, willing to take the
needy into her big house filled with candles and statues of the
Virgin Mary and Jesus.
   Puente took street people, transients, elderly and disabled
people, cleaned them up, fed them and appeared to give them loving
care, said Peggy Nickerson, a social worker who sent 19 people there
over two years.
   Nickerson also encouraged churches to give Puente money to help
her in her good work at Christmas.
   Most of the boarders, according to neighbors, were older men,
some with mental disabilities.
   Puente also arranged to have herself designated as payee on the
disability checks of at least one of her now-missing boarders,
authorities say. She is suspected of collecting welfare or
disability benefits for other boarders as well.
   Nickerson said she stopped sending clients to Puente about three
months ago, after she heard Puente verbally abusing one boarder.
   Nickerson said it isn't unusual for the transient clients she
works with to move on without leaving word, and she was not
suspicious initially when boarders she had placed in Puente's home
vanished.
   But it was Nickerson's call to police, plus a neighbor's
independent report about a different missing person, that brought
detectives to the house Friday.
   By Monday afternoon, seven bodies had been discovered. Most
appear to have been buried for several months, and none of have been
positively identified yet.
   ``We may have to search for dental records, medical records and
other things to find out who these people are,'' police Lt. Joe
Enloe said.
   To help, Nickerson has provided the names of her missing clients,
and Peter D'Anna, district manager of the Social Security
Administration, said his staff would search records to see if
recipients had lived at the house or had signed benefits over to
Puente.
   Nickerson and D'Anna said it is not uncommon for persons such as
the kind of boarders in Puente's home to have welfare, Social
Security or disability checks cashed for them by another party.
   No charges have been filed against Puente, but an arrest warrant
for investigation of murder has been issued for her. Her whereabouts
are unknown.
</TEXT>
