<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle-Senate     11-14 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle-Senate,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vice President-Elect to Give Senate Successor Seniority Edge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle announced
Monday he intends to resign his Senate seat in time to give his
successor a jump in seniority over the new class of lawmakers being
sworn in Jan. 3..
   Quayle said he had ``no recommendations'' to make on a successor
when he met privately with Indiana Gov. Robert Orr, who will make
the appointment. ``I evaluated everyone from top to bottom,'' he
told reporters afterward.
   Orr, a Republican, stressed that the decision would be his to
make, and said he and Quayle ``talked about a whole lot of people.
That's confidential.''
   The list of possible successors includes Rep. Dan Coats, a former
aide to Quayle who holds the House seat once occupied by Quayle;
Indiana House Speaker Dan Paul Mannweiler and Mitchell Daniels, a
former White House political director with close ties to Sen.
Richard Lugar.
   Other names mentioned include Marion County prosecutor Steve
Goldsmith; Lt. Gov. John Mutz, who was defeated in the election for
governor last week, and Indianapolis Mayor William Hudnut.
   Others whose names have cropped up include former Indiana
Secretary of State Edwin Simcox, one-time Environmental Protection
Administration chief William Ruckelshaus and Rep. Dan Burton.
   Quayle's wife, Marilyn, has passed up several opportunities to
say whether reports of her interest in the seat are true, although
the vice president-elect told reporters that she intends to issue a
statement shortly.
   Speculation on a new Indiana senator picked up Monday as
President-elect George Bush said in Florida that he had ``no
specifics yet'' on the duties Quayle will hold in the new
administration.
   Bush said his campaign pledge that Quayle will head a space
council stands. But he said his wish to have Quayle serve as drug
czar has been complicated by legislation requiring that the head of
the program not hold any other position in the government.
   Officials also announced that Quayle would sit on on Tuesday when
Bush meets with visiting West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   Quayle issued a statement about his Senate seat after his meeting
with Orr, whose appointee will serve until a special election in
November 1990.
   In a brief statement, Quayle seemed to raise the possibility that
Orr would designate a new senator before the post became officially
vacant. Privately, some Republicans with ties to the state have said
they expect an appointment well before the end of the year.
   Orr is expected to meet within the next several days to discuss
the Senate seat with Republican Sen. Richard Lugar, Indiana's senior
senator.
   In a brief statement, Quayle said he told Orr he intends to
resign his seat before Jan. 3, the date incoming senators are sworn
in for the 101st Congress. A new senator sworn in before that date
would have an advantage over other newcomers when it came to
parceling out the perquisites of office.
   It also could translate to better committee assignments and in
time, a larger staff.
   Quayle's statement said the effective day of his Senate
resignation ``would probably be Jan. 1st or 2nd. Should Governor Orr
name someone to fill the Senate seat prior to the first of the year,
the vice president-elect has pledged that he and his Senate staff
will work with the appointee to make the transition a smooth one.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
