<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShootingRampage     11-14 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shooting Rampage,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dedication Ceremony May Have Triggered Interstate Shooting Spree</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Associates of a former administrator of a
group home for the retarded had feared that he might seek revenge
for his dismissal, but didn't anticipate the violent reaction that
left two people dead.
   ``People thought there would be some attempt to hurt people, but
not physically. Most people thought he would sue,'' said Peter
Kowalski, executive director of John F. Murphy Homes, the non-profit
organization that took over the group home in Mechanic Falls after
it emerged from bankruptcy.
   Authorities said Alan Matterson, embittered by being fired 18
months ago for mismanagement, went on a 3{-hour rampage that started
late Saturday in New Hampshire and ended early Sunday when he killed
himself with a shot in the head while fleeing police in Maine.
   Also killed was a state official whose duties involved regulation
of community care facilities. And three people were wounded: another
state official, a former bookkeeper for the Mechanic Falls home and
the bookkeeper's sister-in-law.
   The shootings, which began Saturday night in Milton Mills, N.H.,
came on the eve of an open house marking the dedication of Main
Street Mechanic Falls, as the group home for 14 retarded people is
now known.
   Kowalski said Monday that advertisements for Sunday's open house
had appeared in local newspapers and it was likely that Matterson,
36, of Cumberland, was aware of the event.
   ``That may have been the straw that broke the camel's back,''
said Janet Tillson, a nursing supervisor who became interim director
of the group home after Matterson's dismissal.
   ``I don't know whether it was coincidence or whether it was one
of the events that might have caused him to crack. That may be one
of the questions we never know the answer to,'' State Police
spokesman Steve McCausland said.
   The shootings took place at the victims' homes, spread over a
distance of 75 miles, as part of a methodically executed plan
apparently motivated by a desire for vengeance, McCausland said.
   Matterson was armed with a pair of .44-caliber revolvers and had
80 rounds of ammunition in his car, said Detective Timothy Culbert.
Investigators didn't know where he was headed when a Gardiner police
officer spotted his car and gave chase, but Culbert said he may have
been stalking other state officials he felt were reponsible for
destroying his career.
   ``He didn't have a list per se. He didn't have anything written
down,'' Culbert said.
   Details about Matterson's activities over the past year were
sketchy, although authorities said he had been living with his
parents in Cumberland at the time of the shootings. The parents
could not be reached for comment; their telephone number is unlisted.
   State officials and former associates said Matterson was a poor
administrator who was forced to relinquish previous jobs because of
his poor management skills.
   Kowalski said Matterson was regarded by employees at the Mechanic
Falls home as ``very, very introverted, a loner who did not
associate with the people around him.''
   Culbert said Matterson's life had come apart under the strain of
his dismissal and the prospect that he would no longer be able to
find a job in the field in which he had been trained.
   ``This was his whole life, to run a nursing home or a mental
retardation center. He had the certification and the schooling,''
Culbert said. ``When they took it away from him, they took away
everything.''
</TEXT>
