<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Logan     11-14 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Logan,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Memorial Tribute to Career of Broadway and Film Director</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a memorial by turns lighthearted, sentimental
and poignant, colleagues and admirers recalled Monday the career of
Joshua Logan, who directed, produced or wrote some of America's most
honored plays and films.
   ``He was among the greats of the American theater,'' President
Reagan said in a message from the White House, mentioning among
Logan's achievements ``South Pacific,'' ``Mister Roberts,'' ``and my
own favorite, `This is the Army.'''
   Reagan had a role in a movie version of that one, a 1942 G.I.
show. ``And it took him right to the White House, as you all
remember,'' wisecracked Arlene Francis, who read the president's
tribute from the stage of the Shubert Theater, where ``Celebrating
Josh'' played for an audience of about 1,000.
   Logan died in New York on July 12 at age 79.
   James Stewart, a classmate of Logan's at Princeton in the late
1920s, said, ``I will always be grateful with all my heart to Josh
because he gave me my acting career.''
   Stewart said it all came about in a few minutes, after receiving
his degree in architecture with every intention of returning for
graduate work, but letting Logan sweet-talk him into spending the
summer with the University Players.
   ``I said fine and I've been an actor ever since,'' said Stewart.
   Joanne Woodward said her life was changed when Logan hired her in
1952 to understudy Kim Stanley and Janice Rule in the Broadway
production of ``Picnic,'' during which ``I learned more about acting
that one time than the rest of my life.'' She also met Paul Newman,
her husband, who had a small role and understudied the lead.
   In a film clip that opened the tribute, Logan called himself
``one of the world's luckiest men.''
   ``I was lucky enough to be born at the right time so that I could
work with the greatest composers and lyricists and book writers, in
the golden age of American musical comedy ... golden because you
could understand the words of the lyrics and when you understood
them they were worth understanding.''
</TEXT>
