<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Scotus-Commissioners     11-14 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Commissioners,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Supreme Court Rejects Challenge To Leon County Commission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black leaders said they were
disappointed Monday after the U.S. Supreme Court refused to review a
lawsuit filed over the composition of the Leon County Commission.
   ``It would have been a precedent-setting case,'' said Henry
Lewis, a pharmacology professor and the county's first and only
black commissioner.
   Even though Lewis said the current system _ revised since the
original lawsuit was filed _ worked, he noted that reapportionment
was coming up in four years and there was a danger that blacks could
be short-changed.
   Anita Davis, president of the Tallahassee branch of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, also said Monday
that, currently ``the good outweighs the bad.''
   In 1983, when the NAACP sued, Leon County's five commissioners
were elected at-large. The lawsuit contended that system illegally
diluted the voting strength of black residents, who comprised 25
percent of the population of Leon County, which is Tallahassee and
the surrounding area.
   The plaintiffs urged that the commission consist of five members,
each elected from a district.
   When the commissioners revamped the system in 1986, however, it
adopted a plan that provides for five commissioners from districts
and two at-large.
   ``So we got part of what we wanted ... and it seems to be fair,''
Davis said Monday.
   But the NAACP argued that the plan lacked the status of a
legislative enactment, in part because it was not approved by
referendum. It said Florida law required such county reapportionment
plans to be approved by the voters.
   ``The thing is the county should have at least offered the
opportunity for the electorate to decide ... but they did not,''
Davis said. ``They just took it upon themselves.''
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the current plan,
and on Monday, the Supreme Court, with one dissenting vote, left
that ruling intact. The votes of at least four justices are required
to grand such review, and only Justice Harry A. Blackum voted to
hear arguments in the case.
   The appeals court said the plan adopted by the board of
commissioners was ``legislatively enacted,'' in effect similar to
one approved by a state Legislature.
   ``A broad definition of `legislatively enacted' leaves
reapportionment to be performed by a legislative body of the state
rather than the federal judiciary,'' the appeals court said.
   Davis said she did not know if the NAACP would pursue the matter.
   The new plan led to election in November 1986 of six whites and
one black. Commissioners generally serve for four years, although
some members are serving two-year terms.
   Gayle Nelson, a commissioner since 1978, said she was relieved
the legal action was finished. ``I think that any time you have a
lawsuit behind you you're always glad,'' she said.
   ``I think it's the best of both worlds,'' she said in defense of
the current system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
