<HEAD>Major Fire Said To Disrupt Cuban Phone Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A telephone service fire in Havana over the
weekend shut down Cuba's overseas phone and telegraph lines, the
State Department said Monday.
   ``We have no estimate when service will resume,'' Ben Justesen, a
department press officer, said. ``We don't have any informatin on
the cause of the fire at all.''
   The Justesen said the damage prevented telephone contact between
the department and the U.S. interests section in Havana, which is
part of the Swiss embassy.
   ``We have no information on the fire's effect on domestic Cuban
service,'' he said.
   Earlier this year, the U.S. Departments of Treasury and Commerce
authorized licenses for the use of American equipment to replace an
international telephone cable in Cuba.
   The project was not intended to improve domestic service.
   Some employees of the American Telephone and Telegraph Co. were
believed to be headed for Cuba to do some of the work, or may
actually have reached the country. However the fire was not related
to the project, Justesen said.
