<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-14 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snowstorm In West, Headed For Northern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm spread heavy snow Monday in the mountains of the West,
with generous rain at lower altitudes, and the snow was expected to
move to the northern Plains.
   The first heavy snowfall of the season occurred in the Sierra
Nevada near Lake Tahoe. Accumulations ranged from 6 to 8 inches
around lake level to around 2 feet at higher elevations. Donner
Summit, Calif., had 23 inches by morning and Echo Summit, Calif.,
had 18 inches.
   Idaho also got substantial snow. Bald Mountain got 22 inches of
snow with 13 inches on the valley below, and Sun Valley got 9 inches
with 11 inches on surrounding mountain tops.
   Winter storm warnings were posted for parts of Montana, Wyoming,
Idaho, Utah, Arizona and Colorado. Winter storm watches were posted
into Tuesday for western South Dakota.
   Up to 6 inches of snow fell in the mountains of northern Utah,
and a teen-ager was killed when her car went out of control on ice
and snow and careened into an empty school bus.
   Ahead of the storm, rain was reported in northeastern South
Dakota, with snow falling in southwestern North Dakota.
   Generous rain fell across parts of central and eastern
California. Two 2 inches was measured from Sunday morning into
Monday morning below 5,000 feet near Blue Canyon, and 1.3 inches at
Shelter Cove along the northwest coast.
   Up to an inch of rain fell in the Los Angeles area early Monday,
and a pregnant woman and her unborn child were killed in one of the
many highway pileups attributed in part to wet pavement.
   There were scattered power outages in California, and about 3,000
Bakersfield High School students were given the day off because of a
lingering blackout.
   Around the storm, wind gusted to 55 mph at Casper, Wyo., and to
53 mph at Laramie, Wyo. Wind gusted to 40 mph over the mountain and
desert areas of southern California.
   Elsewhere, widely scattered showers developed during the morning
along the central Gulf Coast.
   In sharp contrast to the winterlike weather elsewhere, Galveston,
Texas, reached a record high of 81 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 20
degrees at Cut Bank, Mont., to 90 at Harlingen and McAllen, Texas.
Monday's morning low was 13 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   For Tuesday, the storm in the West was forecast to move from the
central Rockies into the middle Missouri Valley. Widespread snow and
blowing snow were forecast from the Colorado Rockies through the
northern Plains into northern Minnesota. Numerous showers and
thunderstorms were forecast from the middle Mississippi and the
middle and lower Missouri valleys into the southern Plains. Rain was
forecast over the Pacific Northwest.
   Highs in the 20s and 30s were predicted through the northern and
central Rockies into the northern Plains; in the 40s and 50s from
the northern Pacific Coast into the Great Basin of Nevada and
western Utah, and the southern Rockies, and from the Great Lakes
into the mid Atlantic states and New England; in the 60s from the
central California coast into the desert Southwest; in the 60s or
70s across much of the nation east of the Mississippi River and
south of the mid Atlantic states; in the 70s over southeastern
Kansas and southern Missouri into Oklahoma and Arkansas; in the 80s
from the central Gulf Coast into Florida; and from the mid 80s to
lower 90s over central and eastern Texas into the lower Rio Grande
Valley.
</TEXT>
