<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IRAInquest     11-14 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IRA Inquest,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inquest Into IRA Slayings Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coroner heading an inquest
into the 1982 slayings of three unarmed IRA guerrillas refused
Monday to order testimony from three police officers involved in the
shootings.
   The inquest into the slayings opened Monday before an 11-member
jury sitting in Craigavon, 19 miles southwest of Belfast.
   The jury is to establish the circumstances surrounding the
shooting deaths of Gervase McKerr, Eugene Toman and Sean Burns. The
Irish Republican Army has acknowledged the three as members.
   An hour after the hearing began, a lawyer for the family of
McKerr, 31, walked out in protest when coroner James Elliott refused
to summon three officers to testify.
   Attorney Pat Finnucane said he would ask the Northern Ireland
High Court to order the officers to answer questions at the inquest.
The officers were involved in the shooting but a Belfast court
acquitted them of murder charges.
   Elliott said the officers would present statements but could not
be compelled to testify. Finnucane then left, saying the ruling
allowed the officers ``to have their cake and eat it.'' He said the
McKerr family had instructed him to appeal to the High Court.
   The three IRA men were shot and killed in a police ambush on Nov.
11, 1982, as they drove through County Armagh, a hotbed of guerrilla
activity.
   Three more unarmed Roman Catholics, two of them guerrillas and
one apparently an innocent teen-ager, died in unclear circumstances
in two more police ambushes in County Armagh over the next month.
   The overwhelmingly Catholic IRA is fighting to expell the British
from Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland and unite it with the
Irish Republic.
   Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King, Britain's top official in
the province, has barred the inquest from investigating certain
circumstances of the shootings which he considers would be
``detrimental to the national security.''
   King's order, signed last week, expressed concern about
jeopardizing present and future counter-terrorist operations.
   A screen, heavily guarded by policemen, concealed the identities
of police officers giving testimony, and up to one dozen officers
will be identified only by letters of the alphabet.
   The first to testify was a detective inspector of the Royal
Ulster Constabulary's intelligence-gathering unit, called E4A.
   The officer, identified only as AK, said that at a briefing on
the morning of the shooting intelligence was given of a planned IRA
attack. He said Burns and Toman were wanted for questioning about
terrorist activity, and that it was thought they were armed.
</TEXT>
