<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Gorbachev     11-14 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Gorbachev,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Announces Official Gorbachev Visit to Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev will come to Britain next
month for his first official visit since becoming Soviet leader in
1985, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher announced Monday.
   Mrs. Thatcher said in her annual address to the Lord Mayor's
banquet in the City of London, the capital's financial district,
that the visit of Gorbachev and his wife Raisa was scheduled for
Dec. 12-14.
   ``I am very pleased to announce tonight that Mr. Gorbachev has
accepted our invitation ... and that he and Mrs. Gorbachev will come
here next month,'' she said, ``We shall give them a very warm
welcome.''
   It will be the fifth meeting of the two leaders. Mrs. Thatcher
issued her invitation during a visit to Moscow in April 1987 and
repeated it last December when Gorbachev stopped here briefly on his
way to a summit with President Reagan.
   The prime minister, departing from her prepared text Monday, paid
tribute to the Soviet president and Communist Party chief but said
Soviet ``vested interests'' would prevent immediate change.
   ``We very much welcome what Mr. Gorbachev is trying to achieve in
the Soviet Union but we shouldn't expect change to come quickly,''
she said of Gorbachev's plans for economic and social reform. ``The
vested interests opposed to it are immensely strong, as Mr.
Gorbachev frequently reminds us.'' After ensuring a strong defense
in the West, Mrs. Thatcher declared, it is important to encourage
change and reform in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.
   ``We want to see their countries more prosperous, with their
peoples enjoying a fuller share of life's benefits,'' she said. ``We
must do everything we can to stretch out hands across the divide.''
</TEXT>
