<HEAD>Allstate To Pull Out of Massachusetts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 13th graf `Massachusetts accounts' to CORRECT Allstate's
Mass. total from $154 million to $199 million and to CORRECT that
amount is 2 percent of company's insurance premiums, sted total
revenues.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than a week after California voters threw the
insurance business into turmoil by ordering a rate rollback,
Allstate Insurance Co. announced Monday it is leaving Massachusetts
because of losses and frustration over the state's regulatory
climate.
   The announcement came about a week after several insurers doing
business in California promised to leave the nation's biggest market
after voters approved a measure providing deep cuts in auto and
other insurance rates.
   Kevin Sullivan, director of Allstate's Group Auto division, told
a news conference that Allstate has lost $115 million in
Massachusetts over the past five years, largely due to the ``unique
regulatory environment'' for auto insurance.
   Allstate would be the third major insurer to abandon
Massachusetts, following Kemper Group and Fireman's Fund Insurance
Cos. Two smaller companies also have pulled out.
   Allstate will not renew its license when it expires June 30.
Until then, it will sell new policies and follow through on current
ones until they expire, he said.
   Peter Rice, deputy Massachusetts insurance commissioner, reacted
with ``complete surprise.''
   ``I guess our overall assessment is we think the company was
premature in assessing the effect of the recently passed auto reform
bill on the market,'' Rice said.
   Last week, a bill was signed that will reduce 1989 insurance
premiums by 16 percent, or $400 million, by cracking down on fraud
and abuse, reducing required coverages and limiting the number of
auto cases that end up in court. The legislation comes after
industry court challenges and rate decisions increased Massachusetts
rates by nearly one third since 1986 to among the highest in the
country.
   Sullivan said Allstate saw encouraging improvements in the bill.
But he said it did not restore free markets.
   Massachusetts requires all companies wishing to sell any form of
insurance in the state participate in an open ``high-risk'' auto
insurance pool.
   In addition, state law forbids open competition for automobile
insurance. Instead, the state insurance commissioner annually
calculates a single statewide rate for each category of compulsory
and optional insurance. Only Texas has a similar system.
   Allstate, based in Northbrook, Ill., has 6.6 percent of the
Massachusetts auto insurance market and 5.2 percent of the state's
homeowners insurance market.
   Massachusetts accounts for some $199 million of Allstate's
premiums annually, or about 2 percent of the company's business in
the United States.
   In California, voters last week approved Proposition 103, which
mandates that property and casualty insurers roll their rates back
to a level 20 percent below those in effect on Nov. 8, 1987. In
addition, drivers with good records would get an additional 20
percent off.
   However, the California Supreme Court has delayed the start of
the law while it considers its constitutionality.
   Allstate had no intention to pull out of California, saying the
key difference is that California allows ``open competition,''
Sullivan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
