<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Detentions     11-14 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Detentions,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Chief Deplores 168 Arrests, Detentions And Kidnappings Of UN
Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
said Monday that 168 U.N. workers have been arrested, detained or
kidnapped over in a one-year period, and urged member nations to
guarantee the safety of his staff.
   ``It is painful for me to recall the names of our colleagues,
including Lt. Col. William Higgins and Mr. Alec Collett, who are
still in captivity or missing,'' he said. ``The United Nations has
so far been rendered unable to extend to them the protection which
is their right.''
   Higgins, a U.S. Marine, was abducted Feb. 17 while serving as
chief of a 75-man observer corps attached to the U.N. peacekeeping
force in Lebanon. A group calling itself the Organization of the
Oppressed on Earth, claimed responsibility.
   Collett, a Briton, was seized March 25, 1985, while on assignment
in Lebanon for the U.N. Relief and Works Agency.
   They are among 14 foreigners, including nine Americans, missing
in Lebanon. The hostage held longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press, who was abducted
March 16, 1985.
   The Revolutionary Organization of Socialist Moslems, believed
linked to Palestinian terrorist Abu Nidal, claimed on April 23,
1986, to have hanged Collett in retaliation for the U.S. air raid on
Libya, but no body was found.
   Perez de Cuellar said the 168 U.N. workers were reported
arrested, detained or abducted from July 1, 1987, through June 30,
1988, in 16 member nations or territories.
   ``More than 100 staff or members of their families still remain
imprisoned or detained, have disappeared or died, or are being held
against their will in a country,'' said a report he submitted to the
General Assembly's Fifth Committee, which deals with personnel
problems.
   Most were members of the U.N. Relief and Works Agency detained in
the Israeli-occupied Gaza Strip or West Bank, the report said,
adding that other members of the relief agency's staff are detained
or missing in Syria or held in Lebanon by ``militias or unknown
elements.''
   ``I must emphasize that it is also the responsibility of member
states, individually as well as collectively, to arrange that staff
members may perform their individual duties effectively _ free from
arrest, detention or abduction,'' the secretary-general declared.
   He said governments should guarantee arrested or detained U.N.
employees access to other U.N. staff members within 24 hours and
furnish a written explanation within 48 hours.
   The report, prepared by the Federation of International Civil
Servants' Associations, listed 110 cases of U.N. workers whose
fundamental rights had been violated, including some cases dating to
the 1970s.
   Eight U.N. workers were arrested or prevented from carrying out
their duties in Afghanistan in 1979-1984, including Bismillah Kamkai
of the U.N. Development Program, who was put to death, and Tawakal
Shah of the U.N. Children's Fund, imprisoned and believed dead, the
report said.
   Others include a woman arrested in 1976 during the Argentine
military junta's ``dirty war'' on leftists, still missing and
presumed dead, and two women killed after being arrested in Chile in
1973 and 1976.
</TEXT>
