<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 2059EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Strike     11-14 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Strike,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike By Oil Workers Spreads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More oil workers walked off the job
Monday, joining a strike that has virtually paralyzed the petroleum
refining industry in Latin America's biggest country.
   Some workers at offshore and land wells joined the strike by
refinery workers that began Friday, according to Petrobras, the
state-owned oil monopoly.
   Petrobras spokesman Lucio Pimentel said 80 percent of Brazil's
60,000 oil workers were now on strike ``and our guess is that this
percentage will keep growing.''
   The strike has shut down eight of Brazil's 10 refineries.
Refineries in the Amazon jungle city of Manaus and in
central-eastern Belo Horizonte still were operating, he said.
   Those two refineries have a daily production capacity of close to
135,000 barrels. Brazil's total daily production capacity is 1.5
million barrels of gasoline, diesel oil, cooking gas and other
petroleum products.
   Mauro Costa, of the national strike command, said by telephone
from Brasilia that the Manaus and Belo Horizonte refineries were
being run by night-shift crews who had been on duty Thursday night,
a few hours before the strike began.
   ``They are being forced to remain at their jobs by Petrobras,
which is pressuring them with threats of dismissal,'' Costa said.
Petrobras would not comment on Costa's charges.
   Pimentel estimated Petrobras had enough gasoline and diesel oil
stockpiled to last 10 more days. Cooking gas supplies were
sufficient for five days.
   Brazil consumes about 1.1 million barrels of fuel a day, he added.
   Brazil has 6,987 oil wells on land and 1,088 offshore wells, with
a total output of 560,000 barrels a day. Pimentel said the strike
has cut production by about 100,000 barrels
   Costa said the strikers were demanding a 354 percent pay
increase, while Petrobras offered close to 70 percent. He said oil
workers earn an average of about $300 a month.
   Inflation in Brazil is running at over 1,000 percent a year.
   Last week, Durval Gomes of the Rio de Janeiro Refinery Workers
Union said the strikers were demanding a 154 percent increase and
that the average wage was $1,365 a month.
   ``I don't know where Gomes got those figures but they are
completely wrong,'' Costa said.
</TEXT>
