<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Dollar-Gold     11-14 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rebounds From Last Week's Lows</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Longer version on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar bounced back Monday after a weeklong
slide, supported by the Japanese and U.S. central banks and calming
statements from American officials.
   Last week's slide was brought about by fears that President-elect
George Bush and his advisers wanted the dollar to fall to make U.S.
goods more competitive and shrink the trade deficit.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady helped quell those
suspicions on Sunday by issuing a statement that ``the
administration remains committed to exchange-rate stability.''
   Bush backed Brady on Monday by saying he was fully committed to
the Reagan administration's policy of coordinated actions with other
major countries to stabilize the value of the dollar on foreign
exchange markets.
   In contrast to last week's bearishness, ``People weren't that
sure today if the new administration really wants the dollar down,''
said Peter Wild, a senior trader at Switzerland's Bank Julius Baer &
Co. in New York.
   The dollar began the trading day Monday in Tokyo at 122.55
Japanese, near the Jan. 4 low that was the lowest since modern
exchange rates were established in the late 1940s.
   A rebound began when the Bank of Japan bought dollars in the open
market, traders said. The dollar closed at 123.00 yen. Japanese
Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa and Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi
Sumita said Japanese authorities were ready to strengthen their
intervention efforts if the need arose.
   The dollar continued to rise in Europe and the United States as
trading followed the sun, and on Tuesday morning in Tokyo it opened
at 123.60 yen. Bush's statement and dollar purchases by the Federal
Reserve helped counter attempts by traders to carry the currency
lower, several traders said.
</TEXT>
