<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland     11-14 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mortar Blast At Security Base Wounds Two</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The IRA fired mortar bombs at
the Cookstown security base Monday and wounded two members of the
Ulster Defense Regiment, police said.
   Five civilians who were stunned by shock waves from the blast at
Cookstown, about 53 miles west of Belfast, were taken to a hospital,
they said.
   Police said it was the third mortar attack on the base this year
by the outlawed Irish Republican Army, which is fighting to drive
the British out of the province.
   They said the bombs, launched from tubes in a van parked opposite
the base, wounded two regiment members and did substantial damage to
buildings. Two other bombs stuck in their tubes, apparently failing
to fire, and an army bomb disposal expert defused them.
   The Ulster Defense Regiment is a locally staffed, mainly
part-time security force.
   In Belfast, a police statement said rockets, guns, thousands of
bullets and more than 3,500 pounds of explosives were seized in a
security crackdown in the past five weeks.
   Almost 700,000 vehicles were stopped, 1,100 buildings searched
and 66 people charged with ``terrorist-type offenses,'' including 14
of murder or attempted murder.
   The statement followed complaints from the Roman Catholic
minority of harassment but the police said: ``Searching for arms and
explosives must and will continue. Life is at stake.''
   ``We know that the IRA, north and south of the border, are still
in possession of considerable caches of arms and explosives as a
result of the shipments which came into the (Irish) Republic from
Libya,'' it said.
</TEXT>
