<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PLO-Israel     11-14 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-Israel,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Hail Independence As Beginning Of New Era</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab leaders in the Israeli-occupied lands
hailed Tuesday's declaration of an independent Palestinian state as
the beginning of a new era of political moderation and dialogue.
   Palestinians in the occupied Gaza Strip shot off firecrackers,
flew balloons and raised outlawed Palestinian flags to celebrate the
declaration by the PLO-backed Palestine National Council in Algiers,
the Algerian capital.
   Leaders of the 11-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip also called a general
strike Tuesday to mark independence day.
   The declaration was expected to fuel the uprising, but was not
believed to have much effect on everyday life in the occupied lands.
   The declaration and accompanying resolutions implicitly recognize
Israel's right to exist, meeting some of the conditions the United
States has set for dealing with the PLO in peace talks.
   But Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir reiterated his position
that Israel would never negotiate with the PLO.
   ``It's not a problem of definition and formulations on various
positions,'' Shamir said Monday. ``We'll not negotiate with them
because they are opposed to peace in Israel.''
   Shamir, head of the right-wing Likud bloc, was entrusted Monday
by President Chaim Herzog with forming a coalition government and is
likely to be Israel's leader for the next four years.
   Shamir and other Israeli leaders, including Foreign Minister
Shimon Peres of the left-of-center Labor Party, have said they would
not tolerate a Palestinian state in the occupied lands.
   Shamir also opposes returning Israeli-occupied territory in
exchange for peace and holding peace talks within the framework of
an international peace conference, a forum endorsed by the PLO.
   Instead, Shamir favors direct talks with Arab states on limited
Palestinian autonomy.
   Palestinians in the occupied lands were optimistic that the
independence declaration would lead to a political breakthrough.
   West Bank and Gaza Strip Palestinians repeatedly had expressed
their frustration with PLO leaders who for months were divided over
whether to recognize Israel and renounce terror. The quarreling was
blamed for the Palestinians' failure to translate the uprising into
political gains.
   ``This is the beginning of a new era for the Palestinians and the
beginning of moderation in facing our problems,'' said lawyer Fayez
Abu Rahme, a prominent PLO supporter in the Gaza Strip.
   ``It shows the Palestinians are ready to co-exist with Israel,
that they want a state side-by-side with Israel,'' he told The
Associated Press.
   Abu Rahme said the PLO's new moderate stance would enable the
United States to exert pressure on Israel to be more flexible in its
positions. Washington backs an international conference and a
territories-for-peace formula.
   On Monday night, Palestinians in some parts of the Gaza Strip
broke curfews and took to the streets in anticipation of the
declaration of independence.
   In Gaza's Jabaliya refugee camp, residents set off firecrackers
and shouted ``Allahu Akhbar'' (God is Great), an Arab reporter said.
   Elsewhere, residents flew balloons and hoisted pictures of Arafat
to express their joy. Other Gaza Strip residents remained glued to
the radio for news from Algiers.
   At least 312 Palestinians have been killed since a rebellion
began Dec. 8, 1987, among the 1.5 million who live in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the
1967 war. Eleven Israelis also have died.
</TEXT>
