<HEAD>Soldiers Kill Protester As Palestinians Celebrate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs UPDATING with Palestinian homeland declared
with Jerusalem as its capital. PICKS up 6th pvs: Residents of Gaza's
...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULKAREM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers fought
protesters Monday, killing one and wounding at least four, while
Palestinians in the occupied lands celebrated the PLO declaration of
an independent homeland.
   At least 312 Palestinians have been killed since a rebellion
began Dec. 8, 1987, among the 1.5 million who live in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the
1967 war. Eleven Israelis also have died.
   Troopers arrested dozens of alleged guerrillas and destroyed or
sealed nine houses in the effort to prevent pro-PLO demonstrations
while the Palestine National Council, which acts as the PLO
legislature, meets in Algiers.
   ``The Palestinian National Council hereby declares the
establishment of a Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital,
which will be for all Palestinians wherever they are,'' Yasser
Arafat, chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization, announced
in Algiers early Tuesday.
   The Gaza Strip's 650,000 residents remained under curfew for a
third day. Arab reports and Israel radio said some violated the
restrictions because of the council's declaration of an independent
state.
   Palestinians lit firecrackers, raised outlawed Palestinian flags,
flew balloons and hoisted pictures of Arafat.
   Residents of Gaza's Jabaliya refugee camp shouted ``Allahu
Akhbar!'' (God is Great!) and sang ``My Homeland, My Homeland,'' the
Palestinian anthem, an Arab journalist reported.
   Among the words are: ``Palestine live free, live liberated from
the enemy. Palestine, you are the mother of the world ... the symbol
of the holy war.''
   Soldiers using loudspeakers ordered residents to their homes but
took no other action, the reporter said.
   A young Palestinian was killed in a confrontation at the Khan
Yunis camp in Gaza, the army reported. Israel radio said he was
throwing concrete blocks at a patrol when an officer opened fire.
   Youths in Gaza City blocked a main street with burning tires and
rocks, said an Arab reporter at the scene.
   Telephones were cut off in many areas of the West Bank and a
reporter who visited Jericho, near the Jordanian border, said
residents were being prevented from leaving the city.
   Soldiers in jeeps and on foot patrolled villages on the main
highway from Jerusalem to Nablus, largest city in the West Bank, and
on the road west to Tulkarem.
   Israeli officials repeated their view that a declaration of
Palestinian independence would be meaningless.
   ``We will not negotiate with the PLO,'' Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir told reporters in Jerusalem. ``It's not a problem of
definition and formulations of various positions. We'll not
negotiate with them because they're opposed to peace with Israel.''
   Tulkarem, just inside the West Bank, was declared a closed
military area after troops bulldozed three houses of suspected
firebombers. Soldiers blocked reporters from entering the town of
40,000.
   While dozens of troops could be seen patrolling the town, no one
else was visible on the streets and all shops appeared to be
shuttered. At one point, two young boys appeared on a rooftop and
waved, but they disappeared when soldiers shouted at them.
   Army spokesmen refused to say when or exactly how many arrests
were made in the crackdown on underground groups announced Monday.
Israel radio said the announcement was meant to deter expected
violence if independence is declared.
   The army listed 54 people rounded up in five West Bank cities and
said guerrilla cells also were found to be operating in 11 other
areas.
   In addition to the houses destroyed in Tulkarem, five were
demolished in Bani Naim, near Nablus, and one was sealed in Hebron,
the army said.
   In Gaza, three teen-agers were shot by soldiers during
stone-throwing incidents, hospital officials said. One was a
14-year-old listed in serious condition with a stomach wound after
being shot in the town of Khan Yunis.
   In the West Bank, an 18-year-old was listed in serious condition
with a head wound after soldiers opened fire on demonstrators in the
old market area of Nablus, said officials at the city's Al-Ittihad
hospital.
</TEXT>
