<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 2206EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WyoSenateRace     11-14 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wyo Senate Race,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrat Says He'll Wait on Making Recount Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat John Vinich, who lost a close
Senate race to incumbent Republican Malcolm Wallop, said Monday he
will neither ask for a recount nor concede until after an official
review of the election this week.
   Unofficial returns show Vinich finished 1,315 votes behind Wallop
in last week's election, 89,806 to 91,121. Results won't be official
until the state Canvassing Board meets Wednesday.
   Vinich said the count was so close that he feels he owes it to
the people who voted for him to ``to take a close look at the
outcome of this race.''
   ``We're still waiting for the official records. I think that's
only appropriate,'' he said.
   Shortly after the initial returns came in, showing Wallop
defeating Vinich, the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee
charged that there were irregularities in the handling of absentee
ballots in the race.
   Secretary of State Kathy Karpan's office made a
precinct-by-precinct review of ballots late last week, and Karpan
said she was satisfied there were no problems.
   If the canvassing board also finds no problems with the returns,
Vinich will have until Friday evening to decide whether to call for
a recount. He would have to pay for it, which could run up to
$11,500.
   If the board finds irregularities, the state would pay for an
automatic recount.
   Any challenge the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee would
want to make to the results would have to come through the courts,
according to the Karpan's office. If the courts agreed to overturn
the election results, that would force a special election.
   On Saturday. Vinich called on Wallop to join him in requesting a
recount. Vinich said Monday he had not received a response from
Wallop.
   A spokesman for Wallop said the incumbent has no interest in
joining Vinich in calling for a recount.
   ``Right now we see no reason for a recount. We are pleased with
Sen. Wallop's victory, and we've followed the process carefully,''
said Wallop spokesman Kevin Bohnenblust. He said, however, that the
incumbent had not received Vinich's letter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
