<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 2238EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PLO-Scene     11-14 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-Scene,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quietly Emotional Setting For Declaration Of Palestinian State</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was no great explosion of joy when
Yasser Arafat, leader and symbol of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, proclaimed an independent Palestinian state early
Tuesday.
   Instead, hundreds of dignified people expressed their emotions
quietly with handshakes, kisses and an occasional tear.
   In a jam-packed seaside conference hall west of Algiers, Arafat
read the declaration, which proclaims ``the establishment of the
state of Palestine.''
   The reading of the declaration by Arafat, wearing his usual
military fatigues and black-and-white checkered headdress, was
interrupted frequently by clapping and cheering, and high-pitched
ululations from the women.
   Spirits were high before the long-awaited session of the
Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile, to
declare the existence of a state that once was and which they hope
would be again.
   In the lobby at the entrance to the meeting hall, spontaneous
songs and dances broke out. Then, at about 1 a.m. Algiers time _ 2
a.m. in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip where 1.5
million Palestinians live _ they filed into the round, wood-paneled
conference hall.
   As Arafat entered, many council members began chanting the new
slogan, ``Unity, unity until victory. Revolution, revolution until
victory.''
   The slogan was launched Monday by George Habash, leader of the
Marxist Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine. Habash had
opposed Arafat's new moderate policies, but ceded to the vote of the
council majority.
   The proclamation came at 1:38 a.m. (7:38 p.m. EST Monday).
   When the reading was over, people filed out slowly, mingling and
talking in low voices, not unlike the scene at a theater after the
final act.
   There were handshakes, smiles, solemn embraces and tears.
   ``It was a dignified ceremony,'' said council member Mustafa
Hallak. ``There was a lack of emotional demonstration perhaps
because we've known for a week it (the declaration) was coming.''
   Assaad Abdel-Rahman, another Council member, said he felt
different Tuesday morning after the declaration.
   ``Yes, I feel more secure and more responsible,'' Abdel-Rahman
said.
   ``If anything impressed me today, it was the behavior of the top
leadership. They were entirely responsible and democratic in ironing
out differences, very civilized, showing a high calibre of dealing
with differences.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 2309EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RockyFlats     11-14 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rocky Flats,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meeting on Radioactive Waste Postponed; Gov. Romer to Meet with DOE</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A meeting between Department of Energy officials
and three Western governors on hazardous waste storage problems at
the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant has been postponed, Gov. Roy
Romer said Monday.
   Romer was clearly angered at the postponement because several
railroad cars are sitting at Rocky Flats, filled with radioactive
waste, but have no place to go. The plant has only about a
four-month storage capacity.
   Romer, Idaho Gov. Cecil Andrus and New Mexico Gov. Garrey
Carruthers were to meet Wednesday in Salt Lake City with DOE
officials to work on solutions to the storage problem.
   The meeting was postponed so Carruthers, a Republican, could
participate in a presidential transition team meeting, Romer said.
   In late October, Romer rejected plans to expand the storage
capacity at Rocky Flats, urging the DOE to expedite its search for a
permanent facility.
   A proposed site for permanent waste storage is scheduled to open
in New Mexico, but that has been delayed, to the annoyance of Romer
and other governors caught in a push-pull dilemma over existing
waste.
   After the New Mexico site's opening was delayed indefinitely,
Andrus banned further storage of waste at a site in Idaho, which
forced the return to Rocky Flats of one rail car filled with waste.
   Rocky Flats, the Argonne National Laboratory near Chicago and the
Lawrence Livermore Laboratory in Livermore, Calif., had been
shipping radioactive rags, machines parts, gloves, liquids and other
debris to the Idaho site, where an estimated 2 million cubic feet of
the waste is stored below ground and 2.4 million cubic feet is
stored above ground in steel barrels.
   Romer said he is insisting on a meeting with the DOE anyway
because of pressing problems at Rocky Flats. The agency has agreed
to send several representatives to Colorado on Wednesday.
   ``I wanted to have that meeting Wednesday. I called the
Department of Energy this afternoon and told them I wanted to go
ahead. They said they wanted to reschedule it because they felt it
was necessary for Carruthers to be there,'' he said.
   ``I told them we should reschedule the meeting as soon as
possible, and I told them I wanted to meet with them on Wednesday.''
   Cindy Parmenter, Romer's press aide, said the meeting will be
closed, but the participants will be available for reporters'
questions later in the day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
