<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Balloon 2ndLd-Writethru a0706 11-14 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Balloon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0706,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Balloon, Blown 500 Miles Off Course, Crashes In Southern Utah</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf, `Hendricks was...' to UPDATE with one patient
being transferred to Salt Lake City</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CIRCLEVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A long-range, high-altitude helium
balloon blown 500 miles off course from California crashed near this
southern Utah town Monday, seriously injuring two men aboard.
   The balloon, registered to Scorpion Productions of Perris,
Calif., took off Sunday evening from a parking lot near Disneyland
in Orange County, Calif., authorities said.
   The two friends had planned to take an aerial tour of the Los
Angeles basin, said Hajnal Crieg, co-owner of the four-passenger,
3,500-cubic-foot balloon.
   ``But a storm came in. You can't really control a helium balloon,
so they went wherever the wind takes them,'' she said. The trip
ended about 500 air miles east of Los Angeles.
   ``They were just on an overnight trip,'' Crieg said.
   The balloon wreckage was spotted about 10:20 a.m. in rugged,
mountainous terrain about five miles south of Circleville, said Utah
Civil Air Patrol spokesman Jerry Wellman.
   The California men, pilot Ron Martin, 46, of Long Beach, and
Scott Hendricks, 30, of Chino, were taken to Garfield Memorial
Hospital.
   Hendricks was in critical condition with severe back injuries and
a possible broken ankle. Martin was in serious condition with back
injuries and a dislocated shoulder, said hospital administrator
Wayne Ross. Ross said Hendricks was taken by ambulance to a Salt
Lake City hospital, about 200 miles to the north, Monday afternoon.
</TEXT>
