<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SeattleFire 1stLd-Writethru a0726 11-14 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seattle Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frozen Turkeys Destroyed In Cold Storage Blaze</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 3rd, `About 80...' to UPDATE with
residents returning home; picks up 4th graf pvs, `Five
firefighters...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stubborn fire at a warehouse destroyed at least
340,000 frozen turkeys and millions of pounds of crab, cauliflower
and other foods.
   The overnight fire, which was brought under control Monday
afternoon, was inside thick walls filled with dry,
turn-of-the-century sawdust that helped insulate the Rainier Cold
Storage, said Fire Chief Claude Harris.
   About 80 people had to be evacuated from the plant when ammonia
gas, used in the warehouse's refrigeration, was released.
   The residents were moved back to their homes after utility
services were restored, said Lt. Herb Brooks. Electricity and gas
lines had been shut off for safety, he said.
   Five firefighters were injured slightly in the blaze and a sixth
was hospitalized, Harris said. The cause of the fire was being
investigated.
   Deputy Fire Chief Steve Bailey said it may have started in the
building's electrical system. ``We first received a call of an
electrical problem,'' he said.
   One wall collapsed from the heat and water. Harris said pumping
water into the 4-foot-wide walls was necessary to extinguish the
smoldering blaze, but dangerous because the weight of the water
could cause the walls to collapse.
   At least some walls on the inside of the building, which was
built before 1910 as a brewery for Rainier Brewing Co., had fallen
in, and the roof collapsed.
   ``There was 13 million pounds of food in this building,'' said
Bud Horton, owner of Meats, Inc., and crab was a big part of the
loss. He said he had lost 40,000 pounds of turkeys and 20,000 pounds
of fish, and another broker had lost 300,000 pounds of turkeys.
   Bill Butler, office manager for Rainier Cold Storage, said the
facility rented space to many food brokers. He said he did not know
how extensive losses would be, or whether there was insurance
coverage.
   Mike Roberts, Rainier Cold Storage vice president of marketing
and warehousing, estimated the building's value at $5 million,
adding that the 22-room structure housed about 13 million pounds of
fruits, vegetables, meats and seafood. He said the value of the
frozen foods ranged from 50 cents a pound to $8 a pound.
</TEXT>
