<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StateFarm-Calif 1stLd-Writethru a0668 11-14 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Farm-Calif, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0668,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Large Home And Car Insurer Stops Writing New California Policies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 3rd, `But new...' to UPDATE with quotes
from Proposition 103 author; picks up 4th graf pvs, `The
affiliate...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Insurance Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The largest home and car insurer in
California, State Farm Mutual Auto Insurance Co., said Monday it has
stopped writing new auto policies because of chaos surrounding
rate-slashing Proposition 103.
   State Farm Mutual will continue to carry and renew policies for
its more than 3 million auto insurance customers, the company
announced Monday.
   But new applications will be referred to an affiliated company
that has higher rates, thus shielding the company from some of the
cuts that would be imposed by Proposition 103.
   In California, Proposition 103's author, Harvey Rosenfield,
denounced the plan to switch new customers to a higher-priced
affiliate as an improper attempt to circumvent the measure.
   ``They can't get away with it,'' Rosenfield said.
   The affiliate, State Farm Fire and Casualty Co., charges 20
percent to 60 percent more for car insurance than does State Farm
Mutual because State Farm Fire insures higher-risk drivers rejected
by its affiliate, spokesman Jim Stahly said from the companies'
Bloomington, Ill., headquarters.
   State Farm Fire and Casualty Co. has about 300,000 auto policies
in California and also is the state's biggest homeowners' insurance
carrier.
   Implementation of Proposition 103, approved by voters last week,
was blocked by the California Supreme Court. But uncertainty in the
industry has already prompted a number of companies to either stop
writing insurance or to consider a halt.
   Proposition 103 orders sweeping changes of the insurance
industry, including a 20 percent rate cut below November 1987 rates
for auto, home and commercial insurance.
   In Massachusetts on Monday, Allstate Insurance Co. announced it
is leaving that state because of financial losses and frustration
over the regulatory climate.
   Kevin Sullivan, director of Allstate's Group Auto division, said
Allstate has lost $115 million in Massachusetts in five years.
   ``We have no intention to return,'' Sullivan said, making
Allstate the third major insurer to abandon Massachusetts.
   Allstate will not renew its license when it expires on June 30.
But until then, Allstate will sell new policies and follow through
on policies until they expire, he said.
   State Farm made the switch concerning its California business
both to reduce its continuing losses on car insurance and to have a
vehicle to sell insurance to drivers whose own companies may quit
the state, Stahly said.
   ``Our underwriting loss was $76 for each car insured in
California during 1987, and we're losing substantially more during
1988,'' the company said in a news release, adding that escalating
future losses are a ``near certainty.''
   Additional losses could reach $1.3 million in auto insurance
premium income each day for the next year under Proposition 103,
officials said.
   State Farm Mutual owns State Farm Fire. Together, the companies'
California business includes more than 3 million auto policies, 1.2
million homeowner policies and 420,000 business liability customers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
