<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Lebanon-ToxicWaste ADV21   11-14 0883</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Toxic Waste, ADV 21,0909</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Nov. 21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>On Top of War, Lebanon is Hit with Toxic Waste Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ravaged by civil war for 13 years, Lebanon
now has been hit by the dumping of poisonous chemical waste from
Western Europe.
   At least 2,400 tons of Italian chemical waste, which Lebanese
officials said was toxic and dangerous, were discovered last May in
the mountains of Kesrouan province in the Christian heartland about
20 miles north of Beirut.
   That discovery forced the cancellation of another shipment of
30,000 tons of Italian waste destined for Lebanon, Justice Ministry
sources reported.
   The incident is one of several that have recently surfaced in
African, Middle Eastern and Latin American countries where Western
Europe has unloaded its industrial waste, often passed off as
innocent material, because of the high cost of toxic-waste disposal
at home.
   Amid an outcry for tighter controls, several countries have
blocked ships carrying toxic waste from entering their harbors,
leaving the vessels to roam the seas looking for a place to unload
their hazardous cargoes.
   Lebanon's leftist newspapers and radio stations accused the
Lebanese Forces, the Christians' main militia, of allowing the
industrial waste to be brought into the country through the port
they control in Beirut harbor.
   They claim the militia was paid $10 million to dump the waste and
alleged there was an ``Israeli connection.''
   Lebanon has numerous ports run by Moslem and Christian militias
along its Mediterranean coast through which they ship in goods and
weapons.
   The Christian militia has denied involvement in the toxic waste
affairs and diplomats don't believe it was. Officials of the
London-based International Maritime Bureau recently said the
Lebanese Forces have helped them uncover shipping frauds.
   But Beirut's leftist As-Safir newspaper published letters and
documents purporting to prove the militia's involvement. It did not
say who provided the documents.
   A Western diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, told The
Associated Press that former President Amin Gemayel, whose term
expired Sept. 23, deliberately leaked the story to polish up his
image and discredit the militia.
   The Lebanese Forces and Gemayel's Katayeb militia at the time
were battling for dominance of the 800,000-member Maronite Catholic
community, Lebanon's most powerful Christian sect. Since Gemayel
stepped down, the Lebanese Forces have won.
   ``The case was blown up out of proportion, in typical Lebanese
fashion. I don't believe the Lebanese Forces imported the stuff,''
the diplomat said.
   ``Moslem leaders fanned the flames of the scandal, hoping it
would touch off a confrontation between the Christian rivals.''
   ``What happened was a stupid mistake which resulted from
ignorance,'' said Caesar Nasr, head of the Lebanese Forces' foreign
relations department.
   The manifest of the Czechoslovak freighter Radhost, which carried
the waste in October, 1987, to the Lebanese Forces' port, known as
the Fifth Basin, listed the cargo as ``chemical residue and
agricultural products.''
   Nasr said that the militia's ``customs officers'' at the Fifth
Basin ``didn't have the scientific background to realize the
significance of industrial residue.''
   ``Since there's no law forbidding the entry of industrial residue
into Lebanon, they allowed the barrels in,'' he added. He claimed
that ``unscrupulous Lebanese merchants'' brought the waste in.
   Joseph Hashem, Lebanon's health minister at the time, declared
that the waste was poisonous and harmful. Nasr said the militia
later moved the waste back to the Fifth Basin.
   Attilio Massimo Iannucci, first secretary at Italy's Embassy in
Beirut, said the drums contain solvents, paint and plastics products.
   ``It's very dirty because it's the residue of chemical waste .. .
but it's not toxic, explosive or radioactive,'' he added.
   Nonetheless, the Italian authorities sent a 16-man team of
specialists to handle the waste. They spent 50 days repacking it
into 10,000 new drums and 15 containers brought from Italy.
   Toxic waste from Italy has turned up in several countries and the
government in Rome has said it will ban toxic waste shipments to the
Third World.
   Asked why Italy was going to such lengths to rid Lebanon of the
waste, Iannucci said it was part of Italy's ``technical assistance''
program.
   ``Lebanon was facing a problem without the means to solve it .. .
so we offered to help,'' he said. ``Also, these products came from
Italy.''
   Iannucci added that the chemicals were brought to Lebanon after
the Jelly Wax Co. of Milan, a paraffin manufacturer that moved into
the lucrative toxic waste disposal business, made a deal with a
Lebanese company known as Adonis. Lebanese officials said Adonis was
a ``fictitious company.''
   Iannucci said Adonis undertook to destroy the chemicals for a
``huge sum of money'' to be paid after disposal.
   ``Instead, they dumped it in Lebanon and presented an official
document claiming it had been disposed of to get the money.'' The
document proved to be forged.
   Roger Haddad, director of maritime operations with the Nassar
Shipping Co., and four other Christian businessmen linked to Adonis
were arrested on charges of importing toxic waste that endangered
lives. They were later released on bail.
   A warrant has also been issued for Armand Nassar, owner of the
shipping company and a relative of Haddad. Nassar, identified as the
mastermind of the deal, fled Lebanon earlier this year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon AMs, Nov. 21</NOTE>
