<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Spain-Unions ADV23   11-14 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Unions, ADV 23,0716</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Nov. 23, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Spain's Socialist Government and Labor on Verge of Split</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With unemployment the highest in Western
Europe, Spain's Socialist government and labor unions, longtime
allies, are on the verge of a serious split.
   When leaders of Spain's 100-year-old General Workers Union called
recently for a nationwide strike to protest government economic
austerity policies, they took what many saw as the final step toward
a divorce from the governing Spanish Socialist Workers Party and the
46-year-old Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez.
   The union and its erstwhile rival, the Communist-oriented Workers
Commissions, have set a 24-hour nationwide strike for Dec. 14.
   The aim of both unions is to force Gonzalez, a former labor
lawyer, to shift his support to labor and drop policies favoring
only moderate wage hikes and low inflation as the way to high
economic growth.
   Labor Minister Manuel Chaves' decision to create a youth job
corps was the last straw for the unions, who claim the low wages
proposed in the plan will take jobs away from older workers at a
time when the unemployment rate has soared to 18.8 percent.
   The youth plan calls for the creation of up to to 800,000 jobs
for unemployed youths 16 to 25 years old over the next three years
through low wages and tax credits for businesses who must provide
training during their six-to-18 month contracts.
   At least 45 percent of those in the 16-25 age group are
unemployed and many have never held a job.
   Apolinar Rodriguez, member of the General Workers Union executive
committee, said the program ``foments inequities among workers since
youths hired under the plan will be making less than the minimum
legal wage'' _ the equivalent of $376 a month for those aged 18 to
25 _ ``and will be excluded from collective bargaining agreements.''
   Economy Minister Carlos Solchaga reponded, however, that the
unions may find the majority of Spaniards do not share their
disapproval of the youth jobs program.
   Even before the jobs plan conflict, the unions had clashed with
the Gonzalez government over wage agreements.
   Union leaders have denounced the government's request that
employers reject demands for immediate wage increases until after
the first of the year, despite a recent rise in inflation to 5
percent, two points above the 1988 government target.
   Nicolas Redondo, secretary general of the General Workers Union,
helped propel Gonzalez to the top of the Socialist party during the
bitter years of the opposition to the authoritarian regime of Gen.
Francisco Franco. But Redondo quit his Parliament seat in 1987 to
protest a budget he viewed as anti-labor.
   ``The strikes are not just about money, but about ideology,''
Redondo said recently. ``The economic policies of this government,
instead of helping workers, lean clearly to the right. It should
realize it cannot remain in power very long with just the support of
businessmen and bankers.''
   The Spanish Confederation of Employers has given its full support
to the youth plan and backs continued government calls for moderate
wages.
   The economic policies criticized by the unions have helped end a
decade of economic stagnation in Spain and spurred a boom that has
fueled a 5 percent annual growth, the highest in Western Europe, for
the past two years.
   A top Labor Ministry official, Alvaro Espina, has criticized the
unions' opposition to the jobs plan, saying they appear more
interested in politics than helping youths get jobs.
   Espina lamented the growing separation between the unions and the
Socialist administration ``which diminishes their (the unions') role
in society, which is absolutely necessary and which should be
reinforced.''
   Only 10 percent of Spain's active work force belongs to a union,
according to Labor Ministry statistics, and the government appears
confident of public support for its jobs plan.
   A government poll recently indicated that 85 percent of those
surveyed believed the administration's top priority should be
creating jobs for youths.
   An additional 77 percent said they preferred that the government
create the jobs through incentives to businesses rather than
directly hand out unemployment pay.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Nov. 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
