<DOCNO> AP881114-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1431EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV27   11-14 0895</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 27,0924</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv27</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If there's one thing Julie Wilson has learned
during her long career singing in nightclubs and high-tone places
like the Plaza and the St. Regis and the Algonquin, it's never count
on anything.
   ``I'm a total fatalist,'' says the sophisticated song stylist
known for her impeccable way with lyrics. ``I feel if it's going to
happen, it's going to happen. If it's not, it's not.''
   So when Peter Allen told her nearly five years ago that he would
write a role for her in his first Broadway musical, she didn't tell
anyone.
   ``Not a soul,'' Miss Wilson says. ``You know when you want
something so much, it's like the kiss of death if you talk about it.
I didn't open my trap.''
   Her silence _ and waiting _ paid off.
   Miss Wilson now is appearing with Allen at the Mark Hellinger
Theater in ``Legs Diamond,'' a new musical about the 1920s New York
gangster. Allen, who wrote the show's music and lyrics, also plays
the famous outlaw. Miss Wilson is Flo, a woman who fronts a
nightclub secretly owned by Diamond.
   ``They needed a woman of my age and experience to play this role,
someone who's been around the block _ more than once,'' she laughs.
``I'm the older woman in this show. Believe me, I am the oldie. I
like to say `oldie but goodie.'''
   For Miss Wilson, ``Legs Diamond'' is her first Broadway musical
in nearly two decades. Broadway has only been a part of her show
business career, which began at the age of 17 back in Omaha when she
was chosen Miss Nebraska. Since then, there have been touring shows,
radio, television, recordings, summer stock and stints in London
where she appeared in West End editions of ``Kiss Me Kate,'' ``South
Pacific'' and ``Bells Are Ringing.''
   But her bread and butter has been nightclubs. Usually wearing a
slinky gown and a gardenia perched behind her ear, Miss Wilson has
sung the best songs of Cole Porter, George Gershwin, Rodgers and
Hart, Kurt Weill, Stephen Sondheim and other Broadway writers.
   Allen's material has been a more recent addition. She met him for
the first time in the 1970s, but he knew about her long before that.
   ``When he was a kid, dancing in Australia, somebody sent him an
old record of mine called `Julie Wilson at the St. Regis,''' she
says.
   Those days in the early 1970s were lean years for Miss Wilson in
New York. Suddenly there was no place to sing. Big clubs were
closing all over town.
   ``I was fighting for my life,'' she recalls. ``I grabbed whatever
came my way. Things like small roles in plays like `Norman, Is That
You?' in Paramus, N.J.''
   At the time, Miss Wilson and Allen shared the same voice teacher
_ Keith Davis. They still do.
   ``I became very aware of Peter because my teacher was always
talking about him and because he had the big hit song, `I Honestly
Love You,''' the singer recalls.
   Whenever she got a job, there would be flowers and a note from
Allen. Sometimes, he and a group of friends would show up to cheer
her on. She attended a lot of his concerts, too, and they became
good friends.
   Then, in 1976, she left New York, returning to Omaha for an
eight-year sabbatical to take care of her ailing parents and raise
her two sons. When she came back in 1984 to resume her career, Allen
showed up at Michael's Pub, an East Side nightclub, to hear her
sing. It was then that he told her about ``Legs Diamond'' and his
plans for her.
   Nothing happened.
   A year later, she was at her voice teacher's studio and ran into
Allen again. ``Would you like to hear your song?'' he asked.
   Allen sat down at the piano and played ``The Music Went Out of My
Life,'' the song Miss Wilson sings in ``Legs Diamond.''
   ``It's a little soliloquy,'' she says. ``It's a woman singing
about her loves, what happened and why they didn't work out.''
   Then another year went by, and Miss Wilson was asked to perform
with Allen in a workshop production of ``Legs.'' The workshop was
done in March 1987. The show's producers decided the book by Charles
Suppon needed work.
   Harvey Fierstein, author of ``Torch Song Trilogy,'' was brought
in to help, to sharpen some of the characters and make the story
brighter.
   Then the show was finally announced to open on Broadway in the
fall of 1988.
   But before ``Legs Diamond'' went into rehearsal, Miss Wilson
found out she was under consideration to replace Dolores Gray and
sing the show-stopping ``I'm Still Here'' in the London production
of ``Follies.'' She told her agent ``no.'' Her heart belonged to
Allen.
   ``I don't want anything else,'' Miss Wilson told her agent. ``I
just want to hang out, do my club thing and hope that the show will
go.''
   She doesn't regret her decision.
   ``I'm on the boards until they get rid of me,'' she says. ``I
knew I had to chance it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1404EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Armenia-UpinArms ADV20   11-14 1195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Armenia-Up in Arms, ADV 20,1227</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Armenian Dispute Fuels Growing Radicalism and Hostility</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YEREVAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Until this year, soft-voiced Agvam
Tadevosyan was a card-carrying Communist and had a steady job. Then
came a transformation: He was sent to jail twice for anti-Soviet
agitation, lost his job and resigned from the Communist Party.
   All this came about, he says, because of what he sees as
Kremlin-imposed terror in his homeland of Soviet Armenia and he
maintains that terror must be answered with terror.
   He is not alone in his view of the Kremlin in Moscow.
   From a tent on a Yerevan square, Khachik Stamboltsyan campaigns
for election to Armenia's Supreme Soviet, or legislature. The
biophysicist expresses scorn for Mikhail S. Gorbachev, charging that
the Soviet leader ``has shown us he is no democrat, but a dictator.''
   Ten months into a bitter territorial dispute with the neighboring
Soviet republic of Azerbaijan on the Caspian Sea, Armenian voices
cry out in anger and frustration. They have turned their hostility
toward the Communist Party and Soviet system, presenting a threat to
Gorbachev and the unity of the multi-ethnic nation he heads.
   Many Armenians predict a confrontation with Soviet authorities,
perhaps even a violent explosion.
   ``People are ready to persevere until our demands are met,'' said
Rafael Poposyan, a former political prisoner, literary critic and
Armenian activist. ``I think this movement can be crushed only with
tanks.''
   In February, tens of thousands marched in Yerevan, the Armenian
republic's capital, to demand the annexation of the predominantly
Armenian Nagorno-Karabakh district, which has been part of
Azerbaijan since 1923. Anti-Armenian rioting broke out in
Azerbaijan, and at least 32 people _ 26 of them Armenians _ were
killed.
   Led by Gorbachev, the Supreme Soviet Presidium, the central
government's top executive body in Moscow, dashed Armenians' hopes
in July by ruling that Azerbaijan's refusal to go along with a
change in its territory took precedence over Nagorno-Karabakh's
petition to join Armenia.
   The Kremlin decision, backed by a tough back-to-work order and
the dispatch of troops to enforce order, produced a brief calm. But
a new wave of strikes and demonstrations broke out in September, and
what began as the ``Karabakh movement'' broadened into an alternate
political force, with rival tendencies, that challenges the
leadership of the Communist Party on issues from ecology to economic
reform.
   ``The movement started with slogans like `We support glasnost and
perestroika,' and people carrying pictures of Gorbachev,'' Popoyan
said. ``This lasted as long as the Armenians had faith that
Gorbachev would understand.''
   Many Armenians now don't have that faith.
   A poster in an open-air exhibit of protest art in Yerevan's Opera
Square, nerve center of the republic's burgeoning nationalist
sentiment, depicts a weeping Armenia and reads: ``Moscow does not
believe in tears.''
   Armenians are painfully aware that for centuries, the very
survival of their largely Orthodox Christian people has often seemed
at stake. For some, the rioting in Sumgait was a terrifying reprise
of the 1915 Armenian genocide organized by Turkey, in which 1.5
million Armenians are said to have perished.
   The mostly Moslem Azerbajanis are ethnically related to the
Turks, and Armenians commonly call them ``Turks.'' Atop a windswept
Yerevan hill, hundreds Armenians come daily to lay flowers at the
memorial to the 1915 genocide victims, in a ritual made more
poignant by the spilling of Armenian blood in Sumgait.
   ``Here 1.5 million Armenians are symbolically buried,'' said one
recent visitor, Gayany Sarkisyan, 25. ``Today the same thing has
started again, in Sumgait.''
   Gorbachev rejected that logic at the Presidium meeting. He told
an Armenian speaker: ``What genocide can one speak of? You know what
that word implies, the weight it carries. You are making accusations
that you will regret for the rest of your life.''
   Gorbachev acknowledged the Karabakh issue had been long
neglected, and the Kremlin has approved a plan to promote the area's
economic and social development by pumping in government money. But
he drew the line at a redrawing of borders, which could set off a
chain reaction among other disaffected Soviet minorities.
   ``If placing the Nagorno-Karabakh Automonous Region under the
jurisdiction of someone else is the only way, then we should recarve
our whole country,'' Gorbachev said. `People have lived here for
centuries. They'll say to us: Have you people at the center gone
crazy or something?''
   Some in Armenia, dismayed by what they see as Moscow's
pro-Azerbaijan tilt, speak openly of organizing a secession attempt.
   ``If they won't accord us the rights that are our due, we'll have
a referendum and vote to live outside the Soviet Union,'' says
would-be lawmaker Stamboltsyan.
   ``Our movement has become a much wider movement _ its goal is now
independence,'' says Tadevosyan, 22, who was fired from his job as a
civilian firearms instructor after he was sentenced to two 15-day
jail terms.
   Tadevosyan said he expects Moscow officials to provoke an
incident in order to provide a pretext for liquidating the Karabakh
movement.
   ``Against state terror we can only reply with terror _ and the
state is using terror,'' he claims.
   For others, however, the Karabakh issue, and not independence, is
still paramount.
   ``Since the Soviet Union has been founded, there have been two
Armenias, and now we want to reunite them, to bring the baby back to
the mother,'' said Artur Danilyan, 52, a worker at a Yerevan perfume
factory.
   Despite the outspoken nationalist sentiment, faith in Moscow has
not vanished among many Armenians. A middle-aged Armenian bard, his
voice choking with emotion, gathered a crowd around him on Opera
Square as he read a poem that included these lines:
   ``And if Russia knew the truth, about what Islam was doing here,
   ``She would sweep the Moslem lice from the face of Russia.''
   The Armenian Apostolic Church, an officially recognized religious
body in the ostensibly atheist Soviet state, has opposed the Kremlin
decision on Karabakh and expressed hope for eventual reunification
between the region of more than 160,000 people and Armenia, itself
about the size of Maine with 3.4 million inhabitants.
   ``Karabakh is historically Armenian territory,'' Archbishop
Nersess Bozabalian said in an interview. ``What people there want is
the freedom to work, to produce and to achieve their aims without
losing their national integrity.''
   The waves of strikes called in Yerevan over the Karabakh issue
have subsided, and special units of internal security troops sent to
the city were withdrawn from the streets in October. But
politically, Armenia remains on the boil.
   On a recent Monday, more than 1,000 marchers set out for Yerevan
from Echmiadzin, the cradle of the Armenian church, to demand
unification with Karabakh and the removal of Echmiadzin's party
chief, whom they accused of corruption and inaction. They turned
back only after a high party official was sent out to the highway to
meet with them.
   Armenia, by all accounts, will never be the same.
   ``These past 10 months have been like a century,'' Stamboltsyan
said. ``We have learned so much. It's as if the entire republic has
been to university.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1514EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Alejandro'sAmnesty ADV20   11-14 1216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Alejandro's Amnesty, ADV 20,1245</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Nov. 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Plastic Card Gives a Farm Worker Back His Dignity</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A year ago, The Associated Press rode along on a
pre-dawn trip to Denver, where Mexican farm worker Alejandro Fierro,
wearing his best blue jeans and finest cowboy hat, met U.S.
immigration officers face to face and applied for amnesty. After 30
years of working illegally, Fierro now boasts a plastic-laminated
temporary residence card. Today, with only days remaining until the
deadline for Special Agricultural Workers to apply for the
government's one-time amnesty, Fierro is well along the way to
permanent status _ and maybe citizenship.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREELEY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After three decades of sneaking into the
United States to earn a living for his family, Mexican farm worker
Alejandro Fierro this year strode across the border, upright and
legal, with proof in his pocket that America's new amnesty program
works.
   Fierro was 19 in 1958 when he first swam the Rio Grande and, like
his father and grandfather before him, became an illegal alien
working in the fields of El Norte _ the land up north.
   Last summer, spiffy in a new shirt and polished cowboy boots, he
summoned up his courage and walked into the Denver office of the
U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service to apply for amnesty
under the landmark Immigration Control and Reform Act of 1986.
   That legislation applied to two groups of foreigners living and
working without permission in this country. Applications from those
trying to prove continuous residency in the United States since
before 1982 totaled 1,761,766 in the one-year registration period
that ended last May 4.
   The second category encompasses illegal aliens who have worked
with perishable crops in certain periods beginning in 1984.
Applicants have until Nov. 30 to seek INS approval. As of Nov. 9,
according to INS figures, 1,014,115 Special Agricultural Workers _
SAWs _ had applied for amnesty. The approval rate was running at 92
percent.
   Fierro is one of the 281,112 SAWS granted temporary resident
status as of Oct. 31. That's the first of three steps leading to
citizenship, a move Fierro says he will consider seriously in the
next few years.
   Sitting in the shade of a big tree on a lunch break in the dawn
to past-dark Colorado onion harvest, Fierro unsnapped the left
breast pocket of his western shirt and pulled out the
plastic-laminated ID card he keeps next to his heart.
   ``A90616632, Fierro-Jacobo, Alejandro,'' says the fine print.
``Bearer entitled to reside and work in U.S. until card expires, not
eligible for federally funded assistance program ... expires Jan. 1,
1991.''
   The 49-year-old father of six speaks no English, but he knew the
meaning of every word on the INS card.
   ``I feel so happy because there is now no problem to find a job
and I can take a bus,'' said Fierro through his friend and
interpreter Reyes Perez, a U.S. citizen who's worked beside him in
farmer Harry Matsushima's fields for years.
   The INS card has given Fierro back his dignity. It's also given
his middle-aged legs a rest.
   Always before, beginning his annual migratory ritual in early
spring, Fierro would start his stealthy journey to Colorado by
buying five days' worth of tortillas, canned meat and sweets and
filling a gallon jug with water. Then, with a spare shirt stuffed in
his pocket, he would pay some strapping Mexican teen-ager $1 to
carry him piggyback across the Rio Grande near Presidio, Texas, and
strike out in the darkness on foot.
   For five days Fierro used to avoid roads and people, walking at
night and hiding by day, and finally board a northbound bus only
when all his instincts told him he was safe from arrest and
deportation.
   Not this year.
   ``For the first time, I crossed the bridge at El Paso, which is
much closer to my home in Chihuahua than Presidio. The American
inspector looks at my card. Everything is OK, so I go straight
across the bridge into the United States. I didn't have to buy food
and water. I got on a bus in El Paso and didn't have to walk
anywhere,'' Fierro said with a big smile.
   He was headed for Santa Fe to work for a few weeks in a
restaurant kitchen before Colorado's agricultural season got
underway. Thirty miles south of Alamogordo, N.M., the Border Patrol
pulled the Greyhound bus over and put Fierro's amnesty card to its
first major test.
   ``They came on and checked the whole bus. I was very relieved
because they let me pass. Everybody on the bus had papers. They
didn't catch one illegal,'' Fierro said.
   Once in Santa Fe, he said it was easy to find a $3.50-an-hour job
in a restaurant ``because there are still a lot of illegals around,
but the bosses won't hire them. They're afraid of being caught.''
   The 1986 legislation aims to prevent illegal aliens from taking
jobs that ordinarily would be filled by Americans and properly
documented workers. The INS estimates as many as 7 million illegal
aliens are still in the United States.
   Nationally, as of mid-October, the INS had issued 3,175 warning
citations and fined 720 businesses more than $2 million for
violating the new immigration law.
   Fierro considers his INS card among his most important
possessions. He has proudly showed it to his 80-year-old father,
Socorro Fierro, who, he says, pronounced it ``a very good thing.''
   Alejandro Fierro's three daughters live in Mexico. Two of his
three sons live and work in this country. One lives in Wichita,
Kan., and is married to an American. The other lives in Santa Fe and
has applied for amnesty. His third son is home in Chihuahua, tending
the 15 cows and small acreage his father has bought with his
Colorado earnings.
   ``I don't know how long I can make him stay home,'' said Fierro.
``He knows he can have a much better life in El Norte, and he wants
to come, too.''
   Fierro, who lives on about $30 a week and sends more than
two-thirds of his annual $6,000 in wages to his wife, planned to
return home ``when it gets cold.'' But he will come back next year,
and every year after that he's able to hoe, harvest and haul onions.
   In 1991, when his current ID card expires, Fierro will be
notified he's eligible to apply for permanent residency ``if he has
been an upstanding citizen and a member in good standing of our
society,'' said INS spokesman Duke Austin in Washington, D.C.
   ``Then he will have to have permanent immigrant status for five
years before he can apply for naturalization to become a United
States citizen,'' said Austin. ``The earliest that could happen is
1996.''
   Fierro, who was an illegal alien for 30 years, said now that it's
actually possible, he often wonders what it would like to be an
American citizen.
   ``It is a big step,'' he said through his interpreter,
``especially learning the English. But why not? I still have many
years left!''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tad Bartimus is the AP Mountain States regional
reporter, based in Denver.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Nov. 20</NOTE>
