<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 2155EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo ADV00   11-14 1174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, ADV 00,1230</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Videos Reviewed this week: ``Anna,'' ``Two Moon Junction,''
``Opera Do Milandro,'' ``Little Nikita.''
   
   ``Anna'' (Vestron Video; VHS-Beta, $79.98; Rated PG-13)
   
   Sally Kirkland was nominated for an Academy Award _ and
deservedly so _ for her portrayal of an aging Czech actress in
``Anna,'' but this gritty film needs more than her extraordinary
performance to carry it.
   Directed by Yurek Bogayevicz, the movie tells the story of Anna,
an actress who was a great star in her native Czechoslovakia before
being forced into permanent exile in America.
   In New York she is forced to endure degrading auditions for bit
parts, her choice of roles limited by her age and her accent. In an
early scene she hops in circles on one foot, screaming the words to
``Humpty-Dumpty'' to one director's bidding. She winds up being the
understudy.
   Enter Krystyna, a young Czech woman who has followed Anna's
career from afar. She comes to New York, tracks Anna to an audition,
asks to be her maid, then faints from hunger. Anna, touched by the
young woman's adulation, takes her in and begins to school her in an
acting career.
   Krystyna, played by the achingly beautiful model Paulina
Porizkova in her film debut, soon learns English, has her rotting
teeth capped, and finds that acting roles drop at her feet with
little effort on her part. Her youth and her beauty are her only
ticket, and she proves a quick study in cashing in on them.
   Predictably, Anna's star falls as fast as Krystyna's rises, and
here lies the chief flaw of the film: Agnieszka Holland's screenplay
is full of such strained parallels. The movie gets very preachy and
stagy so as to better draw the viewer's attention to the injustice
of youth's trampling of experience.
   The ending is absolutely implausible, but so are so many scenes
leading up to it that it hardly comes as a surprise.
   Porizkova, with her finely chiseled features and low-key
performance, is perfect as Krystyna, both savvy and innocent at the
same time. Robert Fields has a thankless role as Daniel, the
sometime-lover of Anna who is still financially dependent on his
parents as he enters middle age.
   _ By Geneva Collins, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Two Moon Junction'' (RCA-Columbia Pictures Home Video;
VHS-Beta, $89.95; Rated R)
   
   Someone once told Sherilyn Fenn she looked a little like Marilyn
Monroe and maybe she ought to be in pictures. You remember Sherilyn,
she was in those two memorable movies, ``The Wild Life'' and ``Just
One of the Guys.'' What? You don't remember? You didn't see them?
You don't know who she is? Tsk. Tsk.
   Then maybe you should keep your record unblemished and skip ``Two
Moon Junction'' as well. It's a seedy little movie filled with fake
erotica and silliness, most perpetrated by our little Marilyn clone.
   Fenn plays April Delongpre, a Southern debutante about to marry
one as equally as privileged as she. The wedding is a big affair
patterned after ``Alice in Wonderland.'' Indeed, April looks
wistfully a her friends, as she clicks together a pair of ballet toe
shoes (perhaps she expects her wedding party to pirouette?), and
says she's always dreamed of a story book weeding.
   Then she meets a carny, and as the publicity hype puts it:
``sparks ignite into flames of passion.'' Their passion is as hot
and appealing as cold grits, and they go through their story with
the speed of molasses. You also can pretty much predict the outcome,
and you also know what evil lurks behind the fatherly smile of Burl
Ives, here a small-town sheriff. Zalman King directed this mess and
also wrote the screenplay.
   With the exception of a perky and much too brief cameo by Kristy
McNichol, you can skip this one.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Opera Do Milandro'' (Virgin Vision, VHS-Beta, $59.95, not rated)
   
   The Brazilian ``Opera Do Milandro'' is a blending of ``Guys 'n
Dolls'' with ``Threepenny Opera'' and set to a samba beat.
   This handsome movie recreates the atmosphere of the era's
soundstage melodramas and musicals, which were especially popular in
Latin America, and it percolates with sambas and tangos and ballads
and little pop songs that are still echoing when the next one begins.
   Director Ruy Guerra shares screenplay credit with Orlando Senna
and playwright Chico Buarque who also wrote the music and lyrics.
   Edson Celulari plays Max Overseas, a handsome good-for-nothing
hood who joyfully lives off the earnings of Margot (Elba Ramalho),
the B-girl with a heart of gold and former girlfriend of Tiger the
policeman (Ney Latorraca).
   With Tiger gunning for him, Max gets Margot fired by Nazi-loving
cabaret owner Otto Strudell (J.C. Violla) then seduces Otto's
gorgeous daughter Ludmilla (Claudia Ohana). The situation gets
desperate and then everything is miraculously resolved _ almost _ in
the final scene.
   ``Opera Do Milandro'' clicks effortlessly. It's a sad, romantic
and funny and visually engaging. If you like Brazilian music, you'll
love the movie. If you like musicals, grab this one.
   _ By Scott Williams, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Little Nikita'' (RCA-Columbia Home Video; VHS-Beta, $89.95;
Rated PG)
   
   Jeff Grant is a typical Southern California teen who likes the
usual things: girls, cars, hanging out with his buddies. He also has
applied to the Air Force Academy and can hardly wait to be a flyboy.
   Only one teensy, tiny hitch: His mommy and daddy are Soviet
spies. It seems they came to the United States in the 1960s as
sleepers _ deep, deep cover agents who carry on a normal life in
their target country until they are called into service by mother
Russia.
   Enter FBI superagent Roy Parmenter (Sidney Poitier). And here's
where the story gets a little dicey: He tells Jeff (River Phoenix)
his parents are agents and enlists the boy's help in keeping tabs on
them and finding what they're up to. To make matters worse, the
parents have been enlisted by a KGB agent trying to stop a killer
Soviet spy. Unfortunately, it all comes across as jibberish. The
plot could work if only it had been better developed by
screenwriters John Hill and Bo Goldman, and better handled by
director Richard Benjamin.
   Poitier and crew do their best to work with improbable situations
and trying lines, and manage to provide some light entertainment and
even a thimble full of suspense.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children
under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
