<DOCNO> AP881114-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 2157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews ADV00   11-14 1098</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, ADV 00,1143</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Review</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``What Up, Dog?'' (Chrysalis) _ Was (Not Was)
   
   Ever wonder what happened to the class clowns in your high
school? In the case of Donald Fagenson and David Weiss, they're now
making records.
   Billing themselves as Donald and David Was, the duo's warped
sense of humor flows through the new album, ``What Up, Dog?''
Fortunately, it's accompanied by some sweet soul music.
   The multi-instrumentalists team with the potent vocal team of
Sweet Pea Atkinson, a gruff bass, and Harry Bowens, a smooth tenor,
to make street-smart music. ``What Up, Dog?'' sounds more consistent
than this group's forgotten 1983 masterpiece, ``Born to Laugh at
Tornadoes,'' but is ultimately less compelling.
   ``Walk the Dinosaur,'' with its ``acka-lacka-boom-boom'' chorus,
is a terrific mindless dance song that, with any luck, should be a
smash.
   Bowers croons the optimistic ``Anything Can Happen,'' with this
irresistible opening couplet: ``She took me in the bedroom to show
me her computer. She asked me if I liked it, I told her she was
cuter.''
   The Was brothers also coax fairly interesting songwriting
contributions from Marshall Crenshaw and Elvis Costello and, on the
compact disc, a vocal performance from Frank Sinatra Jr., of all
people.
   But they include three cuts that are little more than comedy
skits with music backgrounds _ humorous the first time they're
listened to, a drag thereafter. Add them to lackluster tunes such as
``Boy's Gone Crazy'' and ``11 MPH'' _ the latter about John F.
Kennedy's assassination _ and the filler barometer shoots too high.
   Then again, you didn't have to laugh at all your class clown's
jokes to appreciate the effort.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Notes From America'' (Columbia) _ Bonnie Tyler
   
   There's no denying Bonnie Tyler's voice. She could _ should _ be
one of rock's finest female vocalists, with her husky growl that
echoes both Janis Joplin and Tina Turner.
   The presence of such an extraordinary voice makes ``Notes From
America'' worth listening to, but unfortunately the material Tyler
uses and the overblown production on the record make it very, very
ordinary.
   Tyler first hit both pop and country charts 10 years ago with
``It's a Heartache'' and, five years later, had a No. 1 single with
``Total Eclipse of the Heart.''
   Since then, the Welsh-born Tyler has recorded sparingly. On
``Notes From America,'' she teams up with producer-songwriter
Desmond Child, who is known for his work with Bon Jovi and
Aerosmith. The aim is to create big hits. What results is big, and
it might be a hit, but it doesn't do justice to Tyler's abilities.
   The album is overproduced at nearly every turn. ``Don't Turn
Around,'' for instance, is a ballad that starts off as a wonderful
showcase for Tyler's tough yet vulnerable voice. But as it builds to
a crescendo (as many songs on ``Notes From America'' do) and a choir
chimes in, the core of the song is lost in a tidal wave of sound.
   The title track features 50 people corralled on the streets of
Woodstock, N.Y., where the album was made, to sing backup. Why only
50?
   Other tunes stand up better. ``Hide Your Heart'' is a hook-filled
rocker dominated by snarling guitars, while ``Take Another Look at
My Heart'' is a lighter, keyboard-based piece that allows Tyler to
stand out. She even does a version of the Bee Gees' ``To Love
Somebody'' that's better than the original.
   One song stands head and shoulders above the rest. An old Janis
Joplin tune, ``Turtle Blues,'' is a wonderful blues-rocker that
shows the vocal phrasing, range and power of which Tyler is capable.
   ``Notes From America'' sounds like much of the commercial rock
'n' roll on the radio these days. It might make Tyler richer, but
it's a shame such a voice isn't singing more memorable music.
   _ By Curt Anderson, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Land of Dreams'' (Reprise) _ Randy Newman
   
   Randy Newman, the songwriter with humor dark enough to make jokes
about short people, has returned with a rich, complex album that's
easily one of the most pleasant surprises of the year.
   ``Land of Dreams'' is full of sharply drawn characters, cutting
emotion and, of course, humor. Newman, on his ninth album, again
shows he is a deft and perceptive composer.
   Mark Knopfler of Dire Straits and Electric Light Orchestra's Jeff
Lynne produced and played on much of the album, which also features
an appearance by Tom Petty. But things are dominated by Newman's
calliope-like piano and Delta-accented voice.
   Side 1 is purely autobiographical. ``Dixie Flyer'' deals with
Newman's early move to New Orleans, the ``land of dreams.'' In the
ragtime ``New Orleans Wins the War,'' his father returns from World
War II, but not before his mother teaches him some things about life:
   ``She said, `Here comes a white boy-there goes a black one-that
one's an octoroon-this little cookie here's a macaroon-that big
round thing's a red balloon-and the paper down here's called the
Picayune ... '''
   On ``Four Eyes,'' Newman deals with the terrors of his first day
of school: ``You're not gonna leave me here, are you?'' he wails to
his father.
   Three songs deal with love and love lost. ``Falling in Love'' has
a whimsical, catchy hook that captures the happiness of the feeling.
The relationship matures on the evocative ``Something Special,'' but
then is destroyed on ``Bad News From Home,'' a desolate piano piece
about betrayal.
   Side 2 is more light-hearted, starting with ``Roll With the
Punches,'' a satirical look at how some people would solve the
problems of the poor and hungry:
   ``I say we ain't gotta do nothin' for nobody-cause they won't
work a lick you know-they just gonna have to roll with the punches,
yes they will.''
   ``Masterman and Baby J'' is a rap sendup, but with a vein of
sympathy for people trapped in ghettos with nothing but dreams of
stardom to keep their ugly world from ensnaring them.
   The hit song ``It's Money That Matters'' features a rolling
Knopfler lick and a semi-serious lyric about what it takes to make
it in America. And ``I Want You to Hurt Like I Do'' ends the record
on a quiet note of domestic pain.
   ``Land of Dreams'' rings true. While much of it may be drawn from
Newman's own life, in the telling of his stories he tells us about
ourselves.
   _ By Curt Anderson, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
