<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov 25-27 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: A Citizen of the World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sam Neill was born in Northern Ireland, grew
up in New Zealand, first achieved notice in Australian films, and
became well known in American television. A suitable path to
international stardom.
   With his strong features and unaccented English, Neill is a
self-proclaimed citizen of the world, living in London with an
apartment in Sydney and a mountain hideaway in New Zealand. He was
recently here to help launch his new film with Meryl Streep, ``A Cry
in the Dark.'' A quiet-spoken man, he is nevertheless forceful in
his opinions.
   ``A Cry in the Dark'' is based on a real-life cause celebre that
occupied the Australian public for several years. The wife of a
Seventh Day Adventist churchman declared that her nine-week-old
daughter had been snatched from the family's camping tent by a wild
dog known as the dingo. Because of a flimsy set of circumstantial
evidence, the woman was charged with murdering the baby.
   The media exploited the case, stirring up emotions that
apparently continue today despite the fact that the wife, played by
Meryl Streep, was finally cleared of all charges after serving three
years of a life imprisonment for murder.
   ``Anyone who has been to Australia in the last eight years knows
of this case,'' Neill said, ``because of the enormous controversy
the whole thing stirred up. I didn't feel as involved with it as
others who were more familiar with the case, because most of the
time I was living in England.
   ``I was completely flabbergasted by the extent that people were
excited or angered. They were completely involved in the case. Their
opinions are not simply mild; they were extremely black and white.
And they still are, about whether or not these people are guilty or
innocent of this crime.''
   The actor jumped at the chance to rejoin Streep and director Fred
Schepisi, with whom he had worked in ``Plenty.'' But he admitted
that the role of Michael Chamberlain presented the biggest challenge
of his career.
   ``I was scared before we started, terrified,'' he said with a
nervous laugh. ``It was certainly a departure from anything I've
ever done. I was encouraged when I learned that Meryl was just as
frightened as I was.
   ``I had met Michael Chamberlain, and it became apparent that this
was a dual-edged thing. I realized that I couldn't take liberties
with his character or his personality or his story. This meant that
I had to act responsibly. Most acting is a sort of jump of the
imagination. This was not fiction. We're talking about (the
Chamberlains') lives and reputations, and their futures, too. So we
had to do it right.''
   Neill's indeterminate accent is due to his lifelong travels
through the English-speaking world. He was born in Northern Ireland,
where his father was a member of an Irish regiment of the British
army. His father retired when Sam was eight and the family settled
in New Zealand. As an outsider in a colonial environment, he
overcame his shyness by becoming an actor.
   ``I saw a lot of American films, and British films, too,'' he
recalled. ``Films, cars and rock 'n' roll music have been the
primary American export of the past 30 years or so. When I was
growing up we had no television; that came very late to New Zealand.
So we were raised on a diet of films that were made within a four-
or five-mile radius of this very hotel (the Beverly Hills).''
   After college, Neill began making documentary movies, then was
cast by director Roger Donaldson (``The Bounty,'' ``Marie'') in a
modest film called ``Sleeping Dogs.'' That led to ``My Brilliant
Career,'' one of the first films in the Australian movie boom that
has produced such actors as Mel Gibson, Bryan Brown and Paul Hogan,
directors Bruce Beresford, Fred Schepisi, Donaldson and others.
   In explaining the creative surge, Neill commented: ``What we have
in Australia is a very vigorous, young society with young ideas, and
the film industry is part of that. In some ways, it's the cutting
edge of that.''
   In 1980, Neill's life was changed by a telephone call. Out of the
blue the late actor James Mason called him from Switzerland to tell
him: ``You should be working overseas. I'm sending you a plane
ticket to come to London. There's a film I think you should try out
for.''
   The young actor flew from Sydney to London and won the role of
the satanic Damien in ``The Final Conflict,'' last of three ``The
Omen'' movies. That led to his portrayal of the legendary Sidney
Reilly in the acclaimed British TV miniseries, ``Reilly: Ace of
Spies.'' He has also appeared in other miniseries such as ``Kane and
Abel'' and ``Amerika,'' as well as such features as ``Possession,''
``Enigma,'' ``Leap of Faith,'' ``The Good Wife'' and next, ``Dead
Calm.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Nov 25-27</NOTE>
