<NOTE>For release Thursday, Nov. 17, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Nitrogen Storage Can Help Boost Onion Production and Extend Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TIFTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nitrogen atmosphere keeps apples sweet in
storage, and a crop specialist says it could do the same for Vidalia
onions.
   The special storage also could extend the sales season for the
onions from the current six weeks to as long as 32 weeks, said
horticulturist Doyle Smittle at the University of Georgia's Coastal
Plain Experiment Station.
   Growers sell $30 million worth of Vidalia onions from May 1 to
June 15, but about 20 percent of the crop is lost because the onions
can't be stored longer. The pressure to sell forces farmers to
accept lower prices. This year there was an oversupply, and onion
prices dropped below normal.
   Smittle, who has spent five years trying to extend the shelf life
of the world-famous onions, achieved the best results by adapting
the technology used to store apples in Michigan and Washington state.
   Vidalias stored in an atmosphere of 5 percent carbon dioxide, 3
percent oxygen and 92 percent nitrogen kept their sweetness and mild
taste for months, he said. The humidity must be kept high for
apples, but low for onions.
   Smittle compared the quality of 200 pounds of onions in cold
storage and in a controlled atmosphere for 32 weeks last year. The
lack of oxygen in the atmosphere slows the deterioration of the
onions.
   Eighty-nine percent of the cold-storage onions were rated in good
condition a week after removal from a 34-degree room. Sixty-four
percent were good after two weeks, 48 percent after three weeks, and
28 percent after four weeks.
   Onions kept at 34 degrees in the controlled atmosphere were rated
100 percent good after one week, 98 percent after two weeks, 93
percent after three weeks, and 83 percent at the end of four weeks.
   The tests show that onions kept in just cold storage tended to
lose the mild, sweet taste that Vidalias are known for, Smittle
said. ``The onion bites you after you bite it. In Vidalia, quality
is No. 1. If you don't have quality, the Vidalia name won't mean
anything.''
   The current optimum flow of onions is about 250,000 bags a week
during the harvest season, but if they could be stored through
December 18, farmers would need to grow about six times as many, he
said. He believes the special storage ultimately could provide
consumers with Vidalias for up to 11 months a year.
   Based on Smittle's research, W.J. Grimes, a major grower in
Wheeler County, has begun building a controlled-atmosphere warehouse
for 60,000 bags of onions.
   The warehouse, designed by engineers from Georgia Power Co. and
the Little Ocmulgee Electric Membership Corp., will have
computerized controls and sensors to monitor and adjust the
temperature, humidity and gas concentration hourly.
   Grimes said he has tasted Vidalias stored in a controlled
atmosphere for up to seven months. ``The onion still had its flavor.
There's no use in storing it unless it's going to be a Vidalia
onion. I think there's a future in it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1238EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--CoolSuitCrusade Adv17   11-14 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Cool Suit Crusade, Adv 17,0644</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Nov. 17, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Homemaker Helps Kids With Rare Disability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sara Moody proudly shows a videotape of her
10-year-old nephew, Stevie Roper, riding his bicycle and raking
leaves with his father.
   Not so long ago, those routine activities could have killed
Stevie, who suffers from hypohidrotic ectodermal dysplasia, a lack
of sweat glands that can cause the body to overheat.
   But a phone call to NASA in July 1987 has led to a new, active
life for Stevie and hope for hundreds who suffer from the same rare
birth defect. An estimated 400 children in the United States suffer
from HED.
   ``All I did was make a phone call and the rest fell into place,''
said Mrs. Moody, 49, a homemaker and president of the HED Foundation
she formed in March. That call, made after Stevie became overheated
in a car and almost died during a vist to Hampton, was to NASA's
Langley Research Center.
   Mrs. Moody got the idea from watching a TV movie about a young
man who lacked an immune system and lived inside a protective bubble
designed by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   NASA directed her to Life Support Systems Inc. of Mountain View,
Calif., which helped develop a cooling system for space suits and
now makes ``cool suits'' for firefighters, race car drivers and
nuclear plant workers.
   The company designed a child-sized vest and cap that Stevie could
wear as a personal air conditioner. A portable cooling pack powered
by a battery circulates chilled water through tubes to the vest and
cap.
   Knowing that Stevie's parents in Waynesville, N.C., couldn't
afford the suit, Tootsie Moody designed a poster, collected her dill
pickle jars and set them on counters at PoFolks, a restaurant chain
managed locally by a friend.
   The jars and a fund-raising effort by another friend brought in
more than $5,000. But Life Support Systems agreed to sell the suit
at cost for $2,600, so the rest of the money went for Stevie's care.
   After a brief flurry of publicity about the suit, Mrs. Moody went
home and settled down again. Then the telephone started to ring.
   ``You wouldn't believe the people who started calling that had
this problem. Everybody said, `Look, why don't you form a foundation
and go on to help those other children?' I thought, `Well, why
not?'''
   Since she started the foundation, suits have been delivered to
children in Birmingham, Ala.; Knoxville, Tenn.; Tuscon, Ariz.; and
Kuwait.
   ``Here we were already gone national and now then international,
pow!''
   PoFolks restaurants across the country now have jars to collect
money for the HED Foundation, said Carol Koenig, marketing manager
of the Nashville-based company. The campaign would not have started
without Tootsie Moody, she said.
   ``She is tireless. She just keeps going, will not take no for an
answer. But she does it in a way that doesn't offend anyone.''
   Twenty-seven children are waiting for suits to be made and the
money to be raised to pay for them. The foundation has raised more
than $16,000, most of it spent to buy suits, which also have helped
multiple sclerosis and cystic fibrosis patients who need to avoid
overheating.
   Aside from helping the children survive, the suits have brought
together HED victims who told Mrs. Moody they had never known anyone
else with the same condition.
   ``It's made a different person out of Stevie as it has these
other people,'' she said. ``They no longer feel like a freak.
They're out as a normal human being except for no sweat glands. I
think it's done good in a lot of different ways.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Nov. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1239EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary Adv17   11-14 1023</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary, Adv 17,1055</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Nov. 17, and thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: This is the Explorations package for Nov. 17 in summary form.</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Crying' Author Flooded With Letters From Tearful, Tearless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tearful and tearless both cry on
William Frey's shoulder.
   Among those seeking Frey's help since he published ``Crying: The
Mystery of Tears'' three years ago were a woman whose husband
alternated bouts of tears and laughter, and a restaurateur whose
cooks cried chopping onions.
   For the restaurant owner, the answer was easy: Chop under a mist
of water.
   Other times, it's more complicated.
   Frey advised Anne Firebaugh, of Nanoose Bay, British Columbia,
and Alta Sierra, Calif., to take her 71-year-old husband Joseph, to
a neurologist. Mrs. Firebaugh learned there was more to her
husband's problems than runaway emotions. He is suffering from Lou
Gehrig's disease.
   Frey, of the Dry Eye and Tear Research Center at St. Paul-Ramsey
Medical Center, believes tears are the body's way of getting rid of
unwanted chemicals.
   His research showed that the same three biochemicals are present
in both emotional tears and those from irritation:
leucine-enkephalin, an endorphin, and the hormones prolactin and
Adrenocorticotropic hormone, known as ACTH. But he doesn't know in
what amounts and is working on a way to determine that.
   ``If we really understood the biochemistry of stress and emotion,
we might be able to figure out what's going wrong in people who have
emotional disorders,'' Frey said.
   So far though, his research has been confined to the tears of
people who are sad, not the clinically depressed. Emotional tears
are collected in the laboratory by showing poignant scenes from sad
movies. ``Brian's Song,'' ``The Champ'' and ``All Mine To Give''
have proven to be reliable tear-jerkers.
   The flip side of his research could benefit ophthalmology and
sufferers of dry eyes, who number an estimated 2 million to 4
million in the United States, he said. Most sufferers of dry eyes
are postmenopausal women.
   Frey has found women cry on the average of five times a month,
while men generally cry once a month. Other research has shown
little difference in the regularity of emotional crying between boys
and girls under the age of 12.
   ``That's very interesting because, for example, the hormone
prolactin, which I think is probably involved in the sex difference
(in crying) that we see between males and females, is at the same
level in the blood of children,'' Frey said. ``But it's 50 to 60
percent higher in the blood of adult women than in the blood of
adult men.''
</TEXT>
