<HEAD>Anglo-Dutch Giant Posts 12 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unilever, the giant Anglo-Dutch household products
group, said Monday its earnings rose 12 percent in the third quarter
on stronger profit margins in both Europe and North America.
   Unilever said its earnings for the three months ended Sept. 30
came to 222 million pounds, the equivalent of $400 million, compared
with 198 million pounds in the same period a year earlier.
   Earnings per share came to 11.90 pence, compared with 10.63 pence
in the 1987 period.
   Sales rose 7 percent to 4.49 billion pounds from 4.2 billion
pounds.
   ``This was a good quarter,'' both in Europe and North America,
Unilever Chairman Michael Angus said.
   Angus attributed a 15 percent rise in operating profit in Europe
to sales of edible fats and detergents, and a 20 percent rise in
North American operating profit to an excellent performance in
specialty chemicals.
   In the first nine months of the year, Unilever's earnings rose 8
percent to 617 million pounds, or 33.06 pence per share, from 570
million pounds, or 30.58 pence per share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month sales rose 5 percent to 13 billion pounds from 12.4
billion pounds.
</TEXT>
