<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     11-14 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0294</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged upward today, steadying
after last week's slide.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 6.05 to 2,073.08 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers slightly outnumbered losers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 461 up, 424 down and 517
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 19.19 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Stock prices followed the dollar lower in last week's trading, as
investors wondered about the likely course of the U.S. currency in
the administration of President-elect Bush.
   The dollar recovered some of its losses in today's activity,
helping stocks to stabilize.
   Nicholas Brady, secretary of the Treasury, said U.S. policy
remains committed to ``exchange market stability.''
   However, brokers said few market participants were eagerly
bidding for stocks in advance of the government's monthly report,
scheduled to be issued Wednesday, on the nation's trade balance for
September.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Exxon rose [ to 42~;
International Business Machines ] to 117; American Express \ to 26|,
and General Electric ] to 44~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
.31 to 151.55. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .65 at 290.83.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industyrial average fell 47.66 points to
2,067.03, finishing the week with a loss of 78.77 points.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by more than 4 to 1 on the
NYSE, with 292 up, 1,235 down and 414 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 135.50 million shares, up from
128.92 in the previous session.
