<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower today on
the Chicago Board of Trade with the soybean market leading the way
on follow-through selling from last week's price break, analysts
said.
   Soybean prices also were pressured by a combination of bearish
technical and fundamental signals, including beneficial rain over
the weekend in the major soybean-growing region of Brazil.
   Rain in the winter wheat areas of the United States weighed on
soybean prices this morning.
   But corn was down only slightly in early trading with support
stemming from reports that the Soviet Union had told Argentinian
exporters that it intended to buy only U.S. corn to fill its corn
import needs for the remainder of this year.
   ``Corn is actually holding up better than anything else here and
that's probably the reason,'' said Jon Horton, grain market analyst
with Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 6\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.15{ a bushel; corn was 1\
cents to 3 cents lower with December at $2.67 a bushel; oats were 2
cents to 3} cents lower with December at $2.08{ a bushel; soybeans
were 1} cents to 12{ cents lower with November at $7.49 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mostly
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .37 cent lower with December at
72.22 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .30 cent
higher with November at 81.65 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent
lower to .10 cent higher with December at 40.60 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .20 cent to .35 cent higher with February
at 44.60 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly lower on Friday while pork futures
were mixed.
