<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Commodore-Amiga     11-14 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Commodore-Amiga,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commodore Introduces New Computers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST CHESTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commodore International Ltd., the
resurgent maker of microcomputers, on Monday unveiled three new
models aimed at business users, including two additions to its Amiga
line intended to compete with Apple Computer Inc.'s Macintosh.
   The Amiga 2500 and the Amiga 2000HD are the first additions to
the line since two machines, one intended primarily for home use and
another for business, were unveiled in April 1987.
   The Amiga ranks fourth in U.S. sales among computers with 32-bit
microprocessors, behind the Macintosh, International Business
Machines Corp.'s Personal System-2 Model 70, and Compaq Computer
Corp.'s Deskpro 386, according to market researcher IMS America Ltd.
   ``Especially with Apple's introduction of the Mac II and IIX,
they needed to get the new Amigas out because Amiga was the hardware
leader three years ago,'' said Rhett Anderson, associate editor of
Compute Gazette, a magazine targeted at Commodore users and
published in Greensboro, N.C.
   ``Some of their thinking might be if they get these out before
Christmas, they (consumers) might hear the word Amiga and some might
take 500s (last year's low-cost home computer model) home,'' he said.
   The new Amigas offer twice the capacity of the earlier models and
a faster microprocessor.
   The 2000HD comes with software loaded on a hard disk so the
machine is ready to use right out of the box, said spokesman Gary
Fishman.
   The suggested retail price for the 2500 is $4,699 and the 200HD
is priced at $2,699. The suggested prices for the latest Macintosh
machines range from $100 to $3,000 more than the Amiga 2500.
   The company also introduced the PC40-III, which is Commodore's
first IBM AT-compatible machine sold in the United States, Fishman
said. Commodore already sells IBM-compatible computers in Europe.
   Earlier this month, Commodore reported a 52 percent increase in
earnings to $9.6 million for the first fiscal quarter of the year.
The company suffered serious losses in 1985 and 1986 before starting
to turn around last year.
</TEXT>
