<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AutoInventories     11-14 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Auto Inventories,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ward's: Import Inventory Growing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inventories of imported vehicles at the end of
last month stood 2.8 percent above the level at the same time a year
ago, an automotive newsletter said Monday.
   Ward's Automotive Reports said that on Oct. 31, inventories of
imported cars and light trucks stood at 705,853, a 64 days' supply,
compared with 686,261, or a 56 days' supply, at the same time last
year.
   Nissan Motor Corp. in U.S.A., Mitsubishi Motor Sales of America
Inc. and American Isuzu Motor Co. each had more than 100 days'
supply, the journal said.
   Toyota Motor Corp. U.S.A. and American Honda Motor Co. had,
respectively, 17 and 16 days' supplies of cars.
   Overall, inventory of cars made in Japan rose to 58 days on Oct.
31, 1988, compared with 51 days the month before. Inventory of cars
imported from West Germany fell to 81 days at the end of last month
from 91 days on Sept. 30.
   Imported cars from all other countries stood at 62 days at the
end of October, compared with 56 days at the end of September.
</TEXT>
