<HEAD>Control Data Expects Fourth-Quarter Earnings Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp., turning more
pessimistic, said Monday it expects to record a loss in the fourth
quarter that will leave it with approximately break-even results for
the year as a whole.
   The change in outlook is mainly attributable to continued delays
in shipments in the company's computer products division, Control
Data said. This includes start-up production delays for the new
Control Data Cyber 960 mid-range mainframe, which earlier
experienced delays in availability of critical logic chips.
   ``The outlook for the year, particularly in the computer products
division, has changed in the last few days,'' said Robert M. Price,
chairman and chief executive officer, in a written statement. ``...
The bulk of the change is due to timing as opposed to lost
business.''
   Last month, Control Data reported a net loss of $2.4 million on
revenues of $841.4 million for the third quarter ending Sept. 30.
For the first nine months of the year, the company had net earnings
of $14.5 million on revenues of $2.7 billion.
</TEXT>
