<DOCNO> AP881114-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1435EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GrandMet-Pillsbury     11-14 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grand Met-Pillsbury,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury's British Prowler May Be Takeover Target Itself</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Metropolitan PLC, seeking Pillsbury Co. in
a $5.23 billion hostile takeover, said Monday that a group of
investors including Pillsbury may be planning a Pac-Man countermove
on the British conglomerate.
   Walter Montgomery, a spokesman for Grand Metropolitan, confirmed
the accuracy of remarks about the rumored move, which were made by
the company's chief executive officer, Ian A. Martin, in an
interview.
   Martin told the Wall Street Journal he was taking seriously
rumors that a group of other unidentified investors were seeking
buyers for all or parts of Grand Metropolitan, a large London-based
distilling, gambling and franchise concern.
   He also said one of the potential participants might be
Pillsbury, the big Minneapolis-based food and restaurant franchise
targeted for acquisition by Grand Metropolitan last month. At the
same time, Martin expressed some doubt that Pillsbury would
undertake a Pac-Man defense.
   The Pac-Man strategy is so named because it resembles the popular
video game in which a target turns and tries to gobble up its
pursuer.
   Pillsbury spokesman John Thompson said he had no comment on
Martin's remarks.
   Part of the reason Grand Metropolitan might be considered an
attractive takeover target was the difference between its stock
price of about $8 a share and its estimated breakup value of between
$12.50 and $18 a share.
   That degree of discrepancy often invites takeover bids by
investors who hope to profit by selling pieces of a target company.
   ``When there's a gap as big as there is between our share price
and (breakup value) you have to take it seriously just as a
technical matter,'' Martin told the Journal.
   Martin said he saw little logic in a Pillsbury move on his
company, so ``the only conclusion I can come to is that (if the
rumors are true) they're trying to frighten us to abandon our bid,
or something of that kind.''
   Nevertheless, he said, ``we have to take it seriously. We're in a
major bid battle here. We don't know the source of the rumors or how
serious they were.''
   On Oct. 4 Grand Metropolitan undertook one of the biggest hostile
takeover attempts on a company with a $60-a-share tender offer for
Pillsbury, which has been fighting the bid. Last week Pillsbury
announced a restructuring that includes spinning off its Burger King
Corp. subsidiary as an independent company.
   Pillsbury and Grand Metropolitan also have been skirmishing in
court over the validity of Pillsbury's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover
bylaw, which thus far has prevented Grand Metropolitan from
accepting any tendered shares. The bylaw would make an acquisition
prohibitively expensive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
