<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1458EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-RigCount 1stLd-Writethru   11-14 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Rig Count, 1st Ld-Writethru,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rig Count Plunges By 45, Totals 897</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS final two grafs pvs bgng, Among major ... to CORRECT that
Kansas declined, sted gained, by one rig</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of working oil and gas rigs plunged by
45 this week to total 897, marking the largest single-week decline
since February, industry watcher Baker Hughes Inc. reported.
   The sharp drop continues a seesaw trend in the volatile energy
industry, but contradicts a traditional year-end increase, said
Baker Hughes spokesman Ike Kerridge.
   ``The count has been moving up and down, but it's been within a
narrow range for several months,'' Kerridge said. ``We don't have
any explanation for this, except to say that it's probably the
result of of uncertain crude prices.''
   The number of rigs last week increased by 19 to total 942,
following a decline of 10 working rigs in the previous week.
   A year ago the count was 1,174, Baker Hughes said Monday.
   The count is a widely watched industry index of drilling activity
and it reflects the number of rigs actively exploring for oil as of
last Friday, not the number of rigs actively producing oil.
   Houston-based Hughes Tool Co., an oil toolmaker company that
merged with Baker International Corp. of Orange, Calif., has kept
track of the number of working rigs since 1940.
   In December 1981 at the height of the oil boom, the rig count
reached a peak of 4,500. But oil prices plunged to less than $10 per
42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986, prompting a collapse in the
rig count that bottomed out at 663 _ the lowest since Hughes began
compiling figures.
   The lowest level this year was the reported 880 rigs on May 2.
The 897 reported Monday is the lowest count since Aug. 1, when there
were 894 working rigs.
   It also marked the single largest decline since Feb. 1, when the
count dropped by 62 rigs to total 964.
   Among major oil producing states, Texas posted the biggest drop
with 20 fewer rigs, followed by Wyoming, five; Colorado, New Mexico
and Ohio, four each; California and North Dakota, three each; and
Kansas, one.
   States that saw increases include Oklahoma, three; Pennsylvania,
two; and Michigan, one. Louisiana's count was unchanged for the week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881114-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1513EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Reagan-Awards     11-14 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Awards,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Honors Firms for Quality Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Monday recognized the
winners of a new national business award for quality control, saying
their accomplishments helped America become more competitive in
world markets.
   The first annual Malcolm Baldrige National Quality Awards were
presented to Motorola Inc. and Westinghouse Electric Corp.'s
commercial nuclear fuel division in the manufacturing category, and
to Globe Metallurgical Inc. of Beverly, Ohio, in the small company
category.
   The awards were created by Congress last year in honor of
Baldrige, who was killed in a rodeo accident in California in July
1987 while serving as secretary of commerce.
   Supporters hope honoring U.S. companies for their quality-control
efforts will boost the standing of U.S. products on overseas
markets. The Baldrige prize is modeled after the Deming Prize, which
Japan has been awarding since 1951 to recognize quality achievements
by Japanese companies.
   W. Edwards Deming is an American quality control expert revered
in Japan for his work with Japanese companies after World War II.
   ``Today's ceremony reflects both the progress we have made and
the promises that we have yet to keep,'' Reagan said. ``America's
economic strength depends on industry's ability to improve its
productivity and quality.''
   C. William Verity, who succeeded Baldrige as commerce secretary,
said that the awards were a direct answer to critics who ``still
think it is fashionable to question the quality of products that are
marked Made in America. ... Based on the strength of the
applications received this year, I think it is clear that the
winners' accomplishments are just the tip of the iceberg in a
back-to-quality movement in this country.''
   Commerce Department officials said that 66 U.S. companies entered
the competition for the first awards. The legislation allows up to
two awards to be presented in the three categories: manufacturing,
services and small companies with fewer than 500 employees.
   However, the judges decided not to make any awards in services
this year and only one award in the small business category.
   Accepting the awards were Robert W. Galvin, chairman of the board
of Motorola; John C. Marous, chairman and chief executive officer of
Westinghouse, and Arden C. Sims, president of Globe Metallurgical.
   Sims said that Globe, which produces specialty metal alloys at
plants in Beverly, Ohio, and Selma, Ala., ``refused to accept the
gloom spreading over America's smokestack industries. ... We aimed
at becoming the lowest-cost, highest quality producer in the world.
We hit that mark.''
   Motorola's Galvin said that his company, which employs 99,000
workers at 53 plants worldwide, launched a drive to improve the
quality of its electronic products in 1981 and is well on the way to
achieving its 10-year goal of ``zero defects in everything that we
do.''
   Westinghouse employs 2,000 people in its nuclear fuels unit at
plants near Pittsburgh, where the metal tubes are manufactured, and
two facilities near Columbia, S.C., where the uranium fuel pellets
are loaded into the metal rods.
   Westinghouse supplies about 40 percent of the U.S. market for the
nuclear fuel rods used at nuclear plants generating electricity in
the United States and has 20 percent of the world market.
   Marous said his company's nuclear business was part of a
``goldfish bowl industry'' because of public concerns over the
safety of nuclear power. He said he hoped the award would ``reflect
credit on the entire industry, which is so important to the economic
well-being of the nation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
