<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises in Europe, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose in European trading Monday for
the first time since the U.S. presidential election amid signs of
strong official support for the currency.
   Gold prices turned mixed.
   The dollar began its recovery in Tokyo following Bank of Japan
intervention and on bullish comments from Japanese Finance Minister
Kiichi Miyazawa and Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita. Both men
said Japanese authorities were ready to strengthen their
intervention efforts if the need arose.
   The U.S. Federal Reserve intervened later in the European trading
day buying small amounts of dollars for yen, dealers said.
   They said the dollar was given a further boost in Europe
following comments by President-elect George Bush that he will
continue the Reagan administration policy of working to stabilize
currency rates.
   Bush's remarks were echoed by U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady in an interview in Monday's Wall Street Journal.
   But dealers said that despite signs of strong official support
for the dollar, market sentiment remained bearish.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.70 yen to a closing 123.00 yen from Friday's
123.70. Later, in London, it was quoted at 123.40 yen.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.8090 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.8137 late Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday:
1.7452 West German marks, up from 1.7345; 1.4645 Swiss francs, up
from 1.4553; 5.9615 French francs, up from 5.9285; 1.9735 Dutch
guilders, up from 1.9551; 1,303.50 Italian lire, up from 1,296.50;
and 1,2297 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2225.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $420.95 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $419.95.
   In Zurich, gold was lower, closing at a bid $420.00 an ounce,
compared with $420.20 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 32 cents to close at a bid
$422.51 an ounce.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market to a late bid
price of $6.39 a troy ounce, compared with Friday's $6.45 dollars.
</TEXT>
