<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed narrowly mixed
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade after recovering from an early
sell-off on rumors that the Soviet Union had bought up to 2 million
metric tons of U.S. corn.
   The soybean market led the morning decline right from the opening
bell on follow-through selling from last week's losses.
   But the corn market held up well in early trading and ultimately
led the other markets higher. The rumors of Soviet buying followed a
morning news report that the Soviet Union had told Argentinian
exporters it planned to import only U.S. corn for the remainder of
1988.
   ``Around mid-session, we finally bottomed out and started to
recover,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Cargill Inc., a major grain dealer, spurred the price recovery by
buying about 12 million bushels of corn in the afternoon session,
analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was 1} cents lower to 2 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.20} a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 2{ cents higher with December at $2.71} a bushel; oats were
{ cent lower to 1\ cents higher with December at $2.13{ a bushel;
and soybeans were 2} cents lower to 2\ cents higher with November at
$7.60 a bushel.
</TEXT>
