<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-BritishCoal     11-14 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-British Coal,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts Pre-Tax, Six-Month Loss Of 56 Million Pounds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Coal, the state-owned mining company due to
be privatized in the early 1990s, on Monday reported a pre-tax loss
of 56 million pounds, or $101 million, for the first six months of
its fiscal year.
   The loss was narower than its pre-tax loss of 136 million pounds
in the same period a year ago.
   Operating profit, before interest charges and other items, in the
six months ended Sept. 30 spurted 83 percent to 190 million pounds,
or $342 million, from 104 million pounds last year.
   The company said it was its highest operating profit since 1969.
   Total coal production rose to 48.8 million tons from 47.6 million
tons for the same six months a year ago.
   British Coal Chairman Robert Haslam said further pit closures
this year would lead to the loss of 8,000 jobs from the current
total of 114,000. He warned the National Union of Mineworkers that
strike action against the closure plans could mean an additional
12,000 job losses next year.
   Since the 1984-1985 miners' strike over mine closures, British
Coal's workforce has declined to 114,000 from 221,000.
</TEXT>
