<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Tandy-Matsushita     11-14 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tandy-Matsushita,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Matsushita To Sell Tandy-Made PCs Under Panasonic Label</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulling a switch, Tandy Corp. will sell its
American-made personal computers to Japan's Matsushita Electric
Industrial Co. Ltd. for sale under the Panasonic brand name, it was
announced Monday.
   The deal, a marketing success for Tandy, marks the first time a
Japanese company has bought personal computers made in the United
States for sale in the United States.
   Tandy used to sell its computers only through company-owned
stores, but has been moving aggressively to find other outlets for
its broad line of industry-standard machines.
   The Fort Worth, Texas-based company announced last month it would
sell PCs to Digital Equipment Corp. for sale under the Digital
label. In June, it said it would sell PCs through Wal-Mart Stores
Inc.
   ``This agreement is an important step in our announced strategy
to leverage Tandy's computer design and world-class manufacturing
capability by distributing through alternative marketing channels,''
John Patterson, senior vice president of Tandy Computers, said in a
written statement.
   Matsushita, whose brand names include Panasonic, Quasar, Technics
and National, has $4.5 billion in annual sales in the United States,
making it the leading consumer electronics company in U.S. sales.
   Although Matsushita sells personal computers in Japan, they
cannot run the same software as American computers, Panasonic
spokesman James Wickizer said. He said sales of the Tandy-made
machines would begin in the first quarter of 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
