<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 2131EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ComputerShow     11-14 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer Show,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Annual Comdex Show Expected to Draw 100,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comdex, the annual barometer of the economic
health of the computer industry, opened Monday with the promoter of
the event pronouncing the patient in good condition.
   More than 100,000 people are expected to attend this year's show,
which runs through Friday. Demands for exhibit space are up 14
percent over a year ago.
   ``Obviously, the computer industry is alive and well,'' said
Sheldon Adelson, chairman of the Interface Group, the producer of
the five-day event.
   More than 1,700 companies are exhibiting their computer wares at
this year's show, with displays covering 1.75 million square feet in
eight locations.
   The week's activities range from parties introducing new products
to seminars on a host of topics, from industry trends to battling
computer viruses
   Adelson, in an interview Sunday, said he expected this 10th
anniversary show to break all records in terms of attendance,
display space, foreign companies exhibiting their wares and media in
attendance.
   The booming attendance is a good sign for the computer industry,
Adelson said.
   ``Comdex reflects the health of the computer industry,'' Adelson
said. ``How the show goes, so goes the industry, and vice versa. The
turnout at this year's show demonstrates that the industry is alive
and well.''
   Adelson said personal computers (PCs) and laptop computers are
expected to be the big drawing card again this year.
   Comdex Fall in Las Vegas and a companion show in Atlanta in the
spring are used by companies around the globe to introduce new lines
of hardware and software.
   The 1988 show reflects the marked growth of Comdex and the
computer industry from a decade ago, when 4,000 attendees crowded
into a ballroom at a Strip resort to view products from 157
exhibitors.
   Twenty members of the media covered that first show. Some 2,000
are expected for the 1988 version.
   Keynote speakers at Monday's opening event included: Rod Canion,
president of Compaq Computer Corp.; William Gates, co-founder and
chairman of Microsoft Corp.; Philippe Kahn, president of Borland
International; Robert Kavner, president, AT&T Data Systems Group;
and Terry Lautenbach, senior vice president of International
Business Machines Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
