<DOCNO> AP881114-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1830EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-14 0812</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0841</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Plummet On International Discord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices plummeted Monday as reports of discord at
the London meeting of the International Coffee Organization reached
traders on the floor of Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange in New York.
   On other exchanges, copper, gold, silver, oil and pork futures
rose; cattle, grains and soybeans were mixed; and stock-index
futures advanced.
   A week-long meeting of the 74 nation-members of the International
Coffee Organization opened on a sour note with the producer
countries divided on their goals and the United States, the largest
of the consumer members, threatening to withdraw from the ICO unless
it becomes more responsive to the marketplace.
   U.S. representative Allan Wallis, the under-secretary of state
for economic affairs, said U.S. participation in the next
International Coffee Agreeement was ``in jeopardy'' due to the
problems of the two-tier coffee market and the tight availability of
the mild arabica coffee beans favored by American coffee drinkers.
   A two-tier market has been created by the willingness of coffee
producers to sell coffee beans at a discount to countries that are
not ICO members, said Arthur Stevenson, an analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Although the European Economic Community and other Northern
Hemisphere nations belong to the ICO, the United States' absence
from a new agreement ``would likely be seen as a death blow to the
agreement's effectiveness,'' Stevenson said.
   That prospect prompted heavy selling of coffee futures in New
York. Coffee settled .89 cent to 1.52 cents lower with the contract
for delivery in December at $1.2727 a pound.
   The London meeting is the second to be held this year to conduct
preliminary negotiations toward a new coffee agreement. The current
pact expires next Sept. 30.
   Despite his complaints, Wallis expressed confidence that the
negotiations could produce a satisfactory compromise. And Stevenson
noted that bargaining was at an early stage.
   ``We cannot realistically expect the boys in London to wrap up
everything this week,'' he said.
   Copper futures prices advanced slightly on New York's Commodity
Exchange after both the Comex and the London Metal Exchange reported
drawdowns last week in their warehouse stocks of the metal.
   Copper prices declined last week after touching a new record high
of $1.538 for spot delivery. But Fred Demler, metals economist with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York, said the market appeared to
be consolidating before moving higher.
   ``There's a lot of nervousness in the market right now,'' he
said. ``The technicals (chart signals) suggest maybe the correction
isn't over.''
   Copper settled .20 cent lower to 1.80 cents higher with the spot
November contract at $1.43 a pound and December at $1.36 a pound.
   Gold and silver futures advanced on the Comex mainly in response
to a gain in energy prices, Demler said.
   Gold settled $2.10 to $2.30 higher with December at $425.20 a
troy ounce; silver was 2.7 cents to 3 cents higher with December at
$6.445 a troy ounce.
   Fears of tight gasoline supplies supported energy futures prices
on the New York Mercantile Exchange, although trading volume was
light.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents to 32 cents
higher with December at $14.27 a barrel; heating oil was .34 cent to
.62 cent higher with December at 44.63 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .61 cent to 1.51 cents higher with December at 48.16
cents a gallon.
   Cattle futures ended mixed to lower on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange after a late selling flurry erased earlier gains. Analysts
linked the selling to light movement of boxed beef at lower prices
and concern that the live cattle market had also slowed.
   Pork futures gained slightly due to higher cash prices following
light weekend marketings.
   Live cattle settled .33 cent lower to .03 cent higher with
December at 72.30 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent lower
to .25 cent higher with November at 81.60 cents a pound; live hogs
were unchanged to .32 cent higher with December at 40.67 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies were .35 cent to .57 cent higher with
February at 44.77 cents a pound.
   Corn futures advanced on the Chicago Board of Trade on rumors
that the Soviet Union had bought up to 2 million metric tons of U.S.
corn. Wheat and soybeans finished narrowly mixed after recovering
from an early sell-off.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with December at
$4.20} a bushel; corn was 1\ cents to 2{ cents higher with December
at $2.71{ a bushel; oats were { cent lower to 1} cents higher with
December at $2.13} a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents lower to } cent
higher with November at $7.59 a bushel.
   Stock-index futures advanced slightly on the Chicago Merc, where
the contract for December delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
settled .25 point higher at 268.85.
</TEXT>
