<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AlleghenyInternational     11-14 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Allegheny International,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Semiconductor Unit Deal Signed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. said Monday it
signed a definitive agreement to sell its Thermco Systems Inc.
subsidiary, a maker of equipment used in producing semiconductors.
   The terms of the sale were withheld.
   The deal with Silicon Valley Group Inc. is subject to approval by
federal bankruptcy court, where Allegheny International, primarily a
producer of consumer products, has been reorganizing since early
this year. Bankruptcy Judge Joseph Cosetti likely will ask the
opinion of Allegheny International's creditors.
   ``We have no reason to believe they would oppose it,'' said
Anthony Muller, vice president and chief financial officer of SVG of
San Jose, Calif.
   Thermco, based in Orange, Calif., employs about 390 people making
and marketing equipment used to deposit the various layers of
semiconductor wafers. Thermco is slightly larger than SVG, which
recently reported it earned $4.4 million on sales of $49 million for
the year ended Sept. 30.
   SVG, which employs about 450 people, produces equipment used to
prepare the semiconductor wafers before the circuits are etched in
them, Muller said.
   SVG plans no changes in Thermco's operations or employment if the
deal goes through, he said.
</TEXT>
