<DOCNO> AP881114-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 1930EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Interco     11-14 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Interco,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interco Says It Will Continue Appealing Poison Pill Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interco Inc. indicated Monday it would continue
resisting a $2.7 billion hostile takeover bid, and would go ahead
with a planned restructuring if its suitor follows through on its
threat to withdraw the offer.
   The furniture and apparel maker also said it intended to pursue
its appeal of a Delaware court ruling striking down its ``poison
pill'' defense against the $74 a share tender offer.
   Interco closed down $2.12{ a share at $65.87{ in New York Stock
Exchange trading on Monday.
   Interco made its disclosures in a letter to Cardinal Acquisition
Corp., led by Steven and Mitchell Rales of Washington, D.C.
   They came the day after Cardinal released a letter to Interco
extending its hostile offer by two days, to midnight EST Wednesday,
and threatening to withdraw the offer if company did not agree by 5
p.m. EST Wednesday to give it confidential corporate information or
enter into buyout talks.
   Interco fashioned the restructuring as a defensive maneuver to
help it thwart the Raleses, who it has rebuffed since their initial
$64 a share buyout offer in July.
   The $2.8 billion plan includes payment of a special dividend
totaling $30.80 in cash and securities, plus the possible sale of
its Ethan Allan furniture business and other operations.
   The Raleses have insisted on a chance to bid on any assets
Interco might put up for sale. In a letter to Steven Rales released
Monday, Interco Chairman Harvey Saligman indicated that if the
Raleses did decide to withdraw their tender offer they would be
invited to bid on any properties Interco decided to sell.
   Cardinal announced last Wednesday that Interco stockholders had
tendered 29.6 million shares under its offer. Combined with the 3.2
million shares the group already owns, that would give the Raleses
control of 92 percent of Interco's outstanding shares.
   In its letter, the group contended the only barrier to completion
of a buyout was Interco's refusal to withdraw its takeover defense.
   Last week, the Delaware Chancery Court enjoined the use of the
poison pill defense, but Interco has appealed the decision to the
Delaware Supreme Court, which agreed to hear the appeal on Nov. 30.
Interco is incorporated in Delaware.
   ``...while you profess to have confidence in your position on
appeal, your letter boils down to an attempt to pressure us into
abandoning it,'' Saligman's letter read. ``We decline to do so.''
   Interco employs about 54,000 people nationwide and had sales of
$3.34 billion last year. In addition to Ethan Allen, the company
controls such clothing, furniture and shoe brands as London Fog,
Converse and Florsheim.
</TEXT>
