<DOCNO> AP881114-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-14-88 2121EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-API     11-14 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-API,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Industry Wants National Energy Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States could face another energy
crisis if the domestic oil industry fails to gain congressional
support for a national policy, an oilpatch lawmaker told oil company
executives Monday.
   A national oil policy is needed to boost domestic production,
which has plunged in recent months along with crude prices, leaving
the United States dependent on foreign sources for nearly half of
its oil, speakers told the annual meeting of the American Petroleum
Institute.
   ``I think we're drifting toward a serious energy crisis,'' said
Sen. John B. Breaux, D-La.
   Breaux warned that by allowing the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries to flood world markets with oil and, in effect,
to dictate oil policy, ``...I fear there won't be anybody left (in
the United States) to produce.''
   Breaux and other speakers called on industry leaders to urge the
new administration and Congress to support tax incentives to help
neutralize current volatile oil prices.
   Earlier, Amoco Corp. Chairman Richard M. Morrow told reporters at
a news conference that U.S. oil production had fallen by 1 million
barrels a day due to declining oil prices, while demand had
increased by the same amount.
   Morrow, who also is chairman of the API, predicted that if the
current trend continues the United States could be importing
two-thirds of its oil by the year 2000, a situation which has
``serious ramifications'' for the United States. Foreign imports
have soared to about 42 percent.
   But while President-elect George Bush has said he would support
incentives to strengthen U.S. production, U.S. Rep. Richard B.
Cheney, R-Wyo., said winning the support of Congress would not be
easy.
   ``Getting an energy policy is going to be tough. ... I would like
to tell you that things are different but they aren't,'' Cheney said.
   Cheney said consumers as well as many in government are
insensitive to the industry's problems because they ``like cheap gas
and oil.''
   ``Many in Congress are saying...`you guys did well when oil was
$30 a barrel,''' he said.
   Most economists and analysts attending the API meeting said they
were not optimistic that OPEC would reach an accord any time soon on
limiting production to help boost prices.
   The 13-nation cartel meets Nov. 21 in Vienna to discuss possible
ways of boosting prices.
   Morrow also said that he believed more and more U.S. oil
companies would move production overseas in the future, in the
absence of incentives and in an effort to avoid costly environmental
regulations.
   He said Amoco spends 35 to 40 percent of its production budget on
international exploration and will boost that to 50 percent in the
near future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
