<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Robins-Sanofi     11-14 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Robins-Sanofi,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sanofi Asks For $27 Million Fees And Expenses From Robins Merger
Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European pharmaceutical company Sanofi
SA asked a federal judge on Monday to order A.H. Robins Co. to pay
it $27.1 million for fees and expenses from its unsuccessful attempt
to obtain a controlling interest in Robins.
   In the filing in U.S. Bankruptcy Court, Paris-based Sanofi is
seeking a $25 million fee and $2.1 million for its expenses.
   Sanofi's requested breakup fee is the same as U.S. District Judge
Robert R. Merhige Jr. awarded Rorer Group Inc., another unsuccessful
suitor.
   Robins and Rorer had signed a breakup fee agreement that was
approved as part of Robins' Chapter 11 reorganization case, but the
court did not approve a similar proposal involving Sanofi.
   Sanofi said in Monday's filing that it should receive the money
even though it had no court-approved agreement.
   The company claimed there was at least an implied agreement
between it and Robins because their teams of executives, lawyers,
investment bankers, accountants and other advisers worked nearly
around the clock to negotiate agreements and prepare documents by
court deadlines.
   John D. Taylor, a Robins senior vice president, said company
officials could not comment on Sanofi's filing because they had not
seen it.
   The court has approved a plan under which American Home Products
Corp. would acquire Robins, but eight appeals have been filed.
Arguments before a 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals panel are
scheduled for Dec. 6.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
